<H3> <TI>   Implementation of Pre-ISDN in Shanghai </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Implementation of Pre-ISDN in Shanghai </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Detailed Information </H4>

<F P=102> 94P60141B Shanghai DIANXIN KUAIBAO [TELECOMMUNICATIONS 
INFORMATION] in Chinese No 1, Jan 94 pp 2-4 </F>

<F P=103> 94P60141B </F>
<F P=104>  Shanghai DIANXIN KUAIBAO [TELECOMMUNICATIONS 
INFORMATION] </F>

<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Du Jiazhen [2629 0857 3791]: ``Implementation of </F>
Early-Stage ISDN in Shanghai''; MS receipt data not given] 
  [Abstract] The S-1240 switches incorporate foreign 
technology but are made in Shanghai, while the F-150 switches 
are directly imported from Japan. Between its S-1240 switching 
offices, the existing Shanghai telephone network uses 
common-channel Signaling System Number 7 (SS7), while between 
two F-150 switching offices or between an F-150 office and an 
S-1240 office the existing network uses China's MFC [expansion 
not given] Signaling System Number 1. As part of the renovations 
for the pre-ISDN, the F-150 switches had to be converted to SS7, 
while the S-1240 switches' SS7 TUP [telephone user part] had to 
be upgraded with new ISDN-capable circuit boards. Moreover, the 
project was hampered by the difficulty of importing appropriate 
ISDN equipment and software. 
  The key to the entire project is the realization of digital 
user access: the analog subscriber line interface circuit 
(ASLIC) boards in the digital switches had to be replaced by 
digital subscriber line interface circuit (DSLIC) boards to 
permit terminal-to-terminal digital communications. In order to 
avoid replacing the software in the digital switches, the 
digital subscriber circuit signaling protocols had to maintain 
the same techniques as the analog subscriber circuit signaling 
protocols. 
  The basic configuration of this pre-ISDN is shown in Figure 
1 
below. Two types of DSLIC boards have been developed: one for 
S-1240 switches and one for F-150 switches. The ASLIC boards in 
the S-1240 switches have an application-specific integrated 
circuit (ASIC) called the dual processor terminal controller 
(DPTC) [see JPRS-CST-92-010, 22 May 92 pp 53-56], which is the 
interface with the terminal control element. This ASIC is 
retained on the S-1240 DSLIC boards. The U interface device 
(UID) uses 2B1Q encoding to reduce bit rate; when the 
transmitted information rate is 144 kbps (2B + D), the actual 
bit rate is 80 bauds. Each DSLIC board (S-1240 type and F-150 
type) has four UIDs, providing four 2B + D lines. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-CST-006-19A>      Figure 1. Configuration of Pre-ISDN </FIG>

  The digital cross-connect node configuration for this 
pre-ISDN is shown in Figure 2 below. Each node has 15 2W (2W = 
2B + D) lines multiplexed to form one 4W (4W = 30 B + D) [i.e., 
2 Mbps] line, which can be switched to any of seven DS1 circuit 
I/O pots (labeled 4W1-4W7 in the figure) going to other nodes. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-CST-006-19B>      Figure 2. Digital Cross-Connect Node Configuration </FIG>

  There are no tables or references. 


</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-20504 </DOCNO>
<HT>      "jpest010__l94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-EST-94-010-L </AU>
JPRS 
Science &amp; Technology 

</HEADER>

<ABS>  Europe/International German Assessment Report on Materials Research </ABS>


<TEXT>
Program 
<DATE1>   11 April 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100></F>
<H3> <TI>     German Assessment Report on Materials Research Program </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    German Assessment Report on Materials Research Program </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94WS0158A Bonn BMFT REPORT in German Mar 93 pp 1-222 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94WS0158A </F>
<F P=104>  Bonn BMFT REPORT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Report by Dr. Michael Braun, Prof. Dr. Alexander Gerybadze, </F>
Arnold Raetz, Dr. Michael Witzel: "Study on Assessment of 
Materials Research Program"; Subtitle: "Report for Federal 
Research and Technology Minister" prepared by Arthur D. Little 
International, Inc., is an assessment of the BMFT-supported 
advanced materials research program in progress from 1985-1994.] 
  [Text] Structure and Organization of the Study 


    -  This study summarizes the results of our assessment of 
the BMFT's program for materials research and the 
recommendations derived therefrom for the BMFT's future support 
strategy in this sector. 
  -  The analysis is based on talks with nearly 160 experts, the 
examination of additional data, the assessment of secondary 
literature and Arthur D. Little's own know-how. 
  -  The study is broken down into five chapters: 
  --Chapter one summarizes the results and 
conclusions and contains references to the comprehensive 
description in the following chapters. 
  --Chapter two contains the analysis of the program 
that is currently in effect and its impact. 
  --Chapter three provides a comprehensive 
description of materials research and an international 
comparison of support for it. 
  --Chapter four examines the importance of 
materials research for maintaining the competitiveness of German 
industry. 
  --Chapter five develops guidelines for future 
support of materials research in Germany. 
%Each chapter is also preceded by a brief summary of the most 
important results. It also contains references to the in-depth 
information in the text of the chapter. 
%References to the literature that was used and to in-depth 
written materials as well as lists of tables, charts and 
abbreviations are included in the appendix. 

<H5>    1. Summary of the Results </H5>
<H5>  1.1 Objectives and Structure of the Study </H5>
  [Text] With a support budget of DM1.1 billion, the BMFT's 
materials 
research program focusing on the period 1985-1994 constitutes 
the focal point of materials research support on the federal 
level. Its fundamental objective is to safeguard the long-term 
competitiveness of German industry by developing the position of 
materials technology. Defined as other basic top goals of the 
program were: 


    -  Development of materials having new or improved useful 
features 
  -  Mobilization of the scientific and technical potential in 
academic and industrial research for materials engineering 
  -  Enhancement of user oriented basic research in the materials 
research sector and, albeit with reduced weight 
  -  Improved information and technology transfer benefiting small 
and medium-size enterprises [SME]. 

    The materials research program is structured on the basis of 
groups of materials with specific objectives established for 
them in dialog with industry and academic research, 
respectively. In terms of its functional purpose, the program is 
the connecting link between basic research in the academic 
sector and user-friendly research and development financed by 
industry.[.sup]1[/] The economy's self-responsibility for 
ensuring its own competitiveness remains unaffected by this. 
  In order to assess the success and impact of the current 
program and to develop guidelines for the future strategy of the 
BMFT in the materials research sector, the BMFT commissioned 
Arthur D. Little to evaluate the effectiveness and efficiency of 
the current program in this assessment study. On the basis of 
this knowledge and a comparison with an analysis of potential, 
wherein an international comparison of materials research and 
support for it are analyzed, as is the importance of materials 
and processing technologies for German industry, action-oriented 
recommendations are derived for a future support requirement, 
for topical foci, program organization and support principles 
for future support. 
  Also, in the context of an analysis of 
effectiveness, in chapter two, the effectiveness and 
efficiency of the support activities of the current program are 
examined. The effectiveness of the program depends on whether 
the objectives and programmatic foci of the program, the 
indicated target groups and the application and use of resources 
were measured and whether the goals that were set were also 
realized. The main issue in analyzing efficiency is whether the 
targeted results are realized with an optimum cost/benefit 
ratio. This constitutes the answer to the question of the 
effectiveness of the support instruments that are employed, the 
success factors of the principal instrument of combined 
research, the efficiency of the completed project and the 
effectiveness of the program management. 
  The analysis of potential analyzes the technical and market 
development potential of high-performance materials and their 
use (chapter three) as well as an international comparison of 
materials research and support for it (chapter four). These are 
important criteria for assessing the need for action in 
materials research from a higher viewpoint and of future 
potential that can be developed through appropriate BMFT 
activities. In particular, in terms of the higher goal of 
maintaining and enhancing the competitiveness of German 
industry, the future attractiveness of new high-performance 
materials for their manufacturers and consumers as well as the 
activities of other leading nations are important criteria for 
shaping the BMFT's strategy in this field. 
  Using the results of this analysis, chapter five develops 
guidelines for future support of materials research in 
Germany. Chapter 5.2 starts out by examining the need for 
future support for materials science as well as the basic 
requirements for a successful support policy, against the 
backdrop of the general conditions described in chapter 5.1. On 
the basis of this, chapter 5.3 derives topical foci for future 
materials research support, on which to develop the subsequent 
recommendations for operational implementation (chapter 5.4) and 
for supplementary strategies for other institutions (chapter 
5.5). 
  Briefly summarized below are the most important results and 
conclusions of this stage of the analysis. These are described 
in detail in the respective chapters. 
<H5>  1.2 Results and assessment of the current BMFT </H5>
materials research program 
  Chapter two contains the fundamental insights into the 
current program from the assessment of all available data and 
from more than 160 interviews with participants and other 
experts. Following a brief description of the methodology of the 
assessment in chapter 2.1, chapter 2.2 describes in detail 
objectives, instruments and the application of resources. 
Assessment of the program in chapter 2.3 and evaluation of 
project experiences in chapter 2.4 facilitate valuable 
conclusions on goal attainment, the effectiveness of the 
instruments used and conclusions for future actions. The results 
of this analysis can be summarized in the following points: 
  The assessment of all available data and from more than 160 
interviews with participants in the program and other experts 
yielded the following fundamental insights into the current 
program: 
  (1) From 1985 to the start of 1992, 557 independent projects 
(with a total of 1,111 individual applications) having a total 
volume of DM1,652 million were initiated under the BMFT's 
materials research program. The support outlay for those 
projects amounts to DM894 million (SYMBOL 64 \f "Symbol" 54 
percent), DM639 million of which (SYMBOL 64 \f "Symbol" 71 
percent) is allocated to industrial research and DM250 million 
(SYMBOL 64 \f "Symbol" 28 percent) to academic research. On an 
initial approximation, the support outlay is distributed evenly 
among the polymer, metal and ceramic groups of materials. The 
support instrument for combined research, having DM737 million 
in support outlay (SYMBOL 64 \f "Symbol" 83 percent) was 
intensively utilized. 
  (2) The general objectives of the program and those specific 
to materials were essentially properly chosen at the start of 
the program in 1985 and, in the course of the program, where 
clear needs were visible, they were adjusted to the changing 
directions of development. 
  (3)The materials research program has basically contributed 
to the development of effective R&amp;D structures and the 
start-up 
of pioneering development. It was possible to keep abreast of 
high-performance materials in the leading countries of the U.S. 
and Japan. 
  (4) With two exceptions[.sup]2[/], the specific goals set 
for the program were attained well enough. Important scientific 
and technical prerequisites for maintaining and developing the 
long-term competitiveness of Germany's industry were elaborated; 
use of such prerequisites and their conversion into directly 
quantifiable economic results, however, is still pending in many 
cases. 
  (5) The general conditions of the program, such as financial 
arrangement, timeframe for the program, project lifetimes, and 
oversight by the BMFT and project sponsor PLR [expansion not 
given], were favorably assessed and befit the particular 
(strategic) significance of the topic. 
  (6) Still, in the course of the assessment, definite 
openings 
for improvements surfaced, most prominent of which are: the 
strategic focus of a support design, its specific foci, and 
issues of organizational development and implementation. 
  By and large, therefore, the materials research program was 
in a position to meet the desired expectations, in terms of 
science and technology and even on an international comparison. 
As a result, the support principles of direct support and 
combined research, in particular, proved out. Recommendations of 
value for future programs appear to be: a more intense focusing 
of support funds on focal issues; prioritizing of vertical 
project structures and more intensive orientation of the system 
development project. To improve efficiency, the BMFT should 
establish the toolkits of modern portfolio management on 
strategic levels and of project management on project 
sponsor/project levels. 
<H5>  1.3 International Comparison of Materials Research and </H5>
Support For It 
  Chapter three compares materials research and support for it 
in Germany with other leading countries. Chapter 3.1 first 
compares the research foci of German industry with the 
activities of American and Japanese firms. Chapter 3.2 describes 
the support activities of Japan, the U.S. and the EC, while 
chapter 3.3 paints a detailed panorama of materials research in 
German universities and institutes. 
  The upshot is that, in all highly industrialized nations, 
the 
internationally acknowledged major significance of materials 
research as a key and trailblazing technology, leads to 
considerable R&amp;D efforts and corresponding support 
activities. 
The international comparative analysis of materials research and 
support for it, therefore, can be summarized in the following 
results: 
  (1) The most important impetus for materials engineering 
comes from the large, multinational companies in the troika of 
countries. Two-thirds of the companies with the strongest 
turnover worldwide view materials research as a focus of their 
R&amp;D investments. They leave a lasting imprint on the 
international development and use of new materials. 
  (2) Any "benchmarking" for assessing the developmental 
prospects of materials technology in Germany has to focus on the 
chief rivals in Japan and the U.S. In coming years, Japanese 
companies will definitely continue to increase their R&amp;D 
efforts. In this context, they emphasize actions to augment 
efficiency and strategies for national and international 
cooperation. Japanese firms accept as partners only companies 
and institutes that have a very strong technological position 
themselves. 
  (3) Materials research will operate on a continuing high 
level in American industry in coming years. It outstrips 
Germany's R&amp;D efforts by several orders of magnitude. 
Concurrently, an enduring reorientation is observable in the 
U.S., that is definitely focused on improving international 
competitiveness through new materials. Cost and use aspects, in 
particular, are underscored through heavy emphasis on materials 
processing and systematizing. 
  (4) In the two leading countries, the concept of a system, 
that is, the development of a strong national materials research 
in the context of dynamic user industries on the national level, 
receives heavy emphasis. In Germany, by comparison, the 
innovation process remains too heavily centered on the producer 
and is too heavily oriented toward basic research. So far, only 
in a few sectors, even on an international scale, are there 
successful systems allying materials manufacturers and 
growth-oriented, innovative consumers. 
  (5) In Germany, therefore, development is adversely 
impacted, 
above all, by the inadequate presence of dynamic user groups. 
Only dynamic consumers are able to generate the critical mass 
effect for materials development as well as contribute to the 
establishment of competitive structures in the development and 
production sectors. So far, in Germany, even dissemination to 
secondary applications with high growth and net product 
potential has continued to be neglected. Intensive net product 
systems applications, follow-on developments in low-cost sectors 
and the pre- and post-situational development of the processing 
and service stages still continues to receive too little 
attention. 
  (6) Support plays a front-and-center role in a functional 
national system of producers, consumers and research institutes. 
All industrial countries support materials research to a very 
great extent and, accordingly, they prioritize quite similar 
development sectors. It is crucial to pursue a targeted, 
national strategy of differentiation. Successful differentiation 
is primarily realized by aligning national programs as 
effectively as possible with R&amp;D strategies and innovative 
activities of the most important actors from industry and 
research. Japan's support strategy is a model in this respect. 
Even in the U.S. there is an increasingly greater effort, 
through national consensus building, to develop the existing 
strengths of materials engineering. 
  (7) Adversely impacting materials research support in 
western 
Europe with generally high R&amp;D expenditures is national 
fragmentation and parallel development of national innovative 
systems. In many cases existing strengths are still marked by 
"national islands of competence." Since the early seventies, any 
number of European programs and initiatives have been introduced 
to link them together. They continue to be of great 
significance, but they cannot take the place of the development 
of national programs that have to focus on shoring up national 
strengths vis-a-vis the main competitors from Japan and the U.S. 
  (8) The development of basic research has to be integrated 
more intensely than hitherto in this parallelogram of 
international competitive forces. In Europe, Germany enjoys a 
very good reputation for basic research and materials oriented 
training and professionalization. These have to stand out even 
more strongly, however, in a global context in terms of 
long-term industrial convertibility. More intensive "fitness for 
use" criteria have to be adduced as the quality standard for 
research and development. Effective transfer between basic 
research and industrial application occurs in too few sectors of 
German materials research. This requires efforts by all 
participants and new forms of cooperation as well as new forms 
of research support, organization and financing. 
<H5>  1.4 Importance of materials and processing </H5>
technologies for German industry 
  On the basis of a comparison of international important key 
technologies (chapter 4.1) and the present status and 
development trend in the sector of materials and processing 
technologies, chapter four demonstrates their significance for 
German industry. Chapter 4.3 summarizes the impact of competence 
in materials technologies on maintaining competitiveness. 
  This analysis clearly shows that the future prosperity of a 
country decisively depends on safeguarding and enhancing the 
competitiveness of its companies on the world markets. If 
companies as well as the government are to be able to safeguard 
this competitiveness in an arena marked by a high dynamic for 
change on the political, social, economic and technological 
levels, they have to adapt to such changes and actively help 
shape them. 
  A highly industrialized country like the FRG, with a weak 
raw 
materials basis, but with a good supply of fixed capital, an 
established basis of know-how, and a high level of education, 
should use its existing relative strengths in know-how 
intensive, future-oriented sectors of technology to concentrate 
on areas where such strengths can be most effectively used. But, 
as chapter four describes in detail, the leading industrial 
nations have the same marginal conditions as the FRG and 
therefore consider similar sectors of technology future-oriented 
and endeavor to develop them. So it is all the more necessary 
for the FRG to concentrate existing resources effectively and 
efficiently on technology sectors that Germany views as 
future-oriented and develop them as rapidly as possibly. 
  Because of their central importance for the future 
development of many sectors, materials and processing 
technologies are viewed internationally as particularly 
future-oriented technology sectors. It is imperative to 
safeguard and develop the position achieved in this 
broad-spectrum sector of technology to exploit the potential for 
differentiation in internationally important and attractive 
sectors and thereby permanently enhance the competitiveness of 
German industry. 
  This results in the following hypotheses: 
  (1) In all leading industrial countries, research and 
development in the field of high performance materials and the 
associated production and processing technologies enjoy very 
high significance since they 
  -- have high development and application potential 
  -- are, in many cases, the prerequisite for new or 
definitely 
improved technical designs, even allowing for ecological issues, 
and therefore 
  -- afford firms in practically all sectors of industry an 
opportunity to realize strategic competitive advantages. 
  (2) Technological developments in such important industrial 
sectors as automobile manufacturing, electronics/electrical 
engineering, energy engineering, machine and appliance building 
or chemistry are often based on high performance materials. 
Maintaining and developing the FRG's current, often favorable, 
competitive position in such industrial sectors and the 
associated export results (percentage of international exports: 
automobile manufacturing, 22 percent; electrical engineering, 18 
percent; energy engineering, 16 percent; electronics, nearly 10 
percent), can be safeguarded through the solid basis of know-how 
in this future-oriented technology sectors. 
  (3) In order to realize the potential of high performance 
materials, in the future, in the materials and processing 
technologies sector, above all, it will be necessary to overcome 
the gap still existing between materials development and further 
processing or the manufacture of components, so as to ensure the 
transfer of know-how from research and development to innovative 
products and systems. 
<H5>  1.5 Guidelines For Future Materials Research Support </H5>
in Germany 
  Building on the preliminary strategic remarks in chapter 
5.1, 
chapter 5.2 develops the most important principles for a future 
support design. Chapter 5.3 proposes topical foci for it and 
chapter 5.4, the necessary program organization and support 
principles for successful implementation. 
  These recommendations may be summarized as follows: 
  Because of their strategic significance, their 
broad-spectrum 
nature and their potential, high performance materials and the 
associated manufacturing and processing technologies are among 
the most important key technologies supported by government. 
Even for nearly all the FRG's industrial manufacturing sectors, 
they are important factors in maintaining and developing future 
competitiveness, whether as the basis for establishing new 
technical designs or for improving existing technologies and 
systems. 
  Countering the great potential of high performance 
materials, 
their great significance for the competitiveness of individual 
companies, as well as the entire economy, are the frequently 
long times for dissemination into the respective markets, 
uncertainties surrounding the realization of radical new 
technical designs and the associated corporate risks. For this 
reason, as well as consideration of intensive government support 
activities in all important industrial countries, it both makes 
sense and is necessary to have a further government support 
initiative in pre-competitive sectors. 
  As an industrial policy activity, future support of 
materials 
research in Germany should include the following fundamental 
strategic goals: 
  -- safeguarding Germany's technological competence as a 
critical factor for success in international competitiveness 
  -- acquiring leading technology positions in selective 
fields 
of application for high performance materials that are 
strategically important for German industry 
  -- accelerating the dissemination of high performance 
materials and the components and systems produced from them into 
the appropriate market segments as well as assisting German 
industry to maintain and develop its international 
competitiveness 
  -- taking long term ecological factors into consideration 
chapter (5.1). 
  Any future support initiative should tie in with the results 
that have been realized so far under the materials support 
program and with a view towards a more intensive strategic 
orientation with precisely defined strategic goals, as well as 
reorientation of the topical foci and organization of program 
development and implementation, it should also encompass: 
  (1) focusing the program on application foci matching the 
chosen technology strategy (chapter 5.2) 
  (2) reorienting topical foci on materials as integral 
components of systems solutions and taking net product stages 
into consideration (chapter 5.3) 
  (3) prioritizing proven support instruments, especially 
direct support of specific combined projects in contrast to 
non-specific or indirect support activities that have turned out 
to be less efficient (chapter 5.2) 
  (4) substantive systematic and/or institutionalized 
alignment 
with other support activities (chapter 5.4) 
  (5) Adapting program organization to new requirements by 
establishing program management and program administration under 
the purview of the BMFT (chapter 5.3) 
  (6) establishing modern methods of R&amp;D control and 
project 
management for program management and administration (chapter 
5.3). 
<H5>  2. Assessment of the BMFT's Materials Research Program </H5>
  On the federal level, the BMFT's materials research program 
constitutes the programmatic focus for supporting materials 
sciences. The basic goal of the program is to strengthen the 
position of German industry in key technological sectors. The 
result should be a decisive contribution towards ensuring the 
long-term competitiveness of various industrial sectors. For the 
period from 1985 to 1992, the basic results of the assessment 
that was made, that is, analysis and assessment of the materials 
research program, are: 
  (1) From 1985 to the start of 1992, 557 independent projects 
(with a total of 1,111 individual applications) having a total 
volume of DM1,652 million were initiated under the BMFT's 
materials research program. The support outlay for those 
projects amounts to DM894 million (SYMBOL 64 \f "Symbol" 54 
percent), DM639 million of which (SYMBOL 64 \f "Symbol" 71 
percent) is allocated to industrial research and DM250 million 
(SYMBOL 64 \f "Symbol" 28 percent) to academic research. On an 
initial approximation, the support outlay is distributed evenly 
among the polymer, metal and ceramic groups of materials. The 
support instrument for combined research, having DM737 million 
in support outlay (SYMBOL 64 \f "Symbol" 83 percent) was 
intensively utilized (chapter 2.2.3). 
  (2) The general objectives of the program and those specific 
to materials were essentially properly chosen at the start of 
the program in 1985 and, in the course of the program, where 
clear needs were visible, they were adapted to the changing 
directions of development (chapter 2.2.1). 
  (3)The materials research program has basically contributed 
to the development of effective R&amp;D structures and the 
start-up 
of pioneering development. It was possible to keep abreast of 
high-performance materials in the leading countries of the U.S. 
and Japan (chapter 2.3). 
  (4) With some exceptions, the specific goals set for the 
program were attained well enough. Important scientific and 
technical prerequisites for maintaining and developing the 
long-term competitiveness of Germany's industry were elaborated; 
use of such prerequisites and their conversion into directly 
quantifiable economic results, however, is still pending in many 
cases (chapter 2.3). 
  (5) The general conditions of the program, such as financial 
arrangement, timeframe for the program, project lifetimes, and 
oversight by the BMFT and project sponsor PLR [expansion not 
given], were favorably assessed and befit the particular 
(strategic) significance of the topic (chapter 2.3). 
  (6) Still, in the course of the assessment, definite 
openings 
for improvements surfaced, most prominent of which are: the 
strategic focus of a support design, its specific foci, and 
issues of organizational development and implementation (chapter 
2.3; 2.4). 
  By and large, therefore, the materials research program was 
in a position to meet the desired expectations, in terms of 
science and technology and even on an international comparison. 
As a result, the support principles of direct support and 
combined research, in particular, proved out. Recommendations of 
value for future programs appear to be: a more intense focusing 
of support funds on focal issues; prioritizing of vertical 
project structures and more intensive orientation of the system 
development project (chapter 2.3). To improve efficiency, the 
BMFT should establish the toolkits of modern portfolio 
management on strategic levels and of project management on 
project sponsor/project levels (chapter 2.4). 
<H5>  2.1 Methodology of the assessment </H5>
  To assess the effectiveness of the BMFT's materials research 
program, the issues of effectiveness and efficiency have to be 
addressed, that is, it must be clarified whether the proper 
goals were selected and the proper projects pursued and whether 
program and projects were implemented in the most cost-effective 
and efficient manner possible. 
  To be sure, in addressing such issues, the problem of 
R&amp;D 
output quantification surfaces. The problem is not so much on 
the project level, where ideal world/real world comparisons can 
be grasped well enough on the basis of published materials like 
project applications and progress reports. It is rather on the 
project groups level and the program level that it exists. The 
impact of the results realized under the program on the 
competitiveness of German industry and individual industrial 
sectors, is not open to direct quantification because of the 
long dissemination times. So far there is no proven and 
acknowledged method for this. 
  For this reason, in addition to direct methods on the 
project 
level: 
  -- output analysis of individual projects through ideal 
world/real world comparisons 
  -- case studies. 
  Recourse has to be had to a number of indirect methods: 
  -- patent analyses 
  -- analyses of the trade balances for technologically 
intensive merchandise 
  -- analysis of scientific indicators (e.g., analyses of 
quotability, bibliometric analyses) 
  -- document analysis 
  -- analysis of specialized literature 
  -- assessment of secondary literature and material 
  -- written and oral survey 
  -- interviews with experts. 
  In this connection, the interviews with experts, 
supplemented 
by a written questionnaire, constitute a principal focus. Arthur 
D. Little conducted nearly 160 technical discussions and 
interviews with experts from the materials and processing 
technologies sector around the world for this study. Nearly 100 
of them were in Germany, 40 in Japan, and 20 in the U.S. In 
selecting interviewees care was taken to include representatives 
from academic and industrial research, participants and 
non-participants in the materials research program and 
representatives from all stages of the net product chain. 
  The personal interviews were supplemented by a questionnaire 
distributed to more than 100 materials experts from academic and 
industrial research. The return rate totaled 80 percent. And 
they were statistically evaluated. The questionnaire mostly 
contained questions pertaining to materials research and the 
industrial arena. 
  Lastly, an experts seminar was held for each of the 
ceramics, 
polymers and metals groups of materials. The discussion during 
them centered principally on development trends and strategies 
specific to materials. 
  The assessment of the international comparison of materials 
research and support mostly involved: 
  -- analyses of selected materials research projects in the 
FRG, EC, and Japan 
  -- assessment of the BMFT's APC [expansion not given] Davor 
database 
  -- assessment of studies and projects analyses for other 
comparable BMFT programs. 
<H5>  2.2 Description of the materials research program </H5>
<H5>  2.2.1 Objectives </H5>
  The design and contents of the materials research program 
are 
derived from the former federal administration's broad research 
and technology policy guidelines prevailing in the early 
eighties. Those guidelines were aimed at ensuring a broadly 
focused basic research while simultaneously supporting 
cutting-edge technology, improving the general conditions for 
research and development within industry and focused support for 
research in selective key and broad-spectrum sectors of 
technological development for safeguarding the long-term 
competitiveness of German industry. Materials engineering was 
recognized as such a technology having a broad-spectrum aspect. 
As a result, with the materials research program, targeted 
support activities were provided for its further development. 
  With the program came the pursuit of broad objectives as 
well 
as specific partial goals under the individual groups of 
materials. The broad goals of the program can be summarized as 
follows: 


    -  improvement of German industry's competitiveness 
  -  development of new materials with new and/or improved useful 
features 
  -  mobilization of the scientific and technical potential 
in academic and industrial research for materials engineering 
  -  enhancement of user oriented basic research in the materials 
research sector and, albeit with reduced weight 
  -  improved information and technology transfer benefiting small 
and medium-size enterprises [SME]. 

    The underlying assumption is that it is the proper 
responsibility of an industrial concern to safeguard 
competitiveness. The federal government's technology policy 
activities therefore are in line with the subsidiary principle, 
that is, official support for research is applied where private 
sector research and development need assistance for broad 
economic or social considerations. Thus, for example, the 
enhancement and mobilization of highly qualified research groups 
in the various institutions for basic and applied research is an 
appropriate resource. 
  In this context, preference should be given to basic 
research 
projects with an applied orientation having clearly defined and 
limited foci, that can also be transformed into products and 
applications over the medium-to-long term. Furthermore, the 
establishment of combined projects for the transfer of know-how, 
especially benefiting SMEs, should be guaranteed. 
  Under the materials research program, materials having 
especially high potential for innovation whose further 
development is supported as a focal point, are clustered into 
groups of materials. Within the individual groups of materials, 
specific partial goals for each are pursued, as summarized 
below. Concurrently, a brief outline is provided for the 
respective groups of materials, their fundamental properties and 
basic areas of application. 
<H5>  Objectives For Ceramic Materials </H5>
  Ceramic materials display a number of features that make 
them 
attractive for many uses. Among other things, they are marked by 
high temperature resistance, low specific weight, and good 
resistance to corrosion and wear and tear. Because of these 
properties or an optimum combination of them, high-performance 
ceramic components are used in many applications in engine 
manufacturing, energy engineering, machine and equipment 
building and the chemical and metallurgical industries. 
Functional ceramics, for example, reputed for their insulating 
properties and especially good heat conductivity, are a 
permanent component of many electrical engineering and 
electronic products. 
  Enhanced dissemination of structural ceramic materials to 
relevant, potential fields of application, however, was 
confronted with a number of drawbacks inherent to ceramics, at 
the outset of the program. These included, for instance, the 
brittleness of ceramic components, the associated low resistance 
to changes in temperature, and sensitivity to blows and shocks. 
The considerable hardness of ceramic materials plus the absence 
of joining and bonding technologies also made it difficult to 
process components. Lastly, insufficiently developed methods of 
characterizing materials impeded the development of 
non-destructive processes for materials testing and quality 
assurance. 
  The following program goals specific to ceramics were 
derived 
from the considerable potential for ceramic components and the 
indicated impediments to broader industrial use. 


    -  development of technically reliable ceramics and 
components having high potential forindustrial applications 
  -  improvement of the disadvantageous features of ceramics 
  -  development and improvement of technologies for powder 
production, compression, molding and strengthening 
  -  elucidation of the fatigue and failure mechanisms of 
high-performance ceramics 
  -  further development of the processing steps to prepare for 
the 
serial production of large volume and complex, molded 
components. 

    Over the course of the program, moreover, the exploitation 
of 
the development potential of functional ceramics was explicitly 
incorporated into the objective for the ceramic group of 
materials. 
<H5>  Objectives For Polymer Materials </H5>
  Because of their various, specifically adaptable properties, 
it is impossible to imagine most areas of engineering and 
everyday life without polymer materials. Increasingly, the 
consistent further development of polymer chemistry will tackle 
new and more promising formulations for both structural polymers 
and for functional polymers. The outstanding features of polymer 
materials in this context are their low specific weight, their 
toughness and high strength when reinforced. These are 
supplemented by excellent electrical properties, good resistance 
to chemicals and easy ductility. 
  Especially attractive are the different variations of such 
features based on chemical and structural alternatives. The 
alternative applications resulting from the profile of the 
features are as diversified as is polymer chemistry itself and 
include specialized and high performance materials, above all, 
in the road vehicle manufacturing and electrical engineering and 
electronic industries. 
  At the outset of the program, the prime objectives in 
developing the exceptional potential of polymer materials for 
innovation, were: 


    -  development of polymer materials having extreme 
stability under load 
  -  development and improvement of systems of polymer alloys 
  -  development and improvement of methods for modifying and 
characterizing polymer surfaces 
  -  development of polymers with special electrical, magnetic and 
optical properties 
  -  development of polymers as input-output devices 

<H5>    Objectives For Metallic Materials </H5>
  There are two foci for the support of metallic materials 
under the materials research program: powder metallurgy and 
high-temperature and special purpose metallic materials. 
  Powder metallurgy, a process for producing semi-finished 
products and components from pulverized metals, agglomerations 
of metals and alloys, affords a number of advantages compared 
with molten metallurgy. Metals that can be produced only with 
difficulty using traditional molten metallurgy can be produced 
more easily and with defined texture and/or defined porosity and 
permeability using the powder metallurgy process. With this 
process, complex molded semi-finished products or components 
approximate their final contours and are therefore more 
economical to produce. 
  These advantages result in a potential for using components 
manufactured using powder metallurgy in various important 
industrial sectors. For example, friction bearings and preformed 
parts of iron, bronze, or aluminum alloy materials are used in 
the automobile industry and in the manufacture of equipment and 
machinery. Preformed parts of highly heat resistant nickel and 
cobalt alloys are critical components for the manufacture of 
turbines; the aircraft industry uses weight-saving trans-alloy 
sintered products. 
  A number of drawbacks, however, have to be surmounted to 
further develop the existing potential in other industrial 
sectors as well. These led to the formulation of the following 
development goals for powder metallurgy in the materials 
research program: 


    -  development of a process for producing metal powders 
with controllable distribution of particle sizes 
  -  development of a process for producing metal powders having 
reproducible high chemical purity 
  -  development of a powder processing procedure to adapt to 
locally defined component features 
  -  development of a powder processing procedure to manufacture 
large, complex molded components and semi-finished 
products. 

    High-temperature and special purpose metallic materials 
display special properties like solidity, firmness and 
resistance to corrosion even at high temperatures. These 
materials are key components in many sectors of industry but 
especially and always, wherever increased efficiency and, 
ultimately, therefore, energy savings are pursued. Naturally, it 
is primarily the manufacture of equipment, turbines, and 
generating plants that is interested in this materials and that 
uses them in the form of austenitic steels and super-alloys that 
can be used at temperatures up to nearly 1,200 degrees C. 
Light-weight metallic materials like aluminum or titanium alloys 
are also used in the manufacture of drive gears and aircraft. 
  To develop the existing potential in the indicated 
industries 
as well as in new areas of application, the materials research 
program formulated the following development goals for 
high-temperature and special-purpose metallic materials: 


    -  development of new (inter-) metallic phases for 
applications at temperatures ranging between 900-1,500 degrees C. 
  -  improvement of known systems of metallic materials, primarily 
by shifting the useful temperatures for such materials to higher 
temperature ranges. 

<H5>    Objectives For Composite Materials </H5>
  Unlike the materials described up to this point, composite 
materials are fashioned from more than a single material. Their 
distinguishing features are a highly specific rigidity and 
strength, that can be aligned either isotropically or in any one 
of a number of pre-established directions. Targeted combining of 
individual composite components enable fiber, surface or 
particle composites to be produced, whose characteristic feature 
is clearly superior to the properties of the individual 
components. 
  Reinforced materials, above all, fiber-reinforced 
synthetics, 
are presently used in a numerous variety of fields of 
application. The aerospace industry, for instance, uses 
carbon-fiber reinforced synthetics for primary structural 
components and special applications. In the automobile industry, 
(short) fiberglass reinforced bodywork components are used. And 
in machine and equipment building, fiberglass and carbon-fiber 
reinforced rollers, bins and pressure reservoirs are being 
manufactured. The sporting goods industry makes use of composite 
materials for the wide variety of sports equipment. 
  So far, broad scale use of composite materials has lagged 
behind the various technical possibilities. Here too, a large 
number of obstacles have to be overcome through development 
activity, in order to be able to continue to develop the 
potential of this group of materials. Foremost among the 
development goals under the materials research program for 
composite materials are the following: 


    -  development of cost-effective production processes for 
the basic materials 
  -  development of cost-effective processing procedures for 
producing semi-finished products and components from composite 
materials 
  -  development of reliable detection of defects and quality 
assurance for semi-finished products and components 
  -  improvement of the interface threshold for individual 
composite 
materials 

    Initially, topics from the field of tribology were 
addressed--ultimately as derivatives of former support 
initiatives--but they disappeared in the first year of the 
materials research program. 
<H5>  2.2.2 Support instruments </H5>
  The supreme principle of the BMFT's technology policy is the 
subsidiary principle whereby the economy is fundamentally 
responsible on its own for determining the nature and the scope 
of its research and development activities. Therefore, the 
responsibilities of government research and technology policy 
are focused on safeguarding broad, basic research of 
qualitatively high value, cultivating precautionary research and 
supporting technological options of a strategic nature. 
  It is up to industry to carry out R&amp;D with an applied 
orientation. But, where necessary, this must be accompanied by 
supportive official activities. In this context, it is 
particularly appropriate for the subsidiary principle to 
function as a multi-level toolkit. The activities carried out by 
the BMFT to support R&amp;D in the economy can be classified as 
indirect, indirect-specific and direct forms of support. 
<H5>  Indirect Support </H5>
  Indirect support activities are aimed at generally enhancing 
the R&amp;D potential of the company. They are oriented towards 
potential and as such, they do not impact the tenor of private 
R&amp;D activity. Indirect support activities include personnel 
cost 
subsidies for R&amp;D and administrative regulations like 
investment 
incentives and special deductions. Cooperation between academia 
and business, supportive activities like industrial community 
research, commissioned R&amp;D, technology transfer and research 
cooperation are also components of indirect support. Lastly, 
also included among indirect activities is the program to 
support corporate foundations with a technological orientation. 
<H5>  Indirect-Specific Support </H5>
  On the other hand, the indirect-specific form of support is 
much more appropriate for broadly effective support of specified 
R&amp;D fields. Using accelerated application and implementation 
processes, that mostly benefit SMEs, the use of specified 
technologies is promoted and in this way the economy's 
innovativeness is increased. In this way, for example, the 
accelerated application of important key technologies to new 
products and processes can be supported and a higher rate of 
dissemination can be achieved more rapidly. The BMFT performs 
indirect-specific activities, for example, to support new 
production techniques (CIM, robotics), micro-systems engineering 
and bioprocess engineering. 
<H5>  Direct support </H5>
  Finally, long-term available technology and the 
innovativeness of the German economy are directly impacted under 
the guise of direct project support. This is done through 
targeted support for project planning that encompasses both the 
basic research of academic institutes and R&amp;D having an 
applied 
orientation with substantial participation by industry. This 
type of support entails the strongest form of intervening 
structurally in the innovation process. 
  The objects of the BMFT's direct project support are 
long-term programs in the field of ocean and space research, 
various aspects of precautionary research, and above all, too, 
important technologies that are critical for ensuring the 
long-term competitiveness of German industry. Besides research 
on renewable energy sources, data processing and microsystems 
engineering, it also includes materials research that has 
rightfully been given greater attention in recent years, not 
only by the BMFT. 
  The BMFT's materials research program is also cast in the 
form of direct project support. In this connection, one of the 
focal points of the program is recourse to the combined research 
instrument, that is, the joint participation by a number of 
firms and research institutes in a single project (in contrast 
to the awarding of isolated individual projects). The objective 
of this procedure is efficient use of scarce research 
capabilities by combining resources and intensification of 
technology transfer from academia to industry. This instrument 
should also improve the possibility of SMEs to participate in 
the program. The distinguishing feature of combined projects is 
that, to accomplish a project goal that is acknowledged to be 
important, industrial firms and academic research facilities 
undertake joint, coordinated R&amp;D efforts in an optimum 
combination for the project, with one of the combined partners 
assuming overall charge of the entire project. As a rule, the 
BMFT shares 50 percent of the total cost of the combined 
project. The industrial partners contribute the remaining 50 
percent for themselves and the participating institutes and 
thereby assume co-responsibility for their expenditures. As the 
project increasingly approaches the point of application, the 
industrial partner's share of support can be scaled back to 30 
percent. When the project is of a highly basic nature, the BMFT 
assumes up to 100 percent of the institute's costs. 
<H5>  2.2.3 Survey of the distribution of R&amp;D allocations under </H5>
the materials research program 
  As of February 1992, 577 independent projects with a total 
budget of DM1,652 million, had been initiated under the 
materials research program. Such independent projects comprise 
both individual and combined projects. A further breakdown of 
combined projects into individual projects by the partners in 
the combination yields a total number of 1,111 individual 
projects. The support outlay for those projects amounts to DM894 
million, equivalent to an average support rate of 54 percent. At 
the conclusion of the first half of the program, that is, by 31 
December 1989, projects having a support volume of DM264 
million, equivalent to an average support rate of 56 percent, 
had already been implemented. In the second half of the program, 
since 1 January 1990, there still remain projects entailing a 
support outlay of DM631 million, equivalent to an average 
support rate of 53 percent. Therefore, for the duration of the 
entire length of the program, the average support rate amounts 
to about 50 percent and thus meets program standards for project 
financing. 
  Of the 577 independent projects, 343, or approximately 60 
percent, are combined projects, each with its own project 
application by the partners in the combination. DM1,372 million, 
or, 83 percent of the total budget and DM737 million of the 
total support, that is, 82 percent, are allocated to those 343 
combined projects. 
  This distribution reflects the focused application of the 
instrument for combined research under the materials research 
program wherein a large number of those carrying out (combined) 
projects have simultaneously continued to include subcontractors 
on their projects. For all independent projects the average 
project budget amounts to nearly DM2.9 million and DM4 million 
for combined projects. Average support for all independent 
projects totals nearly DM1.55 million and nearly DM2.150 million 
for combined projects. 
  The survey of the distribution of projects by major 
categories (see table 2.1) clearly shows that more than half of 
all projects are provided with a budget of less than DM2 
million. Contrasting with this, there are a few large projects 
having a project volume of DM10 million or more (five percent of 
all projects), and these effectively tie up a not inconsiderable 
share of the program budget. 




