    In contrast to table 2.2, in industry it is not ceramics but 
the polymers sector that constitutes the group with the largest 
program budget. Otherwise, even here, ceramics, polymers, 
composites and metals make up the categories of materials that 
are generally supported most heavily. In the field of academic 
research, high-temperature and specialty metals, with DM64.8 
million, were the most heavily supported, followed by ceramics, 
composites, new polymers and powder metallurgy. 
  In keeping with the directives laid down for project 
financing of combined projects under the materials research 
program, the average support rate in the industrial sector 
totals 47 percent, while it is close to 88 percent for academic 
research (see table 2.4). 



