    The latter value in this connection is still substantially 
influenced by the relative low rate for support of the ceramics 
sector, which, in turn, results from the inclusion of a single, 
large project financed, for the most part, by industry. 
Altogether, industry's share in the total funding at DM638.8 
million comes to nearly 72 percent of the support budget. By 
comparison, at about DM249.6 million, approximately 27 percent 
of the total support amount is allocated to university and 
non-university institutes. Other recipients got less than one 
percent. If the funds totaling DM638.8 million going into 
industrial research are recategorized, the result is that the 
lion's share of it went to benefit the research and development 
of large firms (see table 2.5). This coincides with additional 
results obtained under this study, in which German industry 
generally not only provides the lion's share of all national 
R&amp;D 
financing, but the largest firms, at the same time, are also 
providing the decisive impetus for further future development of 
materials research. Large industry, therefore, is the 
predominant sponsor of technological development in the field of 
new materials. 
  Large firms and their subsidiaries invested a total of 
nearly 
DM1,197 million under the materials research program, equivalent 
to 73 percent of industry's total share in the program budget. 
Those projects were supported with DM554 million, equivalent to 
63 percent of total support volume and 88 percent of total 
support for industry. By way of contrast, SMEs shared Much less 
extensively in the materials research program. At approximately 
DM119 million, they were allocated only about seven percent of 
the total budget of DM1,652 million. Support for those projects 
totaled DM57 million, equal to 11.4 percent of the support for 
industry and nine percent of total support. 



