    This result is in start contrast to program goals whereby 
SME 
are among the main target groups for improved information and 
technology transfer. This was also correspondingly criticized in 
the poll conducted among selected participants under this study 
on the course of the program (see section 2.3 on this). Further 
assessment, therefore, has to discover what led to this low 
participation by SME, how it is to be assessed, and, above all, 
how to react in designing a catch-up program, considering the 
dominant role of the large firms in materials research. 
  Lastly, the survey of the distribution of support funding 
among different industrial sectors paints a particularly 
informative picture. According to it, the chemical industry is 
especially deeply involved in the materials research program, 
followed by the metals producing, electrical engineering and 
machine building sectors. The lion's share of support, DM239 
million, is allocated just to the chemical industry. Table 2.6 
below shows the distribution of the amounts of support among 
various industrial sectors. 
  More than 50 percent of support for industrial research 
under 
the materials research program went to benefit the chemical and 
metals producing industries. In this context the leading 
contenders under the program are the sectors producing raw 
materials and other materials. In contrast, processing 
industries and various industrial end users, for instance, above 
all, machine building and road vehicle manufacturing, were 
under-proportionately supported. Because of the importance of 
the user and synergistic aspects, however, such a structured 
distribution of support funding for the specific requirements of 
materials development is only partially fair since it does not 
fully support dissemination into broad areas of application. 
  Distribution by specific sector reveals a clear imbalance 
along the net product chain, that is, from materials development 
up to the component and/or system. This entails implications for 
the formulation of guidelines for future BMFT materials research 
support in terms of enhanced consideration of the materials' 
consumers and their greater incorporation into integrated 
projects with materials developers and processors. 



