<H5>      2.3 Assessment of the materials research program </H5>
  In the highly industrialized countries, research and 
development in the natural and engineering sciences is assuming 
ever increasing importance and now more than ever is a major 
determining influence for competitiveness. The new and improved 
products and processes resulting from research and development 
yield competitive advantages and thereby ultimately held ensure 
economic prosperity. 
  Over the past 20 years in Germany, corporate outlay for 
R&amp;D 
rose from DM10.4 billion to DM55.2 billion, equal to an annual 
8.6 percent rate of increase or nearly four percent when 
allowing for inflation. Currently, firms in Germany are 
providing nearly three-fourths of all national R&amp;D financing. 
Meanwhile, however, development activities have become so cost 
intensive in many sectors that even large firms are unable on 
their own to pursue such financing any longer and are having to 
enter into alliances with other firms around the world or resort 
to official support for research. 
  Materials research is the type of sector that requires 
R&amp;D 
alliances and official support. In many instances the results of 
materials research are the key to establishing new technologies 
and are therefore of strategic importance. Simultaneously, 
however, materials research is cost intensive and full of risk, 
above all, since as a rule, the time for disseminating new 
materials into applications is more than 15 years and 
consequently the period for a return on R&amp;D capital 
investments 
is often immensely long. 
  As the next chapter describes in detail, new developments in 
the materials sciences sector are trailblazing or key 
technologies and are exceptionally significant for competitive 
differentiation. They exert a significant impact on corporate 
and national competitiveness and for this reason are intensively 
pursued and officially supported in most industrial countries. 
  The unambiguous outcome of our many interviews at home and 
abroad is that the BMFT's materials research program is by and 
large deemed a successful program. The fundamental strengths of 
materials sciences were combined for the program and in the 
course of the program R&amp;D structures were set up in academic 
and 
industrial research, international recognition of which is 
uncontested and the positive effects of which are still not 
fully foreseeable at the present time. With some exceptions, the 
target groups that were aimed at were realized and the 
"materials-research [MATFO] generation" that has worked on 
projects at the various institutes and in numerous firms and 
that was sensitized and educated to the importance of materials 
research, will surely make its impact fully felt only in 
following years and will continue to make an important 
contribution towards overcoming the perceptible (linguistic) 
barriers between natural scientists and engineers in the past. 
There is no doubt that the materials research program has 
contributed quite substantially to enabling the FRG to keep up 
with the U.S. and Japan, countries that are leaders in 
technology. 



<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-13A>          Chart 2.1: Assessment of the importance of the materials research program's objectives </FIG>

  As indicated by chart 2.1, the materials experts from 
industry and academia who were queried were unanimous in their 
view that, in terms of an assessment of the program's goals, the 
latter were significant and important. This assessment applies 
both to the broad goals and to the objectives for specific 
materials under the various focal topics, each of which was 
deemed important or very important by nearly 75 percent of all 
those queried. 
  One of the broad objectives of the materials research 
program 
is the development of new materials with new or improved useful 
features. Over the course of the program, basic research with an 
applied orientation especially has been supported. As a result, 
a considerable number of new materials or materials having 
improved features and production processes have been developed 
and occasionally tested in different applications. Some 
selective examples under the respective group of materials are 
listed in tables 2.7-2.11. 
<H5>  [Boxed item] Table 2.7: Selective examples of project </H5>
results in the ceramics sector 


    -  Development and/or optimization of clean room 
techniques, plasma coating, flame coating, thermal CVD, slip 
casting, pressure filtration, electrophoretic molding 
  -  Development or continuing development of sol-gel processes, 
reactive spraying, flame hydrolysis and hydrothermal processes 
  -  Testing serial production of large-size simple geometry 
components for heat engineering 
  -  Clarification of corrosion and oxidation reactions at high 
temperatures 
  -  Clarification of the operation of sintered additives with 
definite increases in strength resulting there from 
  -  Ceramic coatings on an industrial scale for engine exhausts 
  -  Development of efficient engine ceramics (valves and seat 
rings, heel plates, etc.) to the point of readiness for testing 
  -  Development of active ingredients for ceramic/metal bondings 
at 
high temperatures 
  -  Development of ultrasonic methods of surface and near surface 
examination 
  -  Detection of volume defects using microfocus x-ray 
engineering 
  -  Economic production of SIMIT materials 
  -  Development of a luminescent ceramic x-ray reservoir 
  -  Development of pressure filtration and electrophoresis as 
molding processes for ion-conducting ceramics 

<H5>    [Boxed item]Table 2.8: Selective examples of project results </H5>
in the powder metallurgy sector 


    -  Optimization of ultrasonic atomization and liquefied 
gas compression 
  -  Ready to apply injection molding of steel powders 
  -  Development of a process for production of powder from 
refractory metals 
  -  Development of a high strength and highly corrosion resistant 
Al alloy, the latter to the point of readiness for use (Airbus) 
  -  Development of two alloys for turbine and engine components 
to 
the point of readiness for use 
  -  Increasing the maximum useful temperature for Ti alloys to 
600 
degrees C through dispersion reinforcement 
  -  Development of new austenitic ODS alloys 
  -  Development of a ferritic alloy resistant to corrosion up to 
1,350 degrees C to the point of readiness for use 
  -  Definite increase in the lifetimes of (steel) roller bearings 
and contact tubing (ODS alloys) through powder metallurgy 
production 
  -  Development of metal injection molding for fast working 
steels 
  -  Development of a new cermet material for cutting tools 
  -  Al structurally reinforced with fibers having increased 
tensile 
strength and elasticity through multi-strand pressing of 
mechanically alloyed Al and Cu 
  -  Examination of molding alternatives for ductile moldable 
nano-crystalline ceramics 

    As an indicator of the scientific and technical results that 
have been realized, it is possible to note the fact that, during 
the course of the materials research program, up to 1991, more 
than 340 patents, 1,800 publications and 2,500 lectures are 
mentioned in the program's yearbooks. This is also evident in 
the patent evaluations for specific materials. German firms that 
have participated intensively in the materials research program, 
in the 1990 assessment, in contrast to 1985, are among the 
companies most active in patents worldwide in various sectors. 
Still, the starting point has to be that a quite considerably 
higher number of scientific publications, directly or indirectly 
linked to the program, were published. 
<H5>  [Boxed item] Table 2.9: Selective examples of project </H5>
results in the high-temperature and specialty metal sector 


    -  Development of inter-metallic phases with useful 
temperatures in excess of 1,200 degrees C 
  -  Development of powder and molten metallurgical production 
processes for inter-metallic phases 
  -  Development of light metal alloys with Li contents of five to 
six percent 
  -  Development of low-pressure lost wax and sand casting for 
light 
metal alloys as well as superplastic deformation, diffusion, 
laser beam and electron beam welding 
  -  Development of a database for light metal alloys 
  -  Development of an uncoated superalloy usable up to 1,100 
degrees C 
  -  Production of a single crystal turbine bucket 
  -  Increase in the high-temperature resistance of weldable 
steels 
to 650 degrees C albeit with insufficient corrosion resistance 
  -  Development of refractory nitrides, borides and carbon 
nitrides 
that can be applied to substrates through vacuum plasma spraying 
  -  Development of diffusion protective layers for superalloys 
  -  Development of machine part coatings that led to very much 
longer lifetimes 
  -  Development of a photochemical process for non-destructive 
testing of layers 
  -  Development of the DESLI process leading to temperature and 
corrosion resistant steels 
  -  Development of a new process for custom welding and 
continuous 
casting 
  -  Development of highly valuable and cost-effective electrode 
coatings for electrolytic processes 
  -  Development of new permanent magnet materials and 
shape-memory-alloys 

<H5>    [Boxed item] Table 2.10: Selective examples of project </H5>
results in the polymers sector 


    -  Development of new aromatic polycarbonates having glass 
transition temperatures up to 190 degrees C and thermoplastic 
processability 
  -  Development of especially impact-resistant duromers through 
the 
insertion of liquid crystal segments 
  -  Development of liquid crystal polymers suitable for modern 
processing methods 
  -  Expansion of the useful temperature range for standard 
thermoplastics via graft polymerization 
  -  Enhanced economizing of a process stage through controlled 
application of temperature 
  -  Development of computer models for molecular interactions and 
interface phenomena and experimental verification - production 
of strictly alternating co-polymers using catalysts 
  -  Development of property-determining superlattices through the 
incorporation of functional groups in defined sequences 
  -  Synthesis of an organic charge-transfer-complex with metallic 
conductivity 
  -  Synthesis of stable polymers with excellent conductive 
properties 
  -  Reduction of attenuation in polymer beam waveguides to below 
100 dB/km 
  -  Optimization of production and characterization and 
determination of the applied possibilities in the laboratory of 
ultrathin layers 
  -  Development of a new system with the highest, nonlinear 
coefficients in the world 
  -  Production of easily processable conductive polymers albeit 
with a molecular weight that is still too low 
  -  Development of high resolution (up to 0.2 m) photoresists 
  -  Development of a new system from liquid crystal polymer and a 
dye for storing holographic images and possibly even for 
polarizing holography 
  -  Basic research on data storage systems 

<H5>    [Boxed item] Table 2.11: Selective examples of project </H5>
results in the composites sector 


    -  Production of C fibers from mesophase resin with high 
tensile strength and Young's modulus 
  -  Production of AL[.sup]2[/]O[.sup]3[/] filament yarns and 
fibers 
  -  Studies on the impact of surface treatment on C fibers 
  -  Drastic increase in a C fiber/thermoplast compound through 
appropriate fiber layers 
  -  Development of new matrix systems having increased 
temperature 
and oxidation resistance, resistance to cracking and ductile 
yield 
  -  Increased heat resistance of Al and Mg alloys through fiber 
reinforcement 
  -  Optimization of commercial fiber purification processes 
  -  Development of production processes (autoforge process, die 
casting) and optimization of processing procedures (sawing, 
drilling, etc.) 
  -  Fashioning an international lead in the production of fiber 
molded solids 
  -  Development of fiber reinforced dichroit and SiC with high 
defect tolerance 
  -  Drastic improvement in properties through coatings, leading 
to 
an average fiber/matrix interaction 
  -  Production of highly pure powder and improvement of product 
uniformity through cleanroom engineering 
  -  Optimization of various powder production processes 
  -  Development of variable distance texturing having high impact 
resistance and low tendency towards delamination 

    By and large, therefore, over the course of the program a 
sizable number of concrete results have been realized. Those 
results have to be given an absolutely favorable assessment, at 
least as regards the scientific and technical targets. Results 
for the commercial and economic goals call for a more nuanced 
and somewhat critical assessment. The assessment of our written 
questionnaire also reflects this nuanced evaluation of the goal 
attainment (see chart 2.2). 
  While the support goals for combined research, support for 
basic research with an applied orientation and development of 
new materials were relatively well realized, the originally 
pursued goals of 


    -  improving the competitiveness of German industry and 
  -  promoting the transfer of information and technology to 
benefit 
SMEs 

    were not adequately realized in the view of those queried. 
In 
assessing the results in terms of the various categories of 
materials it turns out that the original objectives for ceramics 
and composite materials were not entirely satisfactorily met. 
Although considerable progress was made in the manufacture of 
components, there was still no increased dissemination into 
potential areas of application, primarily because of the absence 
of receptive industrial structures. The results for the powder 
metallurgy and high-temperature and specialty metallic materials 
categories of materials were evaluated more favorably. A 
possible explanation for this might be that support funding 
produces the most leverage in those categories of materials 
where the technology position of German firms is already strong 
anyway. The evaluations and assessments of specific materials 
reflect Germany's competitive position in high-performance 
ceramics and composite materials, which, on an international 
scale, can only be categorized as hanging in there. In contrast, 
the position of German firms in high-performance polymers 
remains strong and so is solidified through official research 
support. 
  A less weighted goal, the greater inclusion of SMEs in the 
materials research program could not be realized. This result is 
also documented in the low allocation of funding. In any event, 
it is highly questionable whether SMEs could yet at all "afford" 
the type of materials research that was primarily to be 
supported by the program. As a rule, SMEs rely on a considerably 
faster return on funding than larger firms and therefore are 
less effectively able to engage in the risky projects with a 
long-term focus typical of materials research. In our view, this 
type of configuration leads to the questioning of such an 
objective, even if, so far, it has been of slight importance. 
  In the opinion of a large part of the experts who were 
polled, the actual broad goal of the materials research program, 
improvement of German industry's competitiveness likewise was 
not adequately realized. In this context, however, attention 
needs to be given to two aspects. The seven year time period 
since the start of the program is not a sufficient length of 
time to be able to assess the extent to which the basic 
operation or results of basic research with an applied 
orientation impact on the competitiveness of companies or 
sectors. The dissemination time for new materials into broad 
areas of application in most instances amounts to 15 years or 
more, so that new developments and products presently are still 
not able to exert a decisive impact on the competitive position. 
That is precisely where strategic research topics and topics in 
the sector of trailblazing and embryonic technologies differ 
from research and development that goes along with products or 
is on the point of being applied. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-17A>        Chart 2.2: Assessment of the materials research program's goal attainment </FIG>

  The many good technical and scientific results of the 
materials research program constitute the basis for ensuring 
strategic competitiveness provided their implementation and 
market dissemination are supported and accelerated in the 
future. The competitive position of user sectors will only be 
sustainably improved on the basis of those results if they are 
able to apply the previously developed basis for materials and 
technologies. 
  Moreover, it must be noted that competitiveness should be 
viewed only relative to the principal competitors. There is no 
question but that Japan and the U.S. are pursuing and officially 
supporting materials research just as intensively as is being 
done in Germany. Over the past years Japan has improved its 
competitive position among the leading industrial nations 
through concentrated and targeted research support. There is no 
question also but that the U.S. is investing extremely higher 
private and even official funding in materials research than the 
FRG and is thereby developing its competitive advantage over the 
longer haul. In this intensive competition the BMFT's materials 
research program is even now playing a critical role in 
maintaining the competitiveness of German industry. However, it 
must be remarked that optimization of the mechanisms for project 
selection and support would have further enhanced the 
forcefulness of the program. Conspicuously absent from project 
selection and support are: 


    -  a clear product and system linkage, enabling 
determination of whether a project is developing new 
technologies or significantly improving existing technologies 
  -  suitable assessment mechanisms in the form of portfolio 
management whereby, specifically in the case of limited 
resources, the most innovative projects can be filtered out and 
made accessible to targeted support 
  -  consistent and earliest possible inclusion of customer 
sectors 
in the innovation process and 
  -  Overlapping of different support programs in which materials 
research plays a part. 

    Based on our research, sufficient support funding has been 
provided under the materials research program, not counting SME 
support that could be only insufficiently included in the 
program. As indicated in chart 2.3, direct project support 
precipitated out combined research with particular emphasis as a 
pre-eminently suitable apparatus. Combined research has been 
supported intensively in the current program and it was often 
the pre-requisite for approval of project applications. More 
than 80 percent of support funding was spent on combined 
projects. 
  Not least, considering experiences in Japan and the U.S. 
(see 
chapter three), it is reasonable to continue the important role 
of combined research even in any future materials research 
support design. In this context, it strikes us as advisable to 
continue differentiating the existing apparatus as much as 
possible to match demand. The following sorts of combined 
support should be considered therein: 


    -  horizontal combinations of a single net product stage, 
wherein firms address basic topics, remote from competition, 
that might be too risky and costly for individual companies 
  -  vertical combinations of successive net product stages, 
wherein 
firms address topics with an applied orientation focused on user 
requirements profiles 
  -  combinations involving academic and industrial research, that 
overlap both of the other combined systems and in which know-how 
is transferred and next-generation researchers are sensitized 
early on to the interests of industry. 

    It must be emphasized, however, that the combined research 
instrument was not the right one for all types of projects, and 
that not all combined projects led to the desired results. 
  In terms of the assessment of the kinds of support applied 
under the materials research program, the results of which are 
summarized in chart 2.4, a rather diversified picture emerges. 
Thus, in the majority estimation of the survey group, support 
for basic research with an applied orientation and applied 
research was well satisfied. On the other hand, support for 
product and processing development was considered less well met. 
However, this was not an explicit component of the program's 
target list and also in connection with considerations of a 
political order and allowing for EC legislation cannot be 
realized without further qualification. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-19A>        Chart 2.3: Assessment of the importance of support principles relevant to materials research </FIG>

  The assessment of the initiation and support of cooperative 
activities and exchange of data particularly in regard to market 
and technology trends turns out to be average to good. In this 
context, it turns out that there is a basic openness among those 
surveyed vis-a-vis more strongly coordinated official activities 
than thus far and this should be taken into account in the 
context of future materials research support. 
  The organization of the program in terms of total support 
amounts, program duration and durations of specific projects is 
positively assessed (see chart 2.5). In the opinion of the 
experts, however, the program, in its current form, displays 
weaknesses because of its not completely satisfactory 
flexibility. Once again, at this juncture, it must be noted that 
the distribution of funding among the individual foci of the 
program and the design of the project selection process should 
be more heavily oriented toward the goal of an improved 
competitive position for German industry in order to achieve 
greater effectiveness. 
  Oversight of the participant by the BMFT and the project 
sponsor, PLR Juelich, in connection with implementation of the 
materials research program is assessed as satisfactory to good. 
Support counseling and total project management were carried out 
very efficiently by those in charge. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-20A>        Chart 2.4: Assessment of the importance of types of support relevant to materials research </FIG>

  On the other hand, from a strategic perspective, program 
management continued to be inadequate. In the current program 
this responsibility did not come under the purview of the PLR, 
but in the future it should really be included among the 
responsibilities of a project sponsor. 
  In terms of the design for future support activities, the 
analysis indicates that rapid, targeted and, as a result, 
efficient handling of a project can only be realized if an 
operative project management is installed. This is evident 
especially from the experiences arising from the in-depth 
analysis of individual projects (see section 2.3). This applies 
above all to organizationally complex combined projects. The 
experiences acquired during the current program make it 
reasonable, among other things, to lay down the following basic 
principles for project management: 


    -  clear project definition and unambiguous formulation of 
primary and secondary goals for entire and partial projects 
  -  clear organization of project development including an 
unambiguous prioritizing of duties and responsibilities 
  -  Establishment of project cycle organization defining the 
course 
of the project and reporting both internally and to the project 
sponsor 
  -  Establishment of efficient project control 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-21A>        Chart 2.5: Assessment of program organization and implementation in the materials research </FIG>

  Inefficiencies always occur in the project cycle whenever 
there is no control system to guarantee a planned approach in 
the realization of the objectives. Such inefficiencies place not 
only the realization of project goals at risk but also the 
realization of broad program goals. 
  Actually, the materials research program was largely able to 
meet the originally desired expectations from a scientific and 
technical point of view. The total spectrum of materials 
sciences in industrial and academic research was able to derive 
a great impetus from the program. In a technical and scientific 
context, a number of unquestionably significant results were 
realized. 
  Considering the all-encompassing nature of the materials 
research program's objectives, however, it was not possible for 
all goals to be realized. The commercial effects of those 
technical successes have yet to become fully manifest. The goal 
of strengthening the competitive position of German industry has 
so far been able to be realized only inadequately. Even the 
desired support for SMEs could not be realized for the reasons 
already described. As a result, the system for goals should be 
reviewed with an eye on future support. 
  It also became apparent several times in the course of the 
analysis that the efficiency of the entire program depends quite 
decidedly on the establishment of consistent management both 
operationally on the project level and strategically on the 
program level. 
<H5>  2.4 Experiences from the current program's projects </H5>
  In previous sections an analysis was made of the materials 
research program, allocation and application of funding as well 
as an assessment of the program's results. The analyses were 
performed in an aggregated form on the level of the entire 
program and for individual subgroups (categories of materials, 
types of financing recipients, etc.). Foremost in section 2.2 
was the assessment of the program's effectiveness in terms of 
the realization of the professed goals of the program. Only 
secondarily, however, was the question of the program's 
efficiency and its most important elements raised. 
  The foremost question when reviewing efficiency is whether 
the results that were achieved were able to be realized with an 
optimum cost/benefit ratio. Such efficiency analysis can only be 
meaningfully carried out if processes, cycles and crucial 
structures are analyzed on as greatly disaggregated a level as 
possible. In that connection, the proper unit of analysis turns 
out to be the individual project. Proceeding from the analysis 
of individual projects, conclusions must be made about the 
program's efficiency and its most important elements. 
  Assessment of program efficiency especially requires 
reference to the special characteristics of materials 
development and the regularity of the industrial dissemination 
process. The total complex of materials research is impregnated 
with special properties that any relevant research support has 
to explicitly allow for. Materials technology entails a 
technology having a pronounced broad-spectrum character, that 
impacts on very many industrial sectors but that encounters 
quite specific user requirements in each individual application. 
The R&amp;D process in materials research, therefore, requires an 
expressly applied thrust even in the earliest basic activities. 
Successful materials development, in particular, is 
distinguished by the fact that all relevant net product stages 
are considered from the outset when the R&amp;D process is being 
given its focus. 
  Since more than 550 projects were supported under the 
program 
over a period of more than a decade, we were obliged from the 
outset to forgo performing a systemic and representative 
analysis of all projects. In lieu of this the approach was to, 


    -  carry out a restricted number of representative case 
studies wherein decision-making cycles, substantive 
responsibilities and coordinating mechanisms were reviewed, as 
well as 
  -  undertake an assessment of the interviews with experts with a 
view towards assessing efficiency on the project and program 
levels. 
  Included especially in the case studies were projects 
03M2012 "ceramic materials for high-performance components for 
the manufacture of engines and turbines," 03M4008 "ultrathin 
polymer layers," 03M4036 "liquid crystal polymers for optical 
data technology," 03M0013 "new ODS superalloys" and 30M102131 
"carmat 2000." 
  The data thus assembled were supplemented by extensive 
analyses and project experiences enabling a more precise 
interpretation and assessment of the existing indicators. In 
this context, the following data, in particular, were addressed: 


    -  assessments of comparable materials research projects 
outside of the country (Japan, EC) 
  -  detailed knowledge of the management of R&amp;D projects in 
the 
context of our consultant activity, especially for large 
firms[.sup]4[/] 
  -  detailed knowledge of the management of combined 
technological 
projects and strategic alliances[.sup]5[/] as well as an 
  -  assessment of studies and project analyses on other 
comparable 
BMFT support programs. 

    There is no questioning the appropriateness of direct 
project 
support for the realization of desired program goals. Any 
efficient R&amp;D support in the materials research sector 
requires 
an apparatus that uses a targeted approach on the project level. 
By way of contrast, the focused support of combined projects 
under the BMFT's materials support program requires a somewhat 
diversified treatment. The basic appropriateness of this 
instrument for the realization of program goals is laudable. By 
incorporating the various partners from basic materials research 
through component production up to and including industrial 
application, access to support is open to all participants and 
in this way account is taken of the specific demands of 
materials research. 
  As the analysis of program implementation demonstrates, 
criteria for the organization and financing of projects were 
administratively implemented by the project sponsor in such a 
way that, for the most part, separate authorizations were 
awarded to the participating partners. The result was functional 
leeway given to them that considerably complicated integrated 
project management and simultaneously, in the case of the 
separate awarding of projects, making it impossible for any 
single industrial partner to shoulder the role of overall 
supervision with the necessary consistency. Therefore, in the 
case of the basic appropriateness of the combined research 
instrument, functional tightening of the implementation in the 
form of consistent project management needs to be pondered. 
  On the whole, our analysis of selective materials research 
projects and the assessment of the indicated supplemental data 
leads to the conclusion that there are generalizable success 
factors, whose realization or non-realization quite decidedly 
impact the efficiency of the projects. The most important 
success factors for materials research projects deserving 
emphasis are: 
  1. The project goals have to as precisely definable as 
possible and provide a clear guiding theme for project 
definition and structuring of responsibilities; the starting 
point should be a specific requirement, if possible, a clearly 
drawn requirements profile. 
  2. In establishing goals and project definition, an 
intelligent search and selection procedure must be employed, 
that is as open as possible, but is goal oriented and that 
includes all important know-how platforms. 
  3. Since goals and responsibilities may change over time, 
there has to be a flexible process for fine tuning the project 
whereby changed goals and requirements can be "brought under 
control" as quickly and trouble-free as possible and be 
coordinated among the participants. 
  4. There have to be clearly defined responsibilities and 
clusters of activities for each of which there are clearly 
defined accountabilities; among the participants there should be 
activities sectors that are as complementary as possible and as 
little competition as possible. 
  5. The number of participants should be restricted as 
closely 
as possible to those partners who are capable of making a 
noteworthy contribution to the success of the total project 
through definite competence, technological strengths and 
management experiences. 
  6. Cooperation should be regulated by a legal framework 
appropriate for the project that spells out, in particular, 
responsibilities, patent rights and liabilities. 
  7. Because of the complicated division of responsibility and 
the constantly changing interests and data of the participants, 
there needs to be a highly intensive exchange of data and 
viewpoints on the formal and also on the informal level. 
  8. In order to be able to appropriately address the 
complicated responsibilities of coordination and harmonization, 
there needs to be a central supervision of the project by a 
coordinator or overall administrator at the hub of the data flow 
and decision-making process. 
  9. The project should be buttressed by as efficient an 
apparatus as possible for project management and control. 

    Such success factors need to be weighted differently for the 
different groups of projects. In this context, the determining 
parameters are: 


    -  scope of the project and project cost 
  -  organization complexity of the project 
  -  the nature of the research and 
  -  the complexity of the research task. 

    Considering these parameters, under the current materials 
research program there is a broad spectrum of project 
manifestations, especially in terms of the combined structure 
and the resulting organizational complexity. In the final 
analysis, the extreme values of this analysis are, on the one 
side, simply structured projects having few subcontractors or 
combined partners and issues and having a basic nature with a 
pronounced applied orientation, and, on the other side, 
organizationally complex combined projects often involving more 
than five separate recipients of funding and their 
subcontractors, wherein, many-faceted, fundamental topics are 
addressed over periods exceeding five years. 
  By all appearances, the apparatus of direct project support 
works trouble-free for simply structured projects, especially if 
the recipients of the financing take on the responsibility for 
R&amp;D management and control themselves. There is no doubting 
the 
successfulness of direct project support even in the case of 
projects entailing high organizational complexity and wherein 
the participating recipients of funding are clustered on the 
principle of self-organization and see to the appropriate form 
of project administration themselves. 
  The apparatus for R&amp;D support, however, and the manner 
in 
which combined research has been practiced up until now do not 
always prove not be optimum if the point is to apply the above 
mentioned success factors to complex projects with many 
independent combined partners. Thus far, the BMFT and the 
project sponsorship have actively influenced the realization of 
the success factors in only a very limited way. 
  In this regard, it is beyond the scope of an assessment of 
the federal government's materials research program 
retrospectively to review project and program efficiency on the 
basis of success factors and assessment criteria that were not 
initially formulated in this fashion and that were originally 
excluded when the program was designed. The indicated success 
factors, however, do facilitate a forward-looking analysis and 
thus constitute an important basis for an ex-ante assessment of 
future support activities. To the extent that in the future 
materials research projects will increasingly display the 
features of more complex and organizationally demanding projects 
as previously described, in the crafting of future programs it 
will be essential explicitly to allow for the indicated success 
factors. Therefore, they will be addressed again in chapter five 
among the recommendations for a future support strategy. 
Footnotes 
  1. Paralleling the materials research program that 
represents 
the cross-section function for materials, so to speak, there are 
other projects receiving support under other programs on the 
federal level, whose tenor is relevant to materials research. 
Such, for instance, are operational materials in the 
micro-electronic and microsystems engineering sectors, in 
high-temperature superconduction as well as those falling under 
the support focus for surface and thin-film engineering. There 
is also considerable, substantive interaction with EC programs 
in the field of materials engineering and with others in the 
various federal states for specific materials research programs. 
  2. It is still not possible clearly to ascertain an 
improvement in German industry's competitiveness, because of the 
long time for the dissemination of materials developments (up to 
15 years) and structural impediments to dissemination; a more 
intense integration of SME was not unequivocally realized. 
  3. Subsidiaries of large firms 
  4. Subsidiaries of large firms 
