<H5>  3.International Comparison of Materials Research and Support </H5>
For It 
  In all highly industrialized nations, the internationally 
acknowledged major significance of materials research as a key 
and trailblazing technology, leads to considerable R&amp;D 
efforts 
and corresponding support activities. The international 
comparative analysis of materials research and support for it, 
therefore, can be summarized in the following results: 
  (1) The most important impetus for materials engineering 
comes from the large, multinational companies in the troika of 
countries. Two-thirds of the companies with the strongest 
turnover worldwide view materials research as a focus of their 
R&amp;D investments. They leave a lasting imprint on the 
international development and use of new materials (chapter 3.1). 
  (2) Any "benchmarking" for assessing the developmental 
prospects of materials technology in Germany has to focus on the 
chief rivals in Japan and the U.S. In coming years, Japanese 
companies will definitely continue to increase their R&amp;D 
efforts. In this context, they emphasize actions to augment 
efficiency and strategies for national and international 
cooperation. Japanese firms accept as partners only companies 
and institutes that have a very strong technological position 
themselves (chapter 3.1.2). 
  (3) Materials research will operate on a continuing high 
level in American industry in coming years. It outstrips 
Germany's R&amp;D efforts by several orders of magnitude. 
Concurrently, an enduring reorientation is observable in the 
U.S., that is definitely focused on improving international 
competitiveness through new materials. Cost and use aspects, in 
particular, are underscored through heavy emphasis on materials 
processing and systematizing (chapter 3.1.2). 
  (4) In the two leading countries, the concept of a system, 
that is, the development of a strong national materials research 
in the context of dynamic user industries on the national level, 
receives heavy emphasis. In Germany, by comparison, the 
innovation process remains too heavily centered on the producer 
and is too heavily oriented toward basic research. So far, only 
in a few sectors, even on an international scale, are there 
successful systems allying materials manufacturers and 
growth-oriented, innovative consumers (chapter 3.1.3). 
  (5) In Germany, therefore, development is adversely 
impacted, 
above all, by the inadequate presence of dynamic user groups. 
Only dynamic consumers are able to generate the critical mass 
effect for materials development as well as contribute to the 
establishment of competitive structures in the development and 
production sectors. So far, in Germany, even dissemination to 
secondary applications with high growth and net product 
potential has continued to be neglected. Intensive net product 
systems applications, follow-on developments in low-cost sectors 
and the pre- and post-situational development of the processing 
and service stages still continue to receive too little 
attention. 
  (6) Support plays a front-and-center role in a functional 
national system of producers, consumers and research institutes. 
All industrial countries support materials research to a very 
great extent and, accordingly, they prioritize quite similar 
development sectors (chapter 3.2). It is crucial to pursue a 
targeted, national strategy of differentiation. Successful 
differentiation is primarily realized by aligning national 
programs as effectively as possible with R&amp;D strategies and 
innovative activities of the most important actors from industry 
and research. Japan's support strategy is a model in this 
respect (chapter 3.2.1). Even in the U.S. there is an 
increasingly greater effort, through national consensus 
building, to develop the existing strengths of materials 
engineering (chapter 3.2.2). 
  (7) Adversely impacting materials research support in 
western 
Europe with generally high R&amp;D expenditures is national 
fragmentation and parallel development of national innovative 
systems. In many cases existing strengths are still marked by 
"national islands of competence." Since the early seventies, any 
number of European programs and initiatives have been introduced 
to link them together (chapter 3.2.3). They continue to be of 
great significance, but they cannot take the place of the 
development of national programs that have to focus on shoring 
up national strengths vis-a-vis the main competitors from Japan 
and the U.S. 
  (8) The development of basic research has to be integrated 
more intensely than hitherto in this parallelogram of 
international competitive forces. In Europe, Germany enjoys a 
very good reputation for basic research and materials oriented 
training and professionalization. These have to stand out even 
more strongly, however, in a global context in terms of 
long-term industrial convertibility (chapter 3.3). More 
intensive "fitness for use" criteria have to be adduced as the 
quality standard for research and development. Effective 
transfer between basic research and industrial application 
occurs in too few sectors of German materials research. This 
requires efforts by all participants and new forms of 
cooperation as well as new forms of research support, 
organization and financing (see especially chapter 5 on this). 
<H5>  3.1 Industrial foci of materials research: Japan, U.S. and </H5>
Germany compared 
  Analysis of industrial materials research in Japan, the U.S. 
and Germany demonstrates that companies with the greatest 
turnover attach high to very high importance to materials 
research. The summary (see table 3.1) makes it clear that 33 of 
the 50 companies with the most turnover around the world see a 
focal point in materials research. Those companies lay out 
considerable funding for such R&amp;D sectors, above all, 
Japanese 
companies, among whom, in many cases, there is a discernible 
tendency to expand their activities. 
  Comparing the R&amp;D fields of the most important 
companies in 
the three indicated countries, one detects an extensive 
prioritizing of similar topical areas that frequently even 
coincide with official support concepts. The most important 
R&amp;D 
fields that emerge are: 
  - materials-oriented topics, for example, ceramics, polymers 
and metals and metal alloys sectors 
  - topics with an applied and systems linkage, for example, 
optoelectronic systems, electronic components and biocompatible 
products. 
  Naturally, the individual, specific R&amp;D plans and 
projects of 
the analyzed firms are focused, respectively, on strategic 
corporate goals and elude comparative analysis on higher levels 
of aggregation. On the whole, however, our research turned up a 
clear tendency to create cooperative research activities and 
combinations for the purpose of economizing on resources and 
increasing efficiency. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-26A>        Table 3.1: The 50 companies with the highest turnover worldwide and the importance of materials </FIG>

  Such combinations extend, respectively, to partners of 
identical or prior or later net product stages. Increasingly, 
cooperative activities entail an international focus and may 
include renowned R&amp;D institutes from the academic research 
sector. For systems development itself, more and more 
inter-disciplinary approaches are being pursued within the firms. 
  All indications are that the transfer of the results 
realized 
in cooperative R&amp;D activities always succeed relatively 
trouble-free if a distinct pull effect comes from 
application-oriented partners of the combination. In this 
connection it turns out that it is precisely the most important 
applied sectors in Germany, for example, the automobile industry 
or machine building, that are hardly dynamic in the use of 
high-performance materials. In any fresh support design for 
materials research this state of affairs should be counteracted. 
<H5>  3.1.1 Materials research activities of Japanese firms </H5>
  Large Japanese firms, whose focal activities are in the 
electronics/data engineering, vehicle manufacturing and chemical 
sectors, attach high to very high importance to high-performance 
materials and their processing technologies (see table 3.2). 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-27A>        Table 3.2: The 25 Japanese companies with the highest turnover and the importance of </FIG>

  Those firms' R&amp;D outlays for high-performance materials 
are 
considerable, as may be expected, and they are significantly 
higher than official allocations for R&amp;D in that sector. 
  Our analysis shows that Japanese firms will increase their 
outlays for R&amp;D, including materials research, beyond the 
level 
attained thus far. Some companies in the materials sector have 
set themselves the goal of investing up to 10 percent of their 
turnover proceeds in R&amp;D. Also observable are corporate 
activities targeting increased R&amp;D efficiency. These 
essentially 
include: 
  - intensification of joint projects involving industrial 
firms and research institutes 
  - intensification of project activity among industrial firms 
from different sectors 
  - Support for Japanese industrial researchers residing 
abroad 
at leading research institutes around the world that apply 
advanced methods and technologies. 
  Paralleling this expansion of R&amp;D allocations and the 
pursuit 
of new forms of R&amp;D management is an extremely intensive 
search 
for new and promising areas for success to be eyed for strategic 
product and market developments. 
  In a poll of leading Japanese chemical firms, the following 
sectors were mentioned as the most important fields for R&amp;D 
targets. According to that survey, the large chemical firms 
prioritize R&amp;D fields from various sectors of materials 
research. For the surveyed firms, of special importance as 
fields for materials research are the sectors, in particular, of 
electronic materials including optoelectronics (26 percent), 
high-performance materials (18 percent), the development of new 
composite materials (three percent) and polymers having 
exceptional properties (two percent). 
  Within the indicated R&amp;D fields, activities were 
concentrated 
on the following groups of materials: 


    -  Development of high-performance ceramics 
  The focus for development of high-performance ceramics is on 
materials like Al[.sup]2[/]O[.sup]3[/], SiO[.sup]2[/], 
BaTiO[.sup]3[/] and ferrites, for oxide ceramics, and for 
non-oxide ceramics, on compounds like SiC, WC, 
SI[.sup]3[/]N[.sup]4[/], AIN, BN. 
%High-performance polymers (specialty polymers) 
  According to the survey these are taken to mean all polymers 
that are resistant to temperatures exceeding 260 degrees C and 
simultaneously are of high strength. Of special interest in this 
connection are the LCP's, PI, PPS, PES, PEEK, and PAR. Under 
development are thermoplasts resistant to temperatures exceeding 
300 degrees C, such as, for instance, special modification of 
PEEK, PAEK, and PKS. 
%Composites 
  Japanese industry's R&amp;D activities in the composites 
sector 
are concentrated on composite materials having a polymer matrix. 
In the past, the R&amp;D focus here was on the development of 
high 
performance reinforcing materials (glass fibers, carbon fibers, 
other). In the future, polymers, that is, thermoplasts and 
duroplasts and their compounding with fibers will also be at the 
center of Japan's R&amp;D activities. Composites having a 
metallic 
or ceramic matrix are of little interest there. 



<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-29A>          Chart 3.1: Selective research activities by Japanese firms in the high-performance materials </FIG>



<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-30A>          Chart 3.2: Selective research activities by Japanese firms in the electronic materials </FIG>

  Chart 3.1 displays, as examples, some selective R&amp;D 
activities by Japanese chemical firms with their focuses in 
various materials sectors. 
  The focus of Japan's industrial research in the field of 
electronic materials is in the fields of: 


    -  Semiconductor materials 
  R&amp;D activities here are concentrated on GaAs, GaP and 
InP 
materials. The target of the research activities is the use of 
such materials in electronics. 
%Printed circuit board [PCB] materials 
%Recording and storage materials 
  In these sectors the foci are on materials for magnetic 
tapes, magnetic and optical disks, especially optical disks that 
can be over-written 
%Materials for optoelectronics 
  The development focus here is on optical and 
energy-exchanging materials 


      Chart 3.2 presents a survey of the focuses of five selective 
Japanese firms in the electronic materials sector. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-31A>        Chart 3.3: Selective cooperative activities by Japanese firms in the materials technologies </FIG>

  In materials research, the surveyed companies in the 
chemical 
and electronic sectors implement both in-house R&amp;D 
strategies as 
well as R&amp;D combinations on the national level that 
supplement 
those and that encompass academic research plus the various 
stages of the net product chain. Supplementing those, 
cooperative R&amp;D activities were sought with foreign firms in 
certain fields. Chart 3.3 presents an analysis of selective 
international cooperative activities by Japanese firms in 
high-performance materials and processing technologies in terms 
of international joint ventures and technology imports and 
exports. 
  The analysis of selective cooperative activities in 
materials 
research, just like the findings from our interviews, reinforces 
the impression that Japanese companies, especially in the 
chemical and electronic sectors, welcome as partners only 
companies and institutes that have a good or very good 
technology position or that contribute specific know-how. This 
cooperative strategy is particularly evident in polymers and 
electronic materials. 
<H5>  3.1.2 Materials research activities of American firms </H5>
  For practically all sectors of the American economy, 
materials research holds high and often even strategic 
significance. Hence numerous firms in materials manufacturing as 
well as in materials using industries conduct R&amp;D activities 
in 
the materials technologies sector. The focus of R&amp;D efforts 
that 
are aimed especially at the development and application of high 
performance materials, devolves upon chemical firms and some 
large companies in the aerospace, electronics and automobile 
industry sectors. Table 3.3 displays an assessment of the 
importance of materials research for American firms. Except for 
petroleum industry firms, materials research commands high to 
very high priority for the largest American companies. 
  In upcoming years, materials research activities in American 
industry will be marked by the following developments: 


    -  R&amp;D planning in the materials research sector in the 
future is likely to have a stronger interdisciplinary focus. It 
is especially likely that closer cooperation between scientists 
and engineers will be sought. 
  -  Materials research efficiency is likely to be augmented 
through 
a more intensive cooperation among firms and institutes. 
  -  In addition to the synthesizing of materials, processing of 
materials and designing of systems will also be focal points of 
future materials research projects. 
  -  Targeted American products are likely to be improved through 
materials research in order to be more competitive on world 
markets. 

    This change in the focus and nature of the implementation of 
R&amp;D planning is deliberately aimed at significantly 
strengthening the competitive position of U.S. companies 
vis-a-vis Japanese suppliers. Mastery of new materials 
technologies, a stronger product and applied orientation and 
management of combined projects that encompasses firms and 
sectors are viewed as the decisive starting point for realizing 
concrete results to increase competitiveness. 
  Within materials and processing technologies, U.S. firms are 
focusing on the following fields of materials research: 


    -  High-performance ceramics 
  -  High-performance polymers 
  -  High-performance composites 
  -  High-performance metals and alloys 
  -  Biocompatible materials 
  -  Electronic materials 
  -  Magnetic materials 
  -  Non-linear optical materials 
  -  Superconducting materials 
  -  Coating technology 
  -  Nano-crystal materials 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-33A>        Table 3.3: The 25 U.S. companies with the highest turnover and the importance of materials research </FIG>

  The analysis of research activities, using as an example 
some leading firms, demonstrates that they basically engage in R&amp;D 
activities in the fields of high-performance polymers, 
high-performance composites and high-performance ceramics. In 
the chemical industry at least, on the other hand, materials 
developments in the high-performance metals and alloys, 
electronic and magnetic materials are realized only selectively 
and often constitute the domains of highly specialized firms or 
are performed by the applied sectors. 
  The analysis of a few selective cooperative activities shows 
that, comparably to Japan, the surveyed companies welcomed only 
partners with demonstrated technology competence. Here too the 
resulting impression is that the firms primarily incorporate 
"low-tech" for cooperative activities and endeavor to obtain 
access to high technology they have not yet mastered via the 
respective alliances. 
<H5>  3.1.3 Materials research activities in German industry </H5>
  In Germany the most important platforms for materials 
research are the large firms from the chemical, vehicle 
manufacture, electrical engineering as well as steel and 
equipment manufacturing sectors that are active internationally 
(see table 3.4 on this). 
  Because of the diverse characteristics in the nature and 
implementation of materials research in the individual sectors, 
the materials research activities of German industry should be 
described on three levels. First come the materials research 
foci in the materials producing industries, meaning, in 
particular, the large firms in the chemical and metal producing 
industries. Next are the materials research foci in the 
materials using industries. Thirdly, the characteristics of the 
development and use of high-performance materials in SMEs from 
various sectors of the processing industry are examined. 
  It is basically the materials research activities in 
industry 
in the former federal states that constitute the focus of the 
following description. In the new federal states at present, 
materials research activities are fundamentally impacted by the 
comprehensive restructuring activities in industry. These have 
led to a complete overhaul of industrial research activities. 
Currently, the industrial research activities of the new federal 
states in the field of materials research appear highly 
fragmented. On the whole, however, the level has to be assessed 
as being far below materials research in West Germany. This is 
certainly attributable also to the equipment that is available. 
Only a few isolated materials research activities are presently 
up to the level of the former federal states. 
<H5>  3.1.3.1 Foci of materials research in sectors that </H5>
manufacture materials 
  German industry's materials research activities encompass 
all 
sectors. While the foci for the chemical or metals producing 
industries are concentrated on the first level of the net 
product chain, that is, basic materials and semi-finished 
products, the materials research activities in industries using 
the materials, for example, automobile industry, electrical 
engineering/electronics and machine building, are focused on the 
subsequent levels of the net product chain, namely, the 
production of components and systems. 
  This diversified focus of materials research activities has 
also impacted the allocation of financing by the BMFT's 
materials research program. In the MATFO program, basically 
focused on the development of new materials, the materials 
producing industries, logically, are the most heavily involved. 
Up to half of the program's time, for example, the chemical 
industry initiated projects having a volume of DM520 million or 
30 percent of the total budget, followed by metals production 
with DM194 million (=14 percent). In contrast to this, the 
participation by each of the applied sectors was distinctly 
lower, although in this context it needs to be noted that firms 
in this sector also take part in other support programs having 
topics of relevance to materials. 
  In the nineties, the research and development activities of 
chemical industry firms in the materials research sector will 
basically be determined by the following developments: 


    -  more intense focusing of materials research activities 
on the innovation requirements of growth-oriented, international 
markets 
  -  R&amp;D projects in the materials sector will be 
increasingly more 
intensively focused on opening up new markets having high net 
product 
  -  Materials research activities will be directed increasingly 
at 
advanced processing in addition to the synthesizing of materials 
  -  R&amp;D projects in the materials research sector will also 
be 
increasingly given an international and interdisciplinary 
organization 
  -  In the future, materials research in the field of functional 
materials will be more closely coupled with systems R&amp;D. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-35A>        Table 3.4: The 25 German companies with the highest turnover and the importance of materials </FIG>

  R&amp;D activities in the German chemical firm's high-performance 
materials sector primarily focus on the continuous development 
of core competencies and on the development of parent companies. 
Concurrently with this, the large chemical firms, however, are 
also pursuing fresh types of projects outside the sectors of 
their traditional businesses and competencies. These may be 
characterized as diversification projects or even as strategic 
R&amp;D fields. For chemical firms these especially include 
research 
activities in the high-performance ceramics sector, electronic 
materials, high-performance metals and alloys and polymer 
composites. 
  The following fields of research in structural materials and 
in functional materials are of special interest for Germany's 
chemical industry firms: For structural materials, R&amp;D is 
being 
carried out in the sectors of sterically and configuratively 
uniform polymers, high-temperature resistant polymers, 
hard-chain (liquid crystal) polymers, memory effect polymers, 
high-performance ceramic, memory effect ceramics and composites 
as well as in the sector of nano-crystal materials. 
  In the functional materials sector, R&amp;D activities are 
fundamentally concentrated in the following areas: materials 
with special electrical or magnetic properties (for instance, 
electrically conductive polymers, high-temperature 
superconductors), materials with special optical properties (for 
instance, beam wave guides, materials for photonics and 
optoelectronics), materials with special thermal properties (for 
instance, materials having high heat resistance), materials with 
special separation properties (for instance, gas-separation 
membranes, high-performance membranes for micro-, ultra- and 
nano-filtration), materials with biological properties (for 
instance, biocompatible materials, biosensors) plus high-order, 
functional, ultrathin layers (for instance, for the development 
of a "molecular electronics"). 
  In upcoming years, the R&amp;D efforts of firms in the metal 
producing industry will be greatly impacted by the following 
developments: 


    -  In the future, R&amp;D planning should be more heavily 
focused on products that enable the realization of high net 
product. 
  -  R&amp;D activities should greatly contribute towards the 
opening 
and development of new fields of business. 
  -  In the future, R&amp;D planning in the metal producing 
industry 
will be concentrated even more heavily on advanced processing 
technologies. 
  -  In the future, R&amp;D projects will be implemented on an 
international and interdisciplinary basis. 

    Within materials research, the R&amp;D activities of this 
sector 
will be concentrated, for example, on the following selective 
fields of research: 
  - Materials related topics 


    -  High-performance metals and alloys (research on the 
structure and bonding properties of metallic materials, metallic 
high-temperature materials, light metals and light-metal alloys, 
composites having a metallic matrix, superalloys and 
optimization of specialty steel properties) 
  -  High-performance ceramics 
  -  High-performance composites 

    - Production-oriented topics 


    -  Production of ultra-pure metal materials and alloys 
  -  Development of production processes approximating the final 
contours 
  -  Development of new coating and alloy techniques 
  -  Rapid rigidifying techniques 
  -  Powder metallurgical processes 
  -  Bonding techniques 
  -  Foundry technology 

    The R&amp;D foci of this industry that have been identified 
are 
clearly concentrated on the continuous improvement of existing 
core competencies and parent companies. Firms in this sector 
seek their materials research foci for the most part in the 
high-performance metals and alloys sector. It is worth noting, 
however, that many firms in the metal producing industry are 
active in the high-performance ceramics and high-performance 
composites sectors. The question arises, however, whether this 
involves a detectable R&amp;D project aimed at securing potential 
licensing rights for the company itself in the replacement 
materials sector or whether it actually represents an active 
pursuit of diversified businesses. 
<H5>  3.1.3.2 Foci of materials research in sectors that use </H5>
materials 
  Sectors that use materials may be divided into dynamic and 
less dynamic based on the usage of high-performance materials. 
Characteristic of dynamic sectors that represent the sources of 
impetus for materials research are that, as a rule, they are 
sectors with above-average growth potential in which, at the 
same time, the benefit from the use of high-performance 
materials is so great that, at least in an initial phase, very 
high prices may be paid for them and intensive R&amp;D activities 
can be financed. 
  Additionally, net product in those sectors is comparatively 
large and secondary effects benefiting high-performance 
materials also branch out into other sectors. 
  The combination of the characteristics of dynamic sectors is 
an exception. For good reason, therefore, the application of 
high-performance materials in early stages is concentrated in 
just a few applied sectors wherein a number of those 
characteristics are encountered simultaneously, for example, 
partial sectors of aerospace manufacturing, electronics, 
information engineering, medical engineering, etc. 
  Analysis of the pattern for the dissemination and 
application 
of high-performance materials in the leading industrial 
countries demonstrates that it has to be the responsibility of 
innovative firms in the applied sector to discover this type of 
potential in promising materials applications and together with 
user firms to search out the conditions for success in such 
markets. The innovation strategies of companies in Japan and in 
the U.S. are decidedly typified by this kind of approach. 
  Considering this type of innovation strategy, that primarily 
rests on the impetus of dynamic applied sectors, the sectors 
portfolio of German industry, so far at least, is 
disadvantageous and inadequately balanced. Important sources of 
impetus displaying simultaneously several of the features of 
dynamic sectors are missing on the national level or are only 
insufficiently developed. 
  In terms of the preceding definition there are few dynamic 
sector users of high-performance materials on the national 
level. Materials research activities in industries using 
materials in Germany essentially fall into the following sectors: 


    -  electrical engineering and electronics industry (in 
which dynamic segments of Germany's electronics are only poorly 
represented) 
  -  machine building and 
  -  the automobile industry. 

    On the applications side those sectors heavily impact the 
image of materials research in Germany although they only 
inadequately encompass the indicted features of dynamic sectors. 
Typically in this context, for the most part, we are not dealing 
with sectors with above-average growth. The net product share of 
high-performance materials is comparatively slight there and 
nearly all of those applied sectors in Germany are price 
sensitive which adversely impacts the receptivity for 
highly-developed new materials. Therefore in the FRG the 
situation is typified by the fact that the right "draft horse" 
is missing, that the primary dissemination of high-performance 
on the national level could be more greatly expedited and branch 
out in turn into other sectors from the enduring secondary 
effects. The non-existence of such a "draft horse" in turn has 
repercussions on the long-term competitive position in the less 
dynamic sectors. 
  Typical of R&amp;D activities in the nineties in all sectors 
using materials -- in dynamic and less dynamic sectors alike -- 
will be the following developments: 


    -  Many market segments are impacted by rising costs for 
R&amp;D precisely for materials oriented developments. 
  -  R&amp;D projects will increasingly have to take on an 
international 
and interdisciplinary shape and organization. 
  -  Because of shorter cycles on the product and system levels, 
R&amp;D 
projects will have to be carried out effectively and efficiently. 
  -  R&amp;D projects will have to be implemented with closer 
market 
adherence. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-37A>        Chart 3.4: Selective materials technologies having great importance for developments in </FIG>

  While these developments are equally important for R&amp;D 
responsibilities and R&amp;D management in all applied sectors, 
the 
requirements specific to the sectors and the respectively 
relevant R&amp;D foci for each sector and each market segment 
have 
to be individually formulated. Chart 3.4 synoptically lists the 
most important development objectives for the individual 
sectors. If these sectors are to meet the resulting requirements 
in the future, materials technologies in the automobile, machine 
building and electrical engineering/electronics sectors will 
have to assume a key role. 
  The all-encompassing strategic and operational significance 
of materials and advanced processing technologies is recognized 
in many firms, but so far they have not been extensively 
integrated into the organization of the firm. Daimler-Benz and 
Siemens, for instance, are the few exceptions where the 
materials technology sector is represented at the highest level 
of the corporation and is also correspondingly supported. 
  A greater problem in upcoming years appears to be ensuring 
broader dissemination of high-performance materials into applied 
materials sectors that are not primarily influenced by a few 
large, internationally active firms. In numerous specialized 
branches of machine building, of the precision 
mechanical-optical industry, in the metal producing and 
processing sector and in automobile industry supplier activity, 
high-performance materials have to find intensified application 
in coming years to be able to meet future requirements of the 
specific sectors. In those sectors, however, the requisite 
economic and organizational bases for a broad dissemination are 
still only inadequately realized. 
<H5>  3.1.3.3 Materials research activities in [SME] </H5>
  The difficulties mentioned in the previous section for more 
intensive dissemination of high-performance materials into the 
applied materials sectors apply not only to large firms. In the 
SME group, however, that does indeed play a precursor role in 
the innovation process in other fields, the interest in the 
field of high-performance materials so far is rather restrained, 
with a few exceptions. 
  SMEs here are to be taken to mean all companies that have 
fewer than 1,000 employees and/or less than DM200 million in 
annual turnover. In the processing industries in the FRG that 
are especially important from an R&amp;D perspective, there are 
about 33,500 such companies, based on statistics[.sup]6[/]. 
Nearly 25,000 of those companies engage in R&amp;D, 20,000 of 
them 
on a regular basis and 5,000 irregularly. On average each SME 
invests DM615,000 in R&amp;D. There is no way to telling, 
however, 
how much of this amount is invested in materials research or in 
fields of research with a materials orientation. 
  What is typical of SME R&amp;D activities, however, is that 
they 
address R&amp;D topics that are very proximate to the market and 
that have to guarantee an adequate return on the amounts 
invested in R&amp;D within one to two years. SMEs have less 
interest 
in strategic research projects that are further removed from the 
market since such projects would be a financial strain for them. 
  If the objectives of SMEs are analyzed, two groups of SME 
companies can essentially be distinguished, each of which have 
different foci in the materials research and materials 
application sectors. In this context, the distinction is between 
SMEs as suppliers and SMEs as niche suppliers. 


    -  The first group, SME as suppliers for large companies, 
constitutes an important element of the medium-sized economy. 
Because of their close supplier ties to large firms they are, on 
the one side, frequently directly involved in the development of 
innovative products and therefore also in the materials research 
activities of the large firms. On the other side, because of the 
international competition, large companies depend on the 
medium-sized supplier industry that is close to the customer and 
can act with flexibility, to come up with preliminary innovative 
activities that they initiate, however, only through their own 
R&amp;D activities and are able to bring to serial readiness in 
cooperation with the large firms. 
  -  The second group, SME as niche suppliers, represent another 
form of medium-sized companies, that are predestined, because of 
their customer proximity and flexibility, to stringently sort 
out newly developed technologies and thereby get them 
disseminated into different applied sectors and specialty 
markets. Typically, such medium-sized firms are consistently 
active in market niches that hold no interest for large firms, 
when considering their international volumes. For specialized 
SME, however, they afford interesting market volumes and 
attractive yields. 

    It follows from these remarks that materials research will 
grow in importance during the nineties both for SMEs active as 
suppliers and for companies active as niche suppliers. Up until 
now this potential has still been tapped much too little and 
motivated too little even by the current MATFO program. Future 
support designs even on the federal level should have an 
appropriate toolkit in readiness to intensify the role of SMEs 
as suppliers for heavy industry even in high-tech areas and more 
closely incorporate them in the process of disseminating 
high-performance materials. 
<H5>  3.2 International comparison of materials research support </H5>
  All industrial countries that were included in the analysis 
are very intensively pursuing high-performance materials and 
their processing technologies and providing considerable support 
to materials research in their countries. The reason for this is 
the fact that high-performance materials and their technologies 
are considered critical for the future competitiveness of 
industry and therefore they will have sizable impact on the 
future economic strengths of the respective economies. 
  There is a limited repertoire of support instruments 
available for official support of promising fields of 
technology. All countries employ them in some form or other. To 
what extent any support instrument is used, of course, depends 
directly on the support principles and strategies that the 
respective countries are pursuing. 
  Basically, the following support policy instruments may be 
used by the government for officially supporting and assisting 
R&amp;D: 
  1. regulatory measures to improve the general conditions 
(legislation, authorization and standardization, capital market 
regulations, patent legislation, etc.) 
  2. support of infrastructure services (support of 
information 
and documentation facilities, patent assessment centers, 
technology transfer centers, etc.) 
  3. direct project-related support (project support via 
allocations and applications) 
  4. direct institutional support (support of joint and 
contract research via institutions set up for that purpose) 
  5. indirect support (e.g., tax exemption or advantages). 
  All of the above-mentioned five instruments are employed by 
the respective governments in the materials research sector. In 
this connection, improvement of general conditions is a support 
policy instrument that facilitates and encourages the innovation 
process. Although that instrument has a rather decisive effect 
on the innovation process, it is often not in a specific, 
controllable manner. 
  The remaining four types of support policy instruments are 
used in all the respective countries in the sector of materials 
research. There are no significant differences among the 
individual countries regarding the choice of instruments. Nor is 
it possible to derive from them any different results for 
national development strategies. 
  Even the amount of materials research support in the 
individual countries is not the unqualified decisive factor that 
determines the impact on and clarifies national development 
strategy. On the whole, to be sure, the U.S. supports materials 
research to a considerably greater extent than the countries of 
western Europe or Japan. In the U.S. a much larger share of it 
is allocated to military developments having perceptible effects 
on the civilian technology sector. In any event, however, 
private R&amp;D investments prevail in the case of materials 
developments aimed at civilian markets and official support 
programs only exercise a partial added effect. When comparing 
materials research programs internationally, therefore, it is 
not so much the national programs' support volume that is 
decisive, it is, much rather, the way in which official support 
activities coincide with the R&amp;D investments and innovation 
activities of private actors. Comparatively small national 
support programs are occasionally able therewith to produce 
quite extensive leverage. 
  Even a comparison of the research topics supported in the 
individual countries discloses no significant differences and 
they cannot be adduced to explain the different developments in 
the individual countries. During the eighties, all countries, 
more or less, supported the same fields of technology considered 
attractive. Information trips, expert staffs, publications and 
recourse to international consultants sped the dissemination of 
know-how about promising fields and categories of materials. 
Meanwhile, more or less comparable foci for the selection of 
certain categories of materials and R&amp;D topics were 
established 
in all major industrial countries. Against this backdrop, a 
decisive approach to national differentiation is generated only 
through a careful analysis of the way in which the specific 
R&amp;D 
topics in individual countries are incorporated into effective 
national development strategies and how they succeed in 
developing functional, stable networks among research 
facilities, universities, producers and consumers. In this 
context, the variously delineated infrastructure in each country 
particularly impacts national R&amp;D strategies. 
  Therefore, a detailed analysis of the different 
organizational parameters for research and technology policy is 
crucial to understanding the support strategies in the 
individual countries. The amount of the support and the 
selection of research topics is not so decisive, rather it is 
the "approach" to designing and implementing the research and 
its incorporation into strategies and activities of the most 
important participating groups on the national level. To 
understand this "approach" it is important accurately to analyze 
the process cycles and decision-making structures that impact 
materials research support and the efficiency of individual 
projects in the individual countries. 
  Important organizational parameters that typify precisely 
the 
"approach" to research and technology policy in the various 
countries are especially: 
  1. What industries or participating groups are the key 
initiators and active platforms for projects and national 
programs? 
  2. How are goals determined and projects defined and 
coordinated among government, research and industry participants? 
  3. Is there a coherent national industrial policy based on a 
consensus into which the various materials research support 
activities are incorporated? 
  4. To what extent is an integrative policy for coordinating 
different support policy instruments being pursued? 
  5. Does the support policy have an applied orientation and 
is 
it coupled with important national industrial sectors or does it 
rather have a basic orientation? 
  6. Is there targeted focusing on a few priority development 
sectors and projects and which of them are the most important? 
  7. How targeted is the impact of government on management 
and 
decision-making for individual projects and programs? How are 
effective and efficient project and program management 
implemented? 
  On the basis of the indicated questions it is possible to 
distinguish specific basic national patterns. Put simply, 
Japan's industrial R&amp;D policy can be described as an extreme 
type. It can be described by the following features and is 
typified by: 
  1. impetuses from large firms and from the government, 
especially in the information engineering and chemical sectors 
that effectively cooperate on specific projects with government 
offices and competitors 
  2. an interactive process for coordinating information and 
an 
efficient mechanism for goal determination and project definition 
  3. the existence of a coherent national industrial policy 
  4. pursuit of a highly integrative policy 
  5. a predominantly application oriented technology policy 
  6. targeted focusing on strongly growing markets in the 
information engineering sector and in the transportation sector 
  7. comparatively strong influence by government authorities 
on projects and programs. 
  At the other end of the spectrum in past years has been 
Great 
Britain whose research and technology policy has been marked by 
the following features: 
  1. frequently only isolated impetuses from a few large firms 
and researcher groups adhering to no uniform national outlook 
  2. a correspondingly less coherent process for goal 
determination and project definition 
  3. deliberate rejection of a national industrial policy 
  4. implementation of R&amp;D support programs alongside a 
comparatively high number at ministries 
  5. a research and technology policy with a highly basic 
orientation 
  6. the fact that, even though focusing occurred, it was only 
slightly influenced by government decision makers. 
  The other countries that were analyzed fall somewhere 
between 
the Japanese and the British patterns. France and Sweden tend 
more towards the pattern of an active, targeted support and 
industrial policy, while the U.S. and Germany presently are 
trending instead towards a decentralized, less targeted and 
basically oriented pattern of support and industrial policy. 
  Although there are significant differences in the 
organizational features and basic patterns of national support 
strategies, there seems to be a stronger thrust in the direction 
of a more active, targeted and application-oriented support 
policy during the nineties. Budgetary constraints in all 
countries, the increasing cost of new technologies and the 
systems nature of import new technologies increasingly emphasize 
the need for pursuing a more intensely integrative, active and 
targeted technology policy. 
  This assessment applies particularly to future materials 
research and technology support. Some countries appear to be 
especially well prepared for this challenge while others are 
having a hard time reacting to the fresh challenges of 
technology policy. 
<H5>  3.2.1 Materials research support in Japan </H5>
  New technologies and their targeted development and support 
play quite a central part in the modernization and restructuring 
of Japan's economy. Development of the nation's R&amp;D system is 
occurring with a dynamism and commitment unlike in any other 
industrialized country. Targeted support of new technologies by 
the Japanese government plays quite a central role, but it is 
occasionally overestimated abroad and its implementation is 
portrayed distortedly. Official support programs have to be 
constantly viewed in terms of their interaction with R&amp;D 
strategies of Japanese firms, the lead actors in the process of 
change. Official R&amp;D support activities are particularly 
effective when they are entirely targeted and coordinated with 
the R&amp;D strategies of the most important companies, providing 
advantages for them and jointly deriving advantages from them. 
But even in Japan some programs have been colossal flops. These 
most frequently occur when official institutions with their 
limited resources (finances, data) try to "push through" 
technologies and projects contrary to the interests of the chief 
protagonists. 
  National R&amp;D outlays (official and private outlays) in 
1990 
reached a level of Yen13,078 billion (converted, nearly DM163 
billion)[.sup]7[/]. The lion's share of that was privately 
financed R&amp;D; a comparatively smaller amount, declining over 
time, is official R&amp;D allocations. In some fields of 
technology, 
however, rather considerable leverage was realized with that 
comparatively reduced amount. That leverage can be safeguarded 
only by: 


    -  making very targeted use of the limited resources 
  -  more heavily emphasizing market and applied orientation than 
support for basic research 
  -  investing a much higher share of gross social product [GSP] 
than in other industrial countries for non-military R&amp;D 
  -  official and private strategies that are inter-coordinated 
considerably more intensively than in other countries and 
  -  the government's administration having polished and proven 
instruments for project management at its disposal. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-41A>        Chart 3.5: R&amp;D allocations of selective Japanese ministries </FIG>

  Official outlays for R&amp;D in 1990 were about Yen1,921 
billion 
(nearly DM24 billion) and will probably rise to Yen2,300 (nearly 
DM29 billion) in 1992 (see chart 3.5)[.sup]8[/]. The lion's 
share of those outlays, or, 49 percent, went to the national 
education ministry (Monbusho; DM11.2 billion in 1991) followed 
by the Science and Technology Agency (STA; DM6.5 billion = 27 
percent) and the Ministry of International Trade and Industry 
(MITI; DM3.2 billion = 13 percent). 
  Those three institutions are also the principal support 
platforms for materials research in Japan with the following 
"division of labor" resulting there from: 


    -  Monbusho finances and coordinates research and training 
in Japanese universities. 
  -  STA supports general basic research programs as well as basic 
research with an applied orientation and is the financier and 
sponsor of important national research institutes. 
  -  MITI finances and coordinates decisive programs for basic 
research having an applied orientation and research having an 
applied orientation for select broad-spectrum technologies. 
  Chart 3.6 illustrates the collaboration of those three 
institutions. It must be emphasized that none of those three 
institutions explicitly engages in a materials research program, 
as, for instance, is the case for the BMFT's MATFO program. 
Materials research activities are spread over a large number of 
projects. But these are not lumped together under the generic 
term of "materials research." Instead, they are directed at the 
quite specific missions and platform programs of each agency or 
each ministry. Among other things, this leads to the positive 
result that projects are aimed at broad national goals or quite 
specific missions and this facilitates participants' 
identification with program goals. It keeps individual interest 
groups from too lopsidedly sticking with certain scientific or 
technical topics. Technology is always viewed as a means to an 
end and in Japan goals are mostly defined in an economic and 
commercial sense. 
  In Japan, materials research that is supported in various 
initiatives, enjoys top political priority as a "means to an 
end." Materials science and technology are viewed as the key to 
technological innovations in numerous branches of industry and 
in important sectors of public life. For the twenty-first 
century, broad national objectives (energy, environment, 
resources, health, etc.) make it essential to master the new 
materials technologies that even now have to be developed and 
supported in the laboratories. 
  As early as 1987, an official R&amp;D project was created 
for 
materials science and technology, based on the recommendations 
of the Council for Science and Technology, under the leadership 
of the prime minister. Such long-term planning and vision will 
constitute an important basis for the harmonization and 
coordination of the most critical materials research projects in 
the nineties. 
  Crucial to the coordination of the diverse materials 
research 
projects that are spread over a number of ministries and 
agencies, is a multi-layered and data-intensive process of 
creating national objectives and visions. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-42A>        Chart 3.6: Schematic depiction of the structural organization for materials research support in </FIG>

  Chart 3.7 illustrates this process. On the left side, broad 
national objectives are formulated and coordinated while also 
taking into consideration the inclusion of individual ministries 
and administrative units on the project level (see right side). 
What is decisive there, however, is that no planning is involved 
that "fixes in concrete" guidelines that once established may 
later become impracticable and end up losing credibility any 
longer with the participants. Instead, a rolling project is 
involved with the process of goal determination and review 
foremost. Forums, councils and project coordinators are convened 
on a number of levels where the principal know-how platforms and 
decision makers introduce and distill strategic knowledge and 
mutually coordinate project ideas. In this sense, the decision 
making process in Japan is not basically different from the 
cycle in the respective programs in the U.S. and in Europe 
(e.g., for COST or EUREKA). What is typically Japanese, however, 
is the consistency with which the process is pursued. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-43A>        Chart 3.7: Basic ministerial activities for the realization of strategic goals in Japan's </FIG>

  This process of coordination involving broad national 
objectives and the goals of the participants in the projects is 
most consistently implemented by MITI and the administrative 
units under its purview (AIST, NEDO). Materials research 
projects are implemented under three major "missions" or 
programs: 


    -  the "Expansion of New Frontiers for Industry and 
Technology" program 
  -  the "Promotion of Technology Development for Energy Security" 
program and 
  -  the "Promotion of International Cooperation" program. 

    MITI annually invests close to Yen100 billion (nearly DM1.25 
billion, see table 3.5) under those three programs. Matching 
these investments by MITI are sizable supplemental R&amp;D 
allocations by Japanese businesses that invest several orders of 
magnitude more on the part of the private sector in projects 
than Japan's ministry of industry itself. It still needs to be 
emphasized that only a limited, albeit not inconsiderable part, 
goes for materials research in the stricter sense of the term. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-44A>        Table 3.5: Most important MITI programs having greater importance for materials </FIG>

  Table 3.6 contains an itemized list of the most important 
materials research projects under those MITI programs. The 
current projects under the JISEDAI program include: 


    -  High-Performance Ceramics 
  -  High-Performance Materials for Severe Environments 
  -  Photoactive Materials 
  -  Non-Linear Photonic Materials 
  -  Silicon-Based Polymers. 
  At present, under the so-called Large-Scale-Projects and 
under the Moonlight-Projects, the following specific materials 
research projects are being pursued: 


    -  Advanced Material Processing and Machining System 
  -  Advanced Chemical Processing Technology 
  -  Superconducting Technology for Electric Power Apparatus 
  -  Ceramic Gas Turbine Project. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-45A>        Table 3.6: Specific MITI materials research projects </FIG>

  In 1991, with a budget of Yen523 billion (nearly DM6.5 
billion), the Science and Technology Agency [STA], is supporting 
national research centers and programs of a basic research 
nature. Materials research is one of seven select focal sectors 
of the STA and enjoys a correspondingly high priority. The STA 
has created a Council for Aeronautics, Electronics and Advanced 
Technologies that has formulated the following focal fields in 
the materials research sector: research on materials in an 
extreme environment, creation of basically new materials using 
new materials design principles, research in the sector of 
mensuration and quality assurance for new materials, optical 
materials and "smart" materials. The STA is financing and 
coordinating such activities at the National Research Institute 
of Metals [NRIM] and at the National Institute for Research in 
Inorganic Materials [NIRIM]. The following activities enjoy 
prominence at the NRIM: 


    -  new materials using rare metals 
  -  inter-metallic composites having improved resistance in 
heat/water 
  -  new methods of materials design on the basis of new theories 
of 
atomic and molecular structures 
  -  superconducting materials 
  -  "smart" materials. 
  At the NIRIM the following materials research projects are 
being intensively addressed: 


    -  inorganic materials with multiple attributes 
  -  new materials with electrical, magnetic and optical 
properties 
  -  synthetic diamonds, oxidized glassware (especially for use as 
electronic and optical materials) 
  -  ultra-high pressure/temperature materials. 
  Since 1981, the STA has had a Special Coordination Fund for 
Promoting Science and Technology. In 1991, the total budget came 
to Yen10.5 billion (DM131 million). Part of that budget goes for 
materials research projects that are summarized in table 3.7. 
The STA is financing a new program aimed at supporting basic 
research internationally on a cutting-edge level. Under that 
program, Exploratory Research for Advanced Technology [ERATO], 
altogether 17 research topics are being addressed currently at 
newly established research centers. The following of its 
projects can be included in the materials research sector: 


    -  the KIMURA metamelt project 
  -  the KUNITAKE molecular architecture project 
  -  the INABA biophoton project 
  -  the YOSHIDA nano-mechanism project 
  -  the KURODA solid surface project 
  -  the MASUMOTO amorphous and intercalation compounds project 
  -  the OGATA fine polymer project 
  -  the NISHIZAWA perfect crystal project, and 
  -  the YOSHIMURA Electron Materials project. 
  In 1988, STA also launched the Multicore Research Project on 
Superconductivity, with the participation of scientists from the 
NRIM, RIKEN, the national space agency [NASDA], the Japan Atomic 
Energy Research Institute [JAERI], the foundation for Materials 
Science and Technology [MST] and the Research Development 
Corporation of Japan [JRDC]. Foremost in this context are 
activities on the theoretical basis, on the characterization of 
superconducting materials, on process engineering, and on 
technology transfer. 
  Japan's ministry of education [MONBUSHO], with a Yen940 
billion (nearly DM25 billion in 1991) budget, finances 
university research and training. The lion's share of that 
funding goes to maintain the nation's infrastructure. But 
MONBUSHO also engages in rather targeted activities that can be 
directly attributable to the improvement of Japan's materials 
research. These activities included, among others: 


    -  refocusing of the activities of the institute for 
materials research at Tohoku university 
  -  re-establishment of a center for ceramics research at the 
Tokyo 
Institute of Technology 
  -  support for materials researchers under the Scientific 
Research 
Grants. 
  To support select research projects in priority sectors, 
MONBUSHO is spending a total of Yen55.8 billion (DM698 million 
in 1990) to finance the Grants in Aid for Scientific Research. A 
not inconsiderable amount even if this funding goes for 
materials research projects. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-47A>        Table 3.7: Materials research projects under the STA's "Special Coordination Fund for </FIG>

<H5>  3.2.2 Materials research support in the U.S. </H5>
  In 1991 the Council of Competitiveness determined upon five 
groups of key technologies that will heavily impact the future 
competitiveness of America's industry and national security. One 
of those groups includes key technologies in the materials and 
processing technologies sector. On the basis of that study, the 
U.S. administration allocated high priority to materials 
research in the U.S. The U.S. administration launched the 
"Advanced Materials and Processing Program [AMPP]" program 
initiative to give a more targeted focus to materials research 
activities that had been established and implemented in 
uncoordinated fashion in the past inside the individual 
departments and agencies. For the first time this program 
endeavors centrally to coordinate the materials research 
activities and priorities spread out over a number of 
departments and agencies in the U.S. But nothing has changed as 
a result of the AMPP in the basic approach in U.S. materials 
research. It continues to be able to be characterized by the 
following points: 


    -  The U.S. administration determines broad, future 
national goals (e.g., increase in living standards, national 
security, safeguarding of industrial output and economic growth, 
etc.). 
  -  Departments and agencies are assigned missions to realize 
those 
national goals. 
  -  Departments' and agencies' materials research issues are 
oriented exclusively towards their assigned missions. 
  -  For the most part, the materials research topics are 
implemented in the laboratories of the departments and agencies. 
But there is also an awarding out of projects to universities 
and industry. 
  -  Industry may not apply for financing from government sources 
to 
carry out materials research projects reflecting their own 
concepts. 
  -  In the U.S., official materials research support is 
characterized by a consistent top-down process terminating in 
the departments. Bottom-up processes, originating with U.S. 
industry, are not possible. 
  This centralized coordination concept of the AMPP endeavors 
to increase the effectiveness of U.S. materials research while 
simultaneously reducing duplication in developments. In the U.S. 
even the organizational structure and cycle for materials 
research support has changed because of the centralized 
coordination. Chart 3.8 presents the present organizational 
structure including the decision-making groups in the materials 
research sector. 
  The initiative for designing a new "Advanced Materials and 
Processing Program" originated with the U.S. administration that 
is advised on materials research issues by the National Critical 
Material Council [NCMC], the President's Council of Advisors on 
Science and Technology [PCAST] and the Federal Coordinating 
Council for Science and Technology [FCCSET]. Also included on 
issues of research support are the Office of Management and 
Budget [OMB] and the Office of Science and Technology Policy 
[OSTP]. As a result, the following responsibilities attach to 
the individual advisory groups: 


    -  NCMC: the NCMC concerns itself with all sorts of 
materials issues. Official support for materials research 
constitutes a special focus 
  -  PCAST: the PCAST serves as a platform for an ongoing 
clarification of R&amp;D concepts from the private sector and 
academia 
  -  FCCSET: the prime responsibility of the FCCSET is R&amp;D 
coordination in the U.S. It includes all federal authorities 
conducting, supporting or representing R&amp;D 
  -  OMB: the OMB is responsible for all budget issues in the 
materials research support sector 
  -  OSTP: the OSTP's most important responsibility is to assemble 
the R&amp;D activities of the different federal authorities into 
supra-jurisdictional programs. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-49A>        Chart 3.8: Schematic depiction of the structural organization for materials research support in </FIG>

  Under the overall leadership of the OSTP, the advisory 
groups 
indicated above elaborated a basic supra-jurisdictional concept 
for future materials research in the U.S. For a detailed 
organization, the departments (DOC, DOD, DOE, DOI, DOT, DOA and 
HHS) and the agencies (NSF, NASA and EPA) were tasked with 
preparing project proposals for materials research and to submit 
them to an Inter-Agency-Committee for evaluation. On the basis 
of previously established assessment and selection criteria, the 
Inter-Agency-Committee selected some of the proposed projects 
that were technically critical and met the objectives for future 
materials research. The resulting program proposal [AMPP] was 
submitted to Congress for approval. 
  Congress, in turn, is advised on issues of research support 
by the Office for Technology Assessment [OTA] and essentially by 
three independent institutions, that is, the National Academy of 
Science [NAS], the National Academy of Engineering [NAE], the 
Institute of Medicine [IOM] and other groups. Both the members 
of the House of Representatives and of the Senate, under the 
Congress, basically endorse official support for R&amp;D in the 
field of materials technologies. Hence, their concurrence is 
mostly assured. Debates in Congress usually involve the regional 
allocation of the R&amp;D funding to be approved for the country, 
with the representatives pleading for their constituencies. 
After Congress' approval of the program, the program is 
coordinated by the OSTP, FCCSET and Inter-Agency-Committee and 
funding made available to the individual departments and 
agencies for implementing their projects focused on the 
department's mission. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-50A>        Chart 3.9: Planned R&amp;D outlays of individual U.S. departments and agencies under the AMPP </FIG>

  The following goals in the field of materials and processing 
technologies are supposed to be ensured by the AMPP: 


    -  The U.S. is to develop its scientific and technological 
leadership in the materials and processing technologies sector 
vis-a-vis other leading industrial countries. 
  -  Gaps should be closed between development of high-performance 
materials and their cross-over into an application. 
  -  Departments' and agencies' goal attainment is to be 
supported. 
  The U.S. administration is planning to make $1.659 billion 
available in 1992 to realize those goals for materials research. 
For 1993, $1.821 billion is projected, representing a 10 percent 
increase over the previous year's budget. Excluded from that 
total are U.S. classified projects and some mission-oriented 
activities like the Superconducting Supercollider-Program and 
the U.S. space glider program. 
  Funding planned for 1993 should be allocated among the 
individual departments and agencies as in chart 3.9. 
Significantly, in this context, the DOE will gain in importance 
at the expense of the DOD. The remaining departments and 
agencies matter less for U.S. materials research. Described in 
detail below are the activities of the five most important 
departments and agencies in the U.S. in the materials research 
sector. Hence, a closer look will be taken, in particular, of 
(1) the Department of Energy [DOE], (2) the Department of 
Defense [DOD], (3) the National Science Foundation [NSF], (4) 
the National Aeronautics and Space Administration [NASA] and (5) 
the Department of Commerce [DOC]. 
<H5>  1. The Department of Energy [DOE] </H5>
  The Department of Energy is engaged in the materials 
research 
sector focusing on materials issues connected with energy 
technology (nuclear and non-nuclear energy sources). The DOE's 
R&amp;D projects includes the following subjects: 


    -  basic research (e.g., elementary particle research) and 
the construction of accelerators (Superconducting Supercollider) 
  -  application-oriented basic research (e.g., synthesis and 
processing of materials for photovoltaic applications) 
  -  Subjects from the R&amp;D applied orientation sector (e.g., 
large-scale developments in the energy technologies sector). 
  The DOE's R&amp;D projects are assigned to the U.S.'s 
national 
laboratories, universities or directly to industry and conducted 
in those locations. Cooperation among official, academic, and 
industrial researchers is desired and encouraged. 
<H5>  2. The Department of Defense [DOD] </H5>
  The Department of Defense is engaged in the materials 
research sector not only with the use of materials in the 
military sector but also with civilian materials applications 
that extend the technological envelope and contribute to the 
technological superiority of the U.S. 
  In this way, the U.S. is the only industrialized nation that 
finances out of its defense budget R&amp;D projects that has a 
broad 
impact in the civilian technology sector. 
  Research projects range from free basic research through 
basic research having an applied orientation and applied 
research all the way up to specific development projects aimed 
at realizing prototypes or concrete production techniques. 
  R&amp;D that is on the point of application is normally 
conducted 
in the form of consortium research with the backing of the DOD. 
For this purpose a consortium of producers, users, and research 
institutes is formed with the goal of developing or improving a 
prototype and relevant production technologies (e.g., 
semi-conductor components). 
  DOD's R&amp;D projects in the materials research sector 
are, for 
the most part, conducted in the large national research 
laboratories, at universities or they are farmed out to 
industrial firms. An attempt is made to encourage cooperation 
among official, academic, and industrial researchers. 
<H5>  3. The National Science Foundation </H5>
  The NSF is an independent federal facility that is supposed 
to support research and training in the natural and social 
sciences, in mathematics and engineering. The training of 
materials scientists and engineers is especially supported in 
the materials research sector. The NSF's foci are exclusively of 
a basic orientation and are concentrated in the following fields: 


    -  solid-state physics 
  -  solid-state chemistry 
  -  low-temperature physics 
  -  theory of condensed matter 
  -  metallurgy 
  -  polymers 
  -  ceramics 
  -  electronic materials 
  -  support for supplies of the relevant equipment 
  The NSF supports inter-disciplinary oriented projects at 
universities, private research facilities, or industrial 
laboratories. 
<H5>  4. The National Aeronautics and Space Administration [NASA] </H5>
  NASA is engaged in the materials research sector with 
materials subjects and applications in air- and spacecraft. 
Materials research is supposed to contribute its share to 
enabling the U.S.'s overall supremacy in space to be maintained 
and developed. 
  NASA's R&amp;D projects are carried out in its own 16 
R&amp;D centers 
and technical facilities or farmed out to universities and 
industrial laboratories. 
  The larger NASA research centers with their own materials 
research foci, for example, are: 


    -  the Goddard Space Flight Center in Maryland 
  -  the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, California 
  -  the Lyndon B. Johnson Space Center in Houston, Texas 
  -  the John F. Kennedy Space Center in Florida 
  -  the Langley Research Center in Virginia. 
  It is worth noting that NASA is the only American federal 
authority that cooperates very heavily with research institutes 
or with industrial firms in the implementation of its R&amp;D 
activities. NASA uses 25 percent of its budget on its own R&amp;D 
activities and 75 percent of its budget is farmed out to outside 
contractors. 
<H5>  5. The Department of Commerce [DOC] </H5>
  The DOC has concentrated its materials research activities 
at 
the National Institute of Standards and Technology [NIST]. 
NIST's prime responsibilities are to assist industry in: 


    -  the development of technologies 
  -  the improvement of product quality 
  -  the modernization of production techniques 
  -  and the speedy commercialization of inventions. 
  The focus of the R&amp;D projects supported by NIST consist 
of 
risky technologies in a precompetitive stage. In this way new 
products and production methods are supposed to be realized 
leading to an expectation of high productivity and market 
potential. 
  Considering the allocation of AMPP financial resources by 
categories of materials (chart 3.10), it turns out that all 
categories of materials--except for magnetic materials--are 
steadily supported very intensively. Particularly prominent is 
the intensive support for biocompatible materials. 
  If the individual groups of materials are sorted into 
function and structural materials, it becomes evident that under 
the AMPP functional materials get more attention than structural 
materials. In 1992 functional materials will probably be 
supported with $634.6 million, but structural materials, on the 
other hand, with $608.9 million. Also, some projects included 
here among structural materials really belong under functional 
materials. The program's structure, however, precludes detailed 
analysis of the support for functional materials. 
  The AMPP comprises five program foci for which funding is 
allocated: 
  1. synthesis and advanced processing of materials - 41 
percent 
  2. characteristics of materials - 29 percent 
  3. theory, modeling and simulation - 14 percent 
  4. training and professionalization - 1 percent 
  5. other - 15 percent 
  With percentages of 41 and 29 percent, synthesis and 
advanced 
processing of materials and characteristics of materials, by 
far, have the greatest importance among those program foci. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-52A>        Chart 3.10: R&amp;D outlays for specific materials under the AMPP program </FIG>

<H5>  3.2.3 Materials research support in European research </H5>
programs 
<H5>  3.2.3.1 Survey </H5>
  In the seventies and eighties the economy in west European 
countries underwent a sizable structural change that went hand 
in hand with increasingly heavier emphasis on the potential of 
research and technology. In fact, it has become increasingly 
essential to achieve a high degree of excellence on the European 
level in order to safeguard the status of technological 
development and international competitiveness vis-a-vis the U.S. 
and Japan. When the EC treaty was reformed in 1987, this 
assessment led to the formulation and creation of an independent 
Community research and technology policy. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-53A>        Table 3.8: Foci of EC research support in the third framework program </FIG>

  While the EC's original medium-term framework program for 
1984-1987, prior to the reform of the EC treaty, was still 
heavily influenced by "traditional" political fields and mostly 
featured research on steel, energy and agriculture, the second 
framework program for 1987-1991 underwent more of an orientation 
towards high-tech sectors like information and communications 
technologies, bio-sciences and materials research. 
  Altogether, under the second EC , ECU5.4 billion were 
allocated between 1987 and 1991. Of that amount, ECU3.1 billion 
alone went for information technologies and for industrial 
modernization. Within the industrial modernization focus nearly 
ECU265 million went for support for materials technologies. 
  In connection with the current third for 1990-1994, there 
has 
been an even more intensive orientation towards three foci of 
Europe's research and technology policy: 1. basic technologies, 
2. use of natural resources and 3. use of non-physical resources 
(see the survey in table 3.8). Under support for basic 
technologies, ECU888 million is allocated for the industrial and 
materials technologies sector. Altogether, between 1990 and 
1994, an amount of ECU309 million in funding will be allocated 
for materials research, narrowly defined[.sup]9[/]. 
  With the Maastricht Treaty for the creation of the European 
economic and currency union, basic impetuses have been generated 
since late 1991 for the continued development of Europe's 
research and technology policy. 
  In the fourth beginning in 1994, the relationship between 
national and European policy will be fundamentally reworked. New 
responsibilities will accrue to the EC Commission in the sector 
of industrial and research policy and a considerable expansion 
of support activities on the EC level can be expected. 
  Besides the EC's research and technology policy programs in 
which non-EC countries participate with the EC based on 
bilateral agreements, other programs and initiatives are being 
conducted on the European level in which non-EC members also 
could participate. In this connection, the COST and EUREKA 
initiatives deserve special mention since they display important 
foci in the materials research sector. Sections 3.2.3.3 and 
3.2.3.4 describe those initiatives and the materials engineering 
projects engendered by them. 
<H5>  3.2.3.2 The BRITE/EURAM program </H5>
  In 1985 and 1986, the BRITE and EURAM programs were 
introduced as separate programs for different target groups, 
respectively. Both programs emphasized support for materials 
research, albeit with respectively different focuses and 
emphases. EURAM gave greater emphasis to materials research 
while BRITE gave greater prominence to process development 
(production, CAD/CAM, Design). 
  In 1989/1990, the two programs underwent a radical 
evaluation 
and correspondingly adapted and reoriented. To be sure, the 
assessment of the original EURAM program favorably determined 
that in many cases it resulted in the initiation of cooperative 
activities among partners from many countries, to super-sectoral 
cooperation, to an enhancement of cooperative activities between 
producers and consumers and to the development of so-called 
thematic excellence networks,[.sup]10[/], facilitating a 
permanently enhanced division of labor and competitiveness in 
Europe. The following points, however, were signaled out for 
criticism: 


    -  there was no clear strategy on the EC level furnishing 
sufficiently clear medium- and long-term project concepts 
  -  there were no clear priorities for project selection 
  -  the result was a disadvantageous focusing on universities and 
research institute 
  -  a disadvantageous distribution of participants among the 
various countries of Europe had to be noted 
  -  the "High-Tech Materials" program too lopsidedly supported 
traditional materials at the expense of improvement 
  -  and the rather considerable problems in the administrative 
implementation of the projects surfaced. 
  The assessment also especially pointed out success factors 
for projects. Those include: 


    -  the clear determination of project goals and the 
availability of the necessary funding to realize those goals 
(finances, technical equipment, etc.) 
  -  the proven expertise of 
each of the participating partners and the complementarity of 
qualifications 
  -  the quality of the administrative and informational support 
by 
the EC Commission ("Monitoring and guidance") and efficient 
management of the combined project by the project leader 
  -  the participation of at least one end user from industry as 
an 
active member of the project team 
  The recommendations from the assessment and the analysis of 
the success factors for projects went into the shaping of the 
BRITE/EURAM II program under the EC's third . Both programs were 
combined under a uniform objective and uniform program 
supervision and administration. Compared with the original 
BRITE/EURAM programs, funding was considerably beefed up for the 
September 1991 to December 1994 time period. All told, ECU309 
million are available for that period for materials research, 
including exploration and recycling. The survey in table 3.9 
indicates the supported sectors. As a result, the BRITE/EURAM II 
program is very comprehensive in terms of categories of 
materials that are supported and net product stages. For 
example, even developments in follow-on activities (production, 
process engineering, design, quality assurance) are supported. 
  The BRITE/EURAM II program is touted in technical interviews 
with representatives from industry, research and management as a 
program that is portrayed as being of above-average efficiency 
compared to other EC and supra-national programs. Mentioned as 
the reason for this is the restriction to a few project partners 
chosen for their competence, targeted project selection, 
responsible program management and the fact that lessons from 
precursor programs were in a number of stages. 
  BRITE/EURAM emphasizes the variously committed participation 
of the EC partner countries. This is influenced by the economic 
strength of the country, by existing competence in the materials 
engineering sector, by the experience from participation in 
earlier BRITE/EURAM programs and by the support strategies for 
materials research in the participating countries. Relative to 
return on funding, Great Britain and France especially were 
heavily represented in BRITE/EURAM up to 1991. By way of 
contrast, partners from the FRG participated to a lesser extent 
in the BRITE/EURAM program up to and through 1991. With the 
enhancement of the activities of the German contact center for 
the BRITE/EURAM program, however, German applicants were able to 
catch up with applicants from France and Great Britain at the 
first call for BRITE/EURAM II in 1992. 
  The initially low participation by German participants in 
the 
BRITE/EURAM program was determined, among other things, by the 
availability of alternative support funding. In the 
decision-making calculation of potential applicants, the 
national MATFO program was considered to be more attractive 
compared to the EC program since it was characterized by clearer 
guidelines and colored by lower coordinating costs. The 
similarity of objectives and support instruments between MATFO 
and BRITE/EURAM, and the fact that BRITE/EURAM, even after 1994 
will probably achieve a high status, makes it necessary to more 
closely examine the issue of coordination between national and 
European support policy. Even more effective coordination, 
however, should be viewed against the background of national and 
European materials research programs that are concurrent and 
complementary to one another (see chapter 5 on this). 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-56A>        Table 3.9: Support sectors under the BRITE/EURAM II program </FIG>

<H5>  3.2.3.3 The COST initiative </H5>
  The COST initiative (abbreviation for Cooperation europeenne 
dans le domaine de la recherche scientifique et technique) 
constitutes one of the earliest activities for coordinating 
scientific and technical projects on the European level. At the 
end of the sixties the initiative for this cooperation 
originated with the then six members of the European Economic 
Community [EEC], but it was subsequently deliberately not 
limited only to EC member states and even now is still an 
initiative outside of the EC . 
  In November 1971, The research ministers of 19 European 
countries [.sup]11[/], at a conference in Brussels, decided 
to conduct jointly coordinated research support in seven select 
fields: 1. computerization, 2. telecommunications, 3. 
transportation, 4. oceanography, 5. metallurgy and materials 
science, 6. environmental protection and 7. meteorology. From 
the outset, joint research in the materials engineering sector 
(see table 3.10) was given relatively high importance, not only 
because it was selected as one of the seven foci, but also 
because it is evident that materials developments frequently 
play a key role even in the other indicated six fields. 
  Financial support for R&amp;D projects remains with the 
national 
governments. There is no supra-national support budget. The 
initiative proceeds "from the bottom up," that is, from 
researchers on the national level. These may join up with 
researchers from other countries participating in COST. If a 
project is initiated by participants from at least four European 
countries, this can then become the basis for a COST action. 
COST projects and actions are coordinated on the European level 
by a number of oversight and steering groups (committee of 
higher officials, COST actions management committee, combined 
projects coordinators). To facilitate coordination and 
information exchange, projects with a similar objective and 
thematic are combined into "concerted actions" and technical 
subgroups. 
  Altogether, under the COST initiative, more than 800 
projects 
were implemented in eight action sectors entailing a budget of 
ECU156 million. At the start of 1991, 82 of those projects were 
still being worked on. 
  The COST initiative is highly supplemental both to national 
support programs and to EC programs. The COST initiative was and 
is administratively and financially supported by the EC 
Commission. This is based on a resolution of the EC Council of 
Ministers and was confirmed by the vice-chairs of the EC 
Commission at the meeting of the research ministers from COST 
member countries in Vienna on 21 November 1991 for COST's 
twentieth anniversary. On the level of specialization, COST 
concerted actions are comparable to BRITE/EURAM individual 
combined projects. Reciprocal information on current and planned 
materials programs and actions has occurred at regular intervals 
since 1988. 
  Nothwithstanding the close coordination between COST 
programs/actions and EC programs, there is no denying some 
replacement that is especially intensified in so far as the EC 
gains in importance relative to the COST initiative. The 
following three phases can be distinguished in the relationship 
between EC programs and COST initiatives. In the phase preceding 
the first EC , between 1971 and 1983, COST still constituted an 
important "platform" for joint European R&amp;D activities; 
between 
1984 and 1992, important topics began competing with individual 
R&amp;D support programs on the EC level. In that phase, firms 
and 
institutes in European Free Trade Association [EFTA] countries 
(CH, S, SF), with no access to EC projects, constituted major 
platforms in the context of COST actions. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-58A>        Table 3.10: Materials research projects under the COST initiative </FIG>

  Then when phase three began on 1 January 1993, countries 
associated with the EEC Treaty got easier access to EC R&amp;D 
support programs. It is therefore questionable how the COST 
initiative will hold up against the European support programs. 
COST initiative competitive advantages, therefore, will have to 
looked for on three levels: 


    -  through rapid, flexible development of new fields of 
research on the part of COST initiators 
  -  through the development of new target groups (e.g., in 
central 
and east Europe) and 
  -  through the mobilization of stable researcher networks set up 
under earlier COST actions. 
<H5>  3.2.3.4 The EUREKA initiative </H5>
  The EUREKA initiative was introduced in 1985 at a conference 
of research ministers from 17 European countries. EUREKA is an 
international framework for S&amp;T cooperation. A market and 
applied orientation is more pronounced compared with other 
support programs and initiatives (e.g., COST). The explicit goal 
is the development of products, processes and services having 
high market potential. For the most part this spotlights highly 
complicated projects that absolutely call for super-sectoral and 
supra-national cooperation (e.g., HDTV, traffic guidance 
engineering, etc.). 
  Since then, 19 signatory states have acceded to the EUREKA 
initiative[.sup]12[/]. In 1992, these introduced a total of 
539 projects with a financial volume of DM21.4 billion. German 
partners participated in 174 of those projects with a financial 
volume totaling DM13.3 billion. German participants had a 
financial volume of DM3.8 billion. The BMFT supported DM933 
million of that. 
  As in the case of COST, project initiation and financing is 
done on the "bottom-up principle," i.e., financing is done in 
the country where the individual contributions originate. The 
initiative mostly originates with individual firms. They look 
for partners from other countries and may apply to their 
national governments for support resources. There is no central 
EUREKA program budget. In clear contradistinction to COST, there 
is only minimal transnational project coordination. 
  The EUREKA "model" offers a pragmatic approach to project 
mobilization, an open framework and a flexible organizational 
structure for initiatives from firms and research institutes. It 
constitutes a new sort of contract model resembling 
"franchising," wherein a number of partners join together under 
a common "brand name." This flexible and open structure made it 
possible to mobilize relatively quickly a large number of 
projects with correspondingly high financial volumes. 
  Even in the materials engineering sector numerous new 
projects were launched. In 1992 there were 53 international 
projects having a financing volume of nearly DM640 million in 
the materials research sector. In 1992, FRG firms and research 
institutes participated in 23 of those projects. Table 3.11 
presents a survey of those EUREKA materials research projects 
that entailed German participation. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-59A>        Table 3.11: Materials research projects entailing German participation under the EUREKA </FIG>

  Of all the cooperative R&amp;D support programs and 
initiatives, 
EUREKA is the one with the least amount of centralization and 
coordination. The underlying principle of self-organization 
facilitates a speedy launching of many new project teams. But 
the question does arise whether that organizational model is 
correspondingly suited for carrying out complex and risky large 
projects all the way to their successful conclusion. The danger 
is that many new activities are "introduced," but because of 
only inadequate central coordination they again disintegrate or 
wither away. 
  The larger and more complicated the development projects 
are, 
the more important does the responsibility of a central 
management become. In individual instances this can be assumed 
by private actors; in other cases, however, it may be 
advantageous to have an official or supra-national authority 
take over the responsibilities for coordination and management 
of the system[.sup]13[/]. 
<H5>  3.2.4 Support for materials research in selected European </H5>
states 
<H5>  3.2.4.1 Great Britain </H5>
  In the fifties and sixties, Great Britain occupied a 
position 
of leadership in the materials engineering sector. During the 
seventies and eighties, however, it had to accept "setbacks" in 
important sectors in comparison with the U.S., Japan, and 
Germany. This was not the least reason why, in the mid-eighties, 
a commission was set up, that formulated national priorities in 
the materials engineering sector and decisively influenced the 
support programs in recent years. 
  Official outlays for R&amp;D in Great Britain total #5.5 
billion 
(DM13.2 billion)[.sup]14[/] (fiscal year 1988-1989). #2 
billion (DM4.8 billion) of that was for the defense ministry 
[MoD], #2.5 billion (DM6 billion) for the so-called Science Base 
and nearly #1 billion (nearly DM2.4 billion) for the financing 
of civilian R&amp;D by different ministries. The lion's share of 
the 
outlays for civilian R&amp;D resides with the Department of Trade 
and Industry (DTI/total #314 million). The DTI finances and 
coordinates the most important materials research programs in 
Great Britain. Besides the DTI, the Science and Engineering 
Research Council [SERC], the defense ministry [MoD], the energy 
ministry [MoE], the transportation ministry [MoT] and the health 
ministry [MoH] participate in the implementation of projects of 
relevance to materials research. 
  Optimistically estimated, Great Britain's official outlays 
for materials research are on the order of #70-80 million 
(DM168-192 million) per year. These are apportioned in a ration 
of 3:3:2 among the DTI, MoD and SERC and/or Department of 
Education and Science [DES]. Based on DTI data, the outlays 
going for R&amp;D on new products, in the narrow sense of the 
term, 
are definitely fewer. On an annual basis, the programs of 
section MTD 2 (Materials and Manufacturing Processes) get #10 
million (DM24 million). There are also materials research 
related R&amp;D projects in the electronics as well as the 
aerospace 
sectors. Altogether, the DTI budget for new materials is more on 
the order of #20 million (DM48 million) per year. 
  Under the DTI budget, the following programs are 
implemented, 
each of which is responsible for a large share of the R&amp;D 
projects in the new materials sector: 


    -  LINK 
  -  General Industrial Collaborative Programme [GICP] 
  -  Advanced Technology Programme [ATP] 
  -  Measurement Technology Support [MTS] 
  LINK aims at cooperative projects involving private firms, 
research institutions and universities in the sector of 
precompetitive research holding considerable relevance for 
industrial application. Altogether, for the current fiscal year 
(1991-1992) it is estimated at 75 projects, 280 participants and 
a budget of #50 million (DM120 million). Only a part of that, 
however, is for materials research projects as such. In the LINK 
program, universities are 100 percent supported, industrial 
outfits, a maximum 50 percent. Average support volumes amount to 
#0.3-0.5 million (DM0.7-1.2 million) and the typical duration of 
a LINK project is four to five years. 
  The GICP is aimed at support of industrial research 
organizations. In 1992-1992, 50 projects are financed under this 
program with a budget of #25 million (DM60 million). 
  The ATP targets cooperation between among firms in the 
precompetitive R&amp;D sector in key fields of technology. All 
told, 
in 1991-1992, 60 projects involving 250 participants and a 
budget of #50 million (DM120 million) are supported. 
  Lastly, MTS is a support program targeting measurement and 
technical testing methods for new materials. 
  DTI is Britain's coordination center for EUREKA projects. 
These aim at industry-led combined projects for the improvement 
of the competitive position of European firms (see section 
3.2.3.4 also on this topic). In 1991-1992, Great Britain was 
participating in 35 EUREKA projects entailing a support volume 
of #60 million (DM144 million). The British attribute especially 
great importance to participation in EUREKA materials research 
projects. 
  In addition to support from the DTI, materials research is 
supported at universities and research facilities by the DES and 
SERC. The establishment of Interdisciplinary Research Centers 
[IRC] aroused special attention in recent years. The goal they 
pursued was to develop centers of expertise in many new fields 
of promising research, that as a rule are set up in the vicinity 
of a renowned university and are supposed to cooperate closely 
with industrial firms. 
  Actually, a number of IRCs were developed in the new 
materials sector (see table 3.12): high-temperature 
super-conductivity in Cambridge and Birmingham, high-performance 
materials in Birmingham, polymer research in Leeds, biomaterials 
at Queen Mary College, etc. 
  Initial experiences with the development of the IRCs appear 
to be mixed. Some centers (e.g., polymer research in Leeds) have 
already acquired sufficient impetus and a high reputation early 
on. Others still have not fulfilled the expectations pinned on 
them. For example, the center for Advanced Engineering Design in 
Glasgow has been re-closed. Critical factors in the success of 
IRCs are: careful selection of management forces, clear and 
early coordination of goals among management, SERC and industry 
and the quickest possible development of a high reputation 
through sensational benchmark projects. 
  Also deserving emphasis as the third leg of materials 
research in Great Britain is the not inconsiderable allocations 
of the MoD, militarily oriented research institutions (e.g., 
RAE) and the largest armaments firms. The impetus for innovation 
in the development of new materials for civilian applications, 
however, that they engender is considered to be comparatively 
slight. 



  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Table 3.12: Interdisciplinary Research Councils [IRCs] in the new material-| 
|s sector                                                                   | 
----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
