----------------------------------------------------------------------------- 


  In Great Britain (unlike in the U.S., for instance), really 
cutting-edge military developments are pursued mostly only in 
the electronics, signals processing and radar engineering 
sectors, fewer, however, in new materials. Large military 
supplier firms occasionally emphasize that they do in fact use 
new materials but they do not develop those themselves but 
purchase them instead. 
  On the whole, Britain's materials research is characterized 
by a large number of initiatives and support agencies. This 
occasionally hampers coordination of the different programs. 
Advantageous in this regard is the activity of the Materials 
Advisory Committee. The latter consists of R&amp;D directors from 
industrial outfits. It meets four times a year and advises on 
strategic issues and the selection of important materials 
research projects. The secretariat for this committee is located 
at the DTI, and a high-ranking industry representative chairs 
it. Since materials research activities are scattered over 
different programs and support agencies, the Materials Advisory 
Committee plays an important advisory and information exchange 
role in considering broad national interests. 
  Despite this extra responsibility of the Materials Advisory 
Committee and the fact that all strands of industry-oriented 
national and European projects converge on the DTI, Britain's 
support policy for new materials is shot through with a high 
degree of decentralization and occasional fragmentation. Many 
competing programs on the national and European levels are 
overseen by relatively few officials with only unclearly defined 
objectives and priorities. A single DTI employee is responsible 
for nearly 100-150 projects. Project management remains nearly 
exclusively with the participating firms and research 
facilities. The support institutions can scarcely play any 
coordinating role on individual projects. 
  The driving forces for national materials research support 
are situated instead on a decentralized level (with individual 
industrial outfits and research groups). National support policy 
is a desideratum of spontaneous "bottom-up processes." The 
upshot is that this makes it possible for lopsided interests to 
intrude with unproportional strength. Certain industrial firms 
with well-developed channels of information to official agencies 
and individual groups from universities and research 
institutions are thus better poised than others. 
  In the sector of applied materials research, some groups 
from 
well-organized branches (e.g., aerospace, automobile 
manufacturing) enjoy distinctly better influence over the 
direction of national programs than others. Accordingly, in the 
basic research sector topics are occasionally formulated that 
arouse the eagerness of researchers but do not necessarily 
address actually existing national research expertise or do not 
find the right fertile industrial soil for their later 
commercial implementation. 
  The result is a "Mismatch" between the research portfolio 
and 
the portfolio of national industries and business fields in 
which critical firms actually have long-term, sustainable 
competitive advantages. Meanwhile, a number of authors have 
noted this inadequate correspondence between research priorities 
and sectors of the national economy. 
<H5>  3.2.4.2 France </H5>
  France is pursuing a type of research and industrial policy 
that resembles Japan's approach in many respects albeit 
significant differences to it are also evident. The most 
important players are the large firms and central government 
administrations that use a tightly interlaced network of 
personnel and capital to coordinate and implement activities 
that are national in their scope. In clear contradistinction to 
Japan, however, is France's industrial policy that is 
characterized by top-down planning, the influence of the 
government as shareholder and inadequate competition among large 
firms. 
  This industrial and political structure benefits 
technological development in France wherever there are large 
technological systems to implement, requiring sophisticated 
coordination among many participants and marked by a high degree 
of official regulation. Accordingly, France's policy displays 
great effectiveness in the implementation of large national 
systems in the telecommunications, transportation, space, energy 
and military sectors. 
  On the other hand, France's technological development is 
often riddled with conspicuous flaws precisely in those sectors 
in which large systems and government regulation have no 
importance for the innovation process. In sectors like machine 
building, the capital goods industry and in many markedly 
medium-sized supplier branches, that is, in which the 
significance of self dynamism, spontaneous entrepreneurship and 
bottom-up processes prevail, there are often pronounced 
shortcomings in France. 
  During the eighties, France strongly promoted important 
materials research developments in the context of a support 
policy directed at large structures. Prestigious national 
developments in the military, space travel, nuclear energy and 
civil aviation sectors led to the targeted development and 
adaptation of strategic new materials. Subsequently, extensive 
effects for impetus and dissemination were expected from them. 
The ideal type of dissemination pattern that was originally 
pursued envisioned specific new materials (e.g., composite 
materials) being tested first in the space sector, then being 
incorporated in fighter aircraft construction and in civilian 
aircraft and then transferred to the entire transportation chain 
(high-speed trains, automobiles). In order to be appropriately 
equipped for that dissemination process, there was constant 
development of capacities in the research and materials 
production sector. 
  Over the past decade in France a number of research projects 
and support programs were initiated in the materials research 
sector. The most important ministries in this context are: 


    -  the Ministere de la Recherche et de la Technologie [MRT] 
  -  the Ministere de l'Industrie 
  -  the Ministere de la Defense 
  -  the Ministere de l'Energie 
  The MRT is responsible not only for basic research but 
especially for the national research center [CNRS]. The MRT 
primarily implements the major support programs supporting key 
national sectors (space, aviation, telecommunications and 
energy) where materials research is of critical importance. In 
addition, MRT supports R&amp;D of relevance to industry under the 
"Sauts technologiques" (technological leaps) focus and supports 
innovation and technology transfer. 
  In the development of materials research in France, the 
Centre National de la Recherche Scientifique [CNRS] enjoys a 
rather crucial role. It has close to 300 laboratories throughout 
France that are directly or indirectly engaged in material 
research issues. The CNRS allocates a total budget of nearly 
FF800 million[.sup]15[/] (DM240 million) for materials 
research. PIRMAT (Programme interdisciplinaire de recherche sur 
les materiaux) is the most important program in the materials 
research sector overseen by the CNRS. 
  The defense ministry (Ministere de la Defense) finances 
materials engineering developments in the aerospace industry 
sector. Nearly FF350 million (DM105 million) are allocated 
annually to materials developments focusing on the composite 
materials, high-performance metals, and high-performance 
ceramics sectors. 
  The Ministere de l"Energie oversees its own materials 
research program that is directed, among other things, at the 
development of high-performance ceramics for the nuclear 
industry. 
  In addition to such "mission oriented" materials research 
programs focused on basic research, aerospace, defense and 
energy, in recent years intensified dissemination-oriented 
activities were launched. Those include, among others, the CRITT 
and ANVAR programs, both financed by the MRT. Under the CRITT 
program a total of 130 regional innovation and technology 
transfer centers were developed. Twenty-nine of those centers 
explicitly are engaged in materials engineering developments. 
Their foci are in the polymers sector (eight centers) and the 
composite materials sector (seven centers) as well as the 
ceramics and metallic materials sectors (three centers each). 
  Under the ANVAR program, industrial R&amp;D projects are 50 
percent supported by the MRT. In 1989, under that program, 
projects were officially supported with a support volume of 
nearly FF1,300 million (DM390 million). A not insignificant 
portion (estimated at 10 percent) of that went for materials 
research projects. 
  Despite efforts to help important "prestige developments" 
involving new materials find greater dissemination and use in a 
host of industrial products, so far no real commercial 
breakthroughs are detectable. A very recently conducted study by 
the BETA institute, analyzing the dissemination process for new 
materials in transportation, concluded that the original "Grande 
vision" of the above-depicted dissemination pattern could not be 
realized as of now. The success factors and challenges in the 
manufacture of rail cars and automobiles are so radically 
different from those in space travel and the manufacture of 
aircraft that no sustainable transfer effect has surfaced thus 
far. 
  As a result, in an early stage, France focused its national 
research capacities on a tight cluster of primary applications 
for new materials, but it did not provide with sufficient 
consistency the conditions for success for the commercially more 
interesting waves of secondary applications in strongly growing 
mass markets. 
<H5>  3.2.4.3 The Federal Republic of Germany </H5>
  The FRG's research and technology policy is essentially 
oriented along the following guidelines and general goals: 


    -  acknowledging freedom of research, particularly basic 
research, the need for self-initiative and improvement of basic 
conditions 
  -  consistent orientation along the subsidiary principle, i.e., 
restraining government vis-a-vis R&amp;D in the private sector 
  -  basic recognition of scientific and technical progress as an 
expansion of human opportunities for action 
  -  development of long-term prospects and options for research 
and 
for conceivable technical uses 
  -  enhancement of the joint responsibility of the federation and 
the states for research 
  -  continued development of international cooperation in 
research 
  In recent years, building on the indicated research and 
technology policy guidelines, the following research and support 
policy foci were generated: 
  1. intensified support for basic research 
  2. development of precautionary research (especially, 
ecology, health, climate research) 
  3. subsidiarily focused support of market-oriented 
technologies having a basic orientation and counterbalancing the 
private sector 
  4. improvement of basic conditions for innovations in SMEs 
  5. Actions to improve the research structure and for 
de-bureaucratization 
  6. Enhancement of research fields having long-term prospects 
  7. development and intensification of international 
cooperation 
  8. research and responsible debate on the consequences of 
technology and on science's accountability. 
  In the past, focusing research support on the 
above-indicated 
points, led to the realization of outstanding research results 
in the FRG, compared with the rest of the world, and some of 
those results also spread out into traditional industrial 
sectors. On the other hand, shortcomings surfaced especially in 
R&amp;D on new technologies and associated fields. In that 
setting, 
research support and the realization of research results as well 
as the transfer of results did not manifest the desired effect. 
  In the FRG, materials research support is circumscribed on 
one side by materials research support on the EC level and on 
the other side by materials research support on the FRG states' 
level. The following description of materials research support, 
therefore, must include the following sectors with the last two 
points constituting the focus: 


    -  materials research support on the EC level 
  -  materials research support on the federal level 
  -  materials research support on the FRG states' level 
  Materials research support on the C level has first-rate 
representation in the BRITE/EURAM, COST and EUREKA programs (see 
chapter 3.2.3). Firms and academic research in the FRG are among 
the most active participants, besides the French and the 
English, in the indicated EC programs. Based on future 
availability of resources, materials research on the EC level 
will assume very great importance in the future. 
  Materials research support on the federal level is basically 
concentrated in the BMFT. Besides the BMFT, the federal ministry 
for economy [BMWI] and the federal ministry of defense [BMVg], 
especially, are also active in the materials research sector. 
The BMFT is responsible in the materials research sector for 
both basic research and basic research with an applied 
orientation. The nucleus of the BMFT's materials research 
support is the materials research program that was launched in 
1985 with a 10-year duration. A support total of DM1.1 billion 
was made available for it. The underlying concept of the MATFO 
program is based on the government -- under a predefined 
framework -- making industry and academic research an offer to 
enable the realization of risky, critical research themes in the 
materials sector. The official subsidy for such cooperation is 
50 percent of the project costs. 
  Because of the broad-spectrum nature of materials sciences 
and materials development, support for them is not carried out 
only in the materials research program. Other BMFT support 
initiatives also support issues of relevance to materials, with 
the following activities being the most conspicuous: 


    -  microelectronics 
  -  physical and chemical technologies 
  -  production engineering; quality assurance 
  -  aviation research and engineering; hypersonic technology 
  -  basic technologies for information engineering 
  -  advanced lines of reactors; power plant technologies 
  -  solar energy; broad-spectrum issues of renewable energies 
  -  hydrogen technologies; energy storage device 
  -  ground transportation and traffic systems. 
  Materials research support on the FRG state level is not 
regulated uniformly. Some states, e.g., Bavaria, North 
Rhine-Westphalia and Baden-Wuerttemberg have recognized the 
importance of materials research and have made the transition to 
initiating their own materials research programs that are 
structured similarly to the materials research programs on the 
federal level. 
  In the state of Bavaria, a materials research program was 
launched bearing the designation "New Materials Research 
Program," that is supposed to enhance materials research in 
Bavarian companies. The program has been available to Bavarian 
companies since 1 August 1991. The goal of the program is 
support of R&amp;D projects in the field of new materials and 
their 
conversion into new products. The program primarily supports 
companies with up to 1,000 employees and a maximum of DM200 
million in turnover. 
  Financing of the program is done via funding from the state 
budget with the average amount being redetermined each year. 
Project funding results in an official subsidy of 50 percent for 
the respective project costs, with projects supposed to arise 
from the following materials sectors: 
  1. metals 
  2. polymers 
  3. ceramics/glass 
  4. composite systems 
  5. supra-materials problems. 
  The choice of projects in that context is primarily oriented 
along the following criteria: 


    -  Projects are supposed to display sizable technical and 
economic risk. 
  -  Projects are supposed to feature a high innovation content. 
  -  Projects are supposed to be mostly implemented in the 
Bavarian 
Free State. 
  -  Any subsidized project has to have the participation of at 
least one medium-sized enterprise and one university and/or one 
research institute having an applied orientation. 
  In the state of North Rhine-Westphalia there is a materials 
support program that arose from the steel program in the years 
1980-1990. The goal of the North Rhine-Westphalian materials 
program is R&amp;D support for metallic materials and allied 
composite materials, but especially steel, intermetallic stages 
and superalloys. But processing technologies such as production 
and advanced processing technologies and processing techniques 
(laser and coating techniques) and bonding techniques are also 
supported. An annual budget of nearly DM25 million is planned. 
Currently, implementation of the program for five years is on 
application with the EC. 
  In the state of Baden-Wuerttemberg there is presently no 
specific program for the support of high-performance materials. 
A support program is planned, however, bearing the designation 
of "Opportunities through New Materials." 
  Besides specific materials support programs, in nearly every 
state of the FRG there is an innovation support program in which 
materials research projects are worked on and subsidized to a 
significant extent. 
<H5>  3.3 Materials research at FRG universities and institutes </H5>
  The FRG enjoys a remarkably high level of technical 
development and a long historical tradition of materials 
research. In the past 15 years it was possible to ensure a 
respectable position for German basic research even on an 
international comparison, through new research projects, through 
the development of institutes and through close cooperation 
between research and industry in the area of new 
high-performance materials. 
  The BMFT's materials research program, concurrently with the 
objective of safeguarding German industry's competitiveness and 
the development of industrial research also pursued on a 
priority basis goals that focused especially on German 
universities and institutes: 


    -  mobilization of scientific and technical potential for 
materials research 
  -  development of new materials 
  -  enhancement of basic research with an applied orientation 
  -  improvement of information and technology transfer to benefit 
SMEs 
  Between 1985-1991 a total of nearly DM250 million went 
directly to universities and free research institutes having no 
university linkage, from the support funding of the materials 
research program. Indirectly, in the form of combined projects, 
additional funding was funneled back to universities and 
institutes by industrial partners. To be sure, support funding 
constitutes only a comparatively small amount of the budget for 
all participating institutes and research facilities. Still, the 
MATFO program could generate a sustainable impetus for 
individual institutes with a high percentage of supported 
projects and for selective research topics in the 
high-performance materials sector. 
  Because of the federal training and research policy of the 
FRG, assessment of any federal program also has to be made 
against the backdrop of the activities of the individual states 
that are relevant to materials research and the development of 
state programs. In the development of institutes and research 
facilities in the materials research sector, in fact, there have 
been occasional coordination problems between federal and state 
levels in recent years. 
  This issue will have to be dealt with separately in an 
assessment of the research structure and in the elaboration of 
future strategies for materials research support. 
  German reunification confronts materials research with both 
a 
possible enrichment and, initially, a challenge to the capacity 
for integrating the German research scene. The research 
potential in the field of materials research in the new federal 
states is considerable, albeit there is still a need for 
organization and administrative incorporation into the newly 
emerging field. At the outset, the situation was marked by the 
difficulties of restructuring, and those will probably lead to 
considerable processes of adaptation for a number of years. 
  National expertise in the materials research and engineering 
sector has to be also constantly assessed in terms of the close 
connection between research and training. On the whole, as an 
analysis of basic research, training and professionalization 
systems indicates, the FRG enjoys an internationally sustainable 
to strong position in the metallic materials and polymers 
sector. There is a long tradition here of development of 
competent research institutes and highly developed training and 
close cooperation among universities, research institutes and 
industrial outfits. Existing strengths are parlayed and 
successive improvements realized. 
  This close-meshed network involving research, industry, and 
the educational system still does not function in a 
comparatively effective manner for some new categories of 
materials (in some high-performance ceramics and composite 
materials sectors). Not least because of the research policy, in 
fact, in recent years, individual "islands of competence" were 
developed here. But there has still not been the required 
success in effecting the broadly effective linkage between 
research, training on several levels and the industrial 
activities of application and production firms. 
Materials-oriented support strategies of upcoming years will 
have to more intensively target the development of those types 
of comprehensive networks of expertise and cooperation. 
<H5>  3.3.1 Materials research at selected universities (former </H5>
federal states) 
  German universities display great diversity in the field of 
materials research. Research and training in the materials 
engineering sector play a major role in many universities. 
Appropriate research, entailing respectively different costs, is 
performed at practically every technically oriented university 
or university having departments/areas of specialization in the 
technical and natural sciences. Still, unequivocal foci for the 
research endeavors and pattern of specialization can be 
identified, above all, in the context of individual categories 
of materials. University institutes in which materials research 
is performed to an extent that is of super-region importance, 
are limited to just a few. Various institutes are renowned for 
their relevant expertise and research capabilities in their 
respective research foci, for example, the technical 
universities [TU] and universities of Aachen, Berlin, Clausthal, 
Hamburg-Harburg, and Karlsruhe as well as Bayreuth, Bochum, and 
Erlangen-Nuremberg. Also, know-how relevant to materials was 
concentrated in the various traditional natural science sectors 
at some universities. 
<H5>  Break-down of activities by category of materials </H5>
  Depending on their research foci in the materials research 
sector, the indicated universities may be associated with 
individual categories of materials as follows: in the ceramics 
sector, in the former states of the FRG, there currently are two 
major foci, one at the Institute for Non-Ferrous Materials at 
the Berlin TU, the other under the Karlsruhe/Stuttgart/Freiburg 
ceramics group financed by Baden-Wuerttemberg state. That group 
integrates the Max-Planck institute for Metals Research (see 
section 3.3.3) and the DLR in Stuttgart. With this kind of 
combination of resources, high-level research is performed, 
promoting expert cooperation, and, in a single materials group, 
it is possible for topics to be extensively addressed. Besides 
those foci, a number of German universities enjoy expertise in 
the sector of research and instruction in the field of ceramics 
materials. 
  Research foci in the field of metallic materials are located 
at the RWTH at Aachen, Clausthal TU and Hamburg-Harburg TU as 
well as the universities of Bochum and Stuttgart. Among those, 
it is the RWTH at Aachen that deserves special emphasis with its 
several institutes (foundry institute, laboratory for machine 
tools and operational instruction, institute for welding 
production processes). Mainly because of the intensive 
cooperation with a large number of corporate foundations in the 
context of the university, a relatively sizable linkage with 
industry in Aachen deserves mention. 
  German university polymer research centers are located at 
the 
universities in Bayreuth, Erlangen-Nuremberg, Freiburg, Mainz, 
and Stuttgart as well as at the Berlin TU and the RWTH at Aachen 
where processing technologies for plastics constitute the active 
foci. The university of Erlangen-Nuremberg's chair for plastics 
engineering gets an important impetus for its research activity 
from the close cooperation with the southern German plastics 
center in Wuerzburg which, in turn, is noted for its conspicuous 
orientation towards the interests of the plastics processing 
industry. 
  Composite materials are the least represented category in 
German university research of the categories of materials 
supported under the foci of the materials research program. 
Relevant research projects are being pursued at the Berlin TU, 
the Karlsruhe TU, and the Hamburg-Harburg TU as well as the 
university of Erlangen-Nuremberg. At the university of 
Kaiserslautern, composite materials activities were 
re-established. At those universities, however, composite 
materials are just one research focus among others, respectively. 
<H5>  The MATFO program's role in the universities </H5>
  An analysis of the project funding approved for the various 
institutes under the materials research program is instructive 
about the position of individual universities in Germany's 
materials research scenario. Under the BMFT's materials research 
program, projects entailing a total of DM135 million (cutoff 
date: 31 December 1991) were supported at German universities. 
Our analysis demonstrates that the allocation of funding was 
also highly clustered resembling the concentration of materials 
research activities at certain German universities (see table 
3.13). Heavy participation in the MATFO program by itself cannot 
be assessed as evidence here for the competence of individual 
universities, but it is to be viewed as an important indicator 
of existing capabilities. 
  By far the front runner among the recipient universities is 
the RWTH at Aachen with a support volume of DM33.56 million. 
This is equal to approximately a 25 percent share of total 
university support under the materials research program and 3.7 
percent of the program's total support amount. Next come the 
Berlin TU with DM13.65 million (1.5 percent), Stuttgart 
university with DM12.94 million (1.4 percent), Karlsruhe TU with 
DM10.48 million (1.2 percent), Mainz university with DM7.5 
million (0.8 percent), Hamburg-Harburg with DM5.3 million (0.6 
percent), Dortmund university with DM4.9 million (0.5 percent), 
Clausthal TU with DM4.7 million (0.5 percent), Hannover 
university with DM4.3 million (0.4 percent), Ruhr university at 
Bochum with DM4.2 million (0.4 percent), and Darmstadt technical 
university [TH] with DM3.1 million (0.3 percent). Over the 
entire duration of the program, all other universities end up 
with, at most, less than DM2 million. 
  Under the BMFT's materials research program, projects 
totaling nearly DM135 million were supported. In this context, 
an average support rate of 93 percent was realized. By far the 
lion's share of all university support under the program went to 
institutes in the former states of the FRG. As of the cutoff 
date, universities in the new states of the FRG received a 
promise of support funding totaling DM7.3 million, equivalent to 
a 5.4 percent share of total university support (see also 
section 3.3.5). 
  The leverage produced by the BMFT's materials research 
program on materials research and its continued development at 
German university institutes has to be assessed diversely. In 
the respective budgets, very different significance is assigned 
to support by the BMFT. Major differences first exist for the 
annual budget of the respective institutes. The range here 
extends from DM1 million (Chair for Materials Sciences of the 
Karlsruhe TU) up to DM14 million (Institute for Machine Tools 
and Production Engineering of the Berlin TU) and thus makes such 
a comparison of the respective research performances problematic 
from the outset. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-66A>        Table 3.13: Allocation of support funding among various universities </FIG>

  As a general rule, basic financing by the appropriate states 
comes to between 10-30 percent of the respective budgets. In 
individual instances, because of special state financing, up to 
50 percent is realized (Karlsruhe TU Institute for Technical 
Ceramics, Freiburg University Institute for Macromolecular 
Chemistry). The percentage of BMFT support in total third party 
funding also varies considerably from 10 percent (Freiburg 
University Institute for Macromolecular Chemistry) up to nearly 
50 percent (Hamburg-Harburg TU Chair for Materials Science). 
Therefore, the BMFT's materials research program holds different 
significance for the activity of the respective institutes. In 
any event, however, at some institutes the BMFT's financing 
constitutes the largest budget entry (60 percent of the annual 
budget at the Karlsruhe TU Chair for Materials Science) and 
therefore contributes significantly to the ability of those 
institutes to operate. Still, on the whole it may be estimated 
that the BMFT's materials research program support funding at 
the various institutes of German universities enables an 
additional 100-150 employees to be employed. 
  Support for basic research in the materials sciences sector, 
therefore, has gotten a significant impetus from the BMFT's 
program. To a considerable extent, in fact, it was possible for 
the program's objectives for the universities to be realized. 
There was a mobilization of additional scientific and technical 
potential and an assemblage of those forces that considerably 
advanced, above all, development in selective categories of 
materials such as ceramics and polymers. In all the program's 
foci it was possible for a large number of new materials to be 
produced and characterized in many of the projects supported by 
the BMFT. Basic research with an applied orientation, in 
particular, underwent a significant enhancement from the 
exemplary realization of research groups through inclusion of 
various academic institutes. 
  In terms of organizational structure, however, the 
development of materials research is only in the early stages. 
In the future a more intensive applied linkage needs to be 
realized by including industrial firms and academic research 
institutes in joint projects. 
<H5>  3.3.2 Materials research at the Max-Planck institutes </H5>
  The Max-Planck Society [MPG] maintains its own research 
institutes in various fields of the sciences and the humanities. 
Their activities are predominantly concentrated on basic 
research. The Max-Planck Institutes [MPI] are especially engaged 
in new tasking that is not yet ready for university research or, 
because of its structural requirements (equipment, size of 
institute), is hardly appropriate for it. Therefore the MPG 
deliberately refuses to be active in all scientific disciplines. 
It is more concerned to focus its activities on especially 
promising fields of research. 
  The MPG is mostly financed from public funding, half of it 
coming from the federal government and half from the states. In 
fiscal year 1990, the MPG's budget amounted to DM1.382 billion. 
Revenues are allocated among the following sources of financing: 
the percentage for financing totaled nearly 84 percent of all 
revenues, with 1.25 percent special financing by the states and 
14.75 percent direct project support, equal to DM181 million. 
Non-public grants in 1990 totaled DM23.7 million[.sup]16[/]. 
  The MPG's present 62 institutes and independent research 
groups diverge considerably in terms of their size, structure 
and tasking. They are strewn throughout the FRG. Following 
German unification, meanwhile, even in the new states of the 
FRG, 15 working groups and one institute (MPI for 
microstructural engineering in Halle; see section 3.3.5) were 
set up. There is no independent sector focusing on materials 
research or materials sciences. Standing in its way is the 
expressly basic nature of the research engaged in by the MPG. In 
its diversity, materials research entailing research issues, 
however, is dealt with more extensively under the basic 
disciplines, especially physics and chemistry, which, in turn, 
claim nearly 40 percent of total outlays and have an equally 
large percentage of total scientific personnel employed (status 
in 1990)[.sup]17[/]. 
  The MPG's institutes received a total DM51.34 million of the 
BMFT's materials research program's support funding. Those funds 
went exclusively to five institutes: the MPI for metals research 
in Stuttgart, the MPI for polymers research in Mainz, the MPI 
for solid state research in Stuttgart, the MPI for biophysical 
chemistry in Goettingen and the MPI for research on iron GmbH in 
Duesseldorf (see table 3.14). Hence, the support of the MPI in 
the materials research sector is clearly concentrated on two 
categories of materials: on the high-temperature and specialty 
materials [MHS] branch and the new polymers branch, with 38 
percent and 27 percent of total MPG funding allocated to 
support. Next, in the allocation lineup, come ceramics with 21 
percent and powder metallurgy with 12 percent. The corrosion + 
tribology branch and composite materials, in contrast, each with 
only one percent, are not supported so well. 



  ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
