<H5>  3.3.3 Materials research at the Fraunhofer institutes </H5>
  The Fraunhofer Society's [FhG] 38 institutes conduct R&amp;D 
activities having an applied orientation for the private sector 
and for government agencies. In this context they realize 
contract research and technology transfer activities in 
important fields of technology. The FhG institutes have a total 
of nearly 6,000 employees, about one third of them scientists 
and engineers. As a result, the FhG is the largest organization 
sponsoring applied R&amp;D institutes in the FRG. 
  In the overall activity of the FhG, the principal platform 
has remained unchanged for years. It is the contract research 
activity sector, accounting for 90 percent of total research 
activity. Growth in that sector is attributable, above all, to 
new activities in the layer and surface engineering and medical 
engineering sectors. Total research activity of DM585 million 
(1990) consisted of federal and state contracts worth DM211 
million and others from industry and associations worth DM166 
million. The FhG also implemented combined projects jointly with 
industry that were supported federally and on the state level 
for a total of DM83 million. In 1990, total industrial contract 
research activity amounted to nearly DM250 million[.sup]18[/]. 
  Approximately 25-30 percent of financing the contract 
research activity sector is done with basic financing from which 
investment expenses also have to be paid. Close to 30 percent of 
proceeds also come from private sector contracts. Amounting to 
nearly 35 percent, federal and state project financing helps the 
Fraunhofer institutes in the preparation of the transfer of new 
technologies and in the implementation of systems solutions that 
were realized through institutionally supported precursor 
research. Other proceeds comprise, above all, funding from EC 
Commission support programs. The trend here has been downward 
for some years since, as a rule, a 50 percent support rate has 
been established for EC projects and the Fraunhofer institutes 
[FhI] are only able, to a limited extent, to make good the 
difference for the complete project budget out of the limited 
resources of their own basic financing. 
  Materials research at the Fraunhofer Society's institutes is 
mostly carried out in the specialized sector of 
micro-electronics and in the specialized sector of components 
and materials, each of which unites a number of Fraunhofer 
institutes into a single combine. The following institutes and 
facilities are participants in the "Fraunhofer micro-electronics 
combine": FhI for applied solid-state physics in Freiburg; FhI 
for integrated circuits in Erlangen; FhI for micro-structural 
engineering in Berlin; FhI for solid-state technology in Munich; 
FhI for micro-electronic circuits and systems in Duisburg; FhI 
for physical measurement engineering in Freiburg; FhI for 
production engineering and automation in Stuttgart. 
  In the specialized sector of micro-electronics, the FhG is 
especially involved with the advanced development of production 
engineering for silicon and gallium-arsenide based integrated 
circuits and in the development of user-specific integrated 
circuits [ASIC] and microsystems. Research foci include various 
semiconductor technologies (lithographic process, 
ion-implantation process, process technologies, masking), 
development of components and circuitry (GaAs/GaAlAs components 
and circuits, electro-optical components, liquid crystal display 
elements, light valves) and the layout and production of 
semiconductor equipment (X-ray lithography, metallization, 
silicon-layering, dry-etching). The annual outlay for all 
institutes participating in the specialized sector totals nearly 
DM105 million. The technologically related activities are 
principally of interest to a few large and some medium-size 
manufacturers. On the other hand, ASIC developments and the 
tools required for them serve extensively to support all 
branches of industry in the use of micro-electronics. 
  The FhG's materials research activities focus, however, is 
unmistakably in the sector of materials and components. With an 
annual cost of nearly DM85 million, that sector ranks third 
among Fraunhofer specialized sectors and comprises the following 
institutes and facilities: FhI for materials mechanics in 
Freiburg; FhI for applied materials research in Bremen; FhI for 
non-destructive testing process in Saarbruecken; FhI for 
operational resistance in Darmstadt; FhI for short-term dynamics 
in Freiburg; Fraunhofer research groups for hydroacoustics in 
Ottobrunn; FhI for silicate research in Wuerzburg; FhI for 
lamination and surface engineering in Braunschweig; Fraunhofer 
working group for wood research in Braunschweig; FhI for 
production technology in Aachen. 
  The research activities of the specialized sector of 
materials and components in which those institutes cooperate, 
aim for an optimum, constructive orientation for materials, good 
useful features, the development of economical production and 
processing procedures and, increasingly, consideration of 
ecological aspects. The fundamental prerequisite for realizing 
such objectives is the characterization of materials and 
component properties, chiefly employing operational resistance, 
fracture mechanics, and non-destructive testing processes for 
that purpose. 
  The most significant research foci for materials research of 
the FhG's specialized sector of materials and components involve 
materials development (materials for severe stress, 
high-temperature and composite materials, non-ferrous, inorganic 
materials and inorganic-organic polymers, new functional and 
structural materials plus coatings, sensors and catalysts, 
production of nano-crystal and amorphous powder, development of 
new metallic and polymer-like laminated materials), materials 
characterization (functional, mechanical-technological 
properties, correlation with microscopic properties, definition 
of structure, advanced and fresh development of testing 
processes) and operational resistance of materials (component 
optimization, computation and simulation, lifetime and defect 
analyses). 
  The FhG has especially focused its activity on the 
production 
and use of highly promising ceramic materials. The production 
and preparation of high-performance ceramics call for 
cooperation that transcends specialization. 
  For this reason a number of institutes have joined together 
in the Fraunhofer combine for high-performance ceramics and in 
this way created a special expertise that ranges from 
development of new production processes to quality assurance 
through special testing process at all stages of the net product 
chain (participating institutes: FhI for materials mechanics in 
Freiburg, FhI for applied materials research in Bremen, FhI for 
non-destructive testing processes in Saarbruecken, FhI for 
operational resistance in Darmstadt, FhI for silicate research 
in Wuerzburg, FhI for production technology in Aachen, the FhI 
being developed in Dresden for ceramics technology and sintered 
materials will further expand that expertise in the future). 
Steadily increasing importance is attributed to the cooperation 
of the various FhI and the transfer of internal know-how. In 
this connection even the linkage with the specialized sector of 
production technologies is especially increasing. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-69A>        Table 3.15: Distribution of MATFO projects among the Fraunhofer Society's </FIG>

  The Fraunhofer institutes' special expertise in the field of 
highly promising ceramics is also reflected in the participation 
in the BMFT's materials research program (see table 3.15). 
Altogether, under that program, the Fraunhofer society is 
supported with DM29.6 million allocated among 10 different 
institutes. More than half, that is, 53 percent of that support 
goes to the ceramics sector. Following by a wide margin are the 
metallic high-temperature and specialty materials [MHS] branch 
with 19 percent and the composite materials branch with 18 
percent. Other sectors received hardly any support (powder 
metallurgy with six percent and corrosion + tribology with four 
percent) or no support (new polymers). 
  Based on their exceptional importance for the processing 
industry, metallic materials splay the major role in the 
contract research of the participating Fraunhofer institutes. A 
significant share of the activities continues to involve the use 
of new materials, above all, metallic specialty materials, 
ceramics and composite materials. Moreover, important 
developments target the production of new laminated systems with 
customized properties. 
<H5>  Large research facilities' [GFE] activities in the materials </H5>
research sector 
  The 16 large research facilities (three of them in the new 
states of the FRG) are a critical component of the FG's R&amp;D 
capacity. They presently employ 16,000 employees (not counting 
project centers, trainees and guest scientists) and get 90 
percent of their basic financing from the federal level and 10 
percent from one or more states where they are located. 
  The establishment in the fifties and sixties of large 
research facilities having a focus occurred mainly in the 
context of the organization and development of nuclear research 
and engineering, aerospace research, data processing and then 
bio-medical research. Currently, the large research facilities 
are making contributions in the sectors of long-term government 
programs (e.g., ocean research, polar research, space research), 
precautionary research (environmental, climate, health and 
safety research and evaluation of the engineering consequences), 
basic research in the natural sciences as well as development of 
market-oriented technologies (e.g., materials research, 
bio-technological research, energy research and engineering and 
underwater engineering). 
  Presented below is a survey of the share of materials 
research in the research activities of the large research 
facilities. Large research facilities not mentioned are making 
only an inconsiderable contribution, if any at all, to materials 
research. The statistics were basically derived from the program 
budget. 
  Also to be taken into consideration in any qualitative 
treatment of the materials research potential of large research 
facilities are activities in other topical foci such as 
solid-state physics, microsystems engineering or hypersonic 
technologies, although they have only a limited connection with 
the goals of the materials research program. 
  In 1992, the contribution of the large research facilities 
to 
materials research is nearly DM114 million (incl. project 
funding). Based on a rough estimate, those include activities 
thematically related to the "materials research" program 
amounting to approximately DM70 million. In 1992, only about 
DM1.1 million in BMFT support was applied and for the period 
1985-1992 it totaled nearly DM15 million. After incentive 
financing from the BMFT of respectively DM4-5 million in past 
years, the GKSS, KFA and even the DLR, are involved partially in 
overall charge of combined projects, that are predominantly 
financed from basic financing. 
  The restructuring and fresh orientations of materials 
related 
research in the KFA and KfK that was launched in 1992 make it 
possible to detect a more intensive orientation towards 
industrial needs and a concentration on a few concrete applied 
sectors. 
  Described below are the active foci of the large research 
foci with their respective links to the current materials 
research program: 
<H5>  Juelich research center GmbH [KFA] </H5>
  A relatively broad spectrum of directions of research is 
pursued at the Juelich research center, extending from the basis 
for information engineering via basic nuclear research, fusion 
research, energy engineering and health and environmental 
research to biotechnology. 
  In the materials technology sector, the KFA conducts 
research 
activities, most of which is basically financed albeit a smaller 
portion is also project financed. Under the BMFT's basic 
financing, in 1992 the KFA allocated DM52 million for materials 
research (including 30 percent of solid-state research, see 
below). That amounts to 11.7 percent of the total KFA budget 
basically financed by the BMFT. 
  At both of the institutes, the Institute for Applied 
Materials Research [IAW] and the Institute for Reactor Materials 
[IRW], materials research activities are conducted on a focused 
basis. Both institutes are actively engaged, albeit without 
financing from project support funding and sometimes taking 
overall charge of MATFO combined projects. Beginning in 1993, 
both institutes will have a fresh orientation based on the 
proposal of the structural committee. They are projected to be 
merged into a single institute with a 50 percent reduction in 
personnel strength and concentration on foci 1) materials for 
fuel cells (SOFC), 2) materials for GuD power plants and 3) 
materials behavior in plasma-wall interactions. The first two 
indicated foci are clearly linked to the MATFO program and will 
enable the KFA in the future to attract third-party funds even 
more strongly even from the BMFT for its research. 
  Besides the above-mentioned foci, the KFA, for the first 
time 
since 1992 has been posting 30 percent of its solid-state 
research under the generic label of "materials research." In 
terms of a materials-oriented solid-state research focusing on 
the production and optimization of interesting new materials and 
layered structures, that appears to be justified. 
<H5>  Karlsruhe nuclear research center GmbH [KfK] </H5>
  Materials research is assuming comparably great significance 
at the KfK. In 1991, DM42.7 million of federal basic financing 
was allocated to that research sector. That is nine percent of 
the KfK's total BMFT-financed budget. Since 1992, however, KfK 
has been posting no funding any longer directly under the rubric 
of "materials research," although materials research projects 
are still conducted under other foci (e.g., microsystems 
engineering, production engineering). 
  At KfK the objective of nuclear research development 
originally pursued when the research center was founded, is 
still distinctly detectable. Research activities foci consist of 
various nuclear engineering issues such as nuclear safety 
research, reprocessing and final-storage problems, and fusion 
technology. Also extensively covered is basic research in the 
field of nuclear and particle physics. Solid-state and materials 
research claims an increasing share of the total budget, 
although it remains predominantly oriented towards nuclear 
engineering. 
  Concurrently, over the past decade the KfK has also engaged 
in research projects on new high-performance materials and plays 
an important role in Baden-Wuerttemberg state's materials 
research program institutional combine. 
  Based on the recommendations of a prospects committee and 
after a restructuring of the institute for materials research 
(only three instead of four partial institutes any longer), in 
1991 the fundamental elements of the active focus for materials 
research were redefined under the general terms of microsystems 
engineering (the major share), nuclear energy research and 
nuclear fusion. Of foremost interest under the concept of 
materials and interfaces are microsystems engineering activities 
having a basic-orientation. Under the nuclear fusion project for 
energy research, developments and studies of structural 
materials for fusion equipment (refractory metals, ceramics) are 
carried out. Also worth mentioning are the more recent 
activities on fullerenes and magnetostriction and piezo-electric 
thin layers. 
  In general, the materials research activities at the KfK 
have 
a relatively basic orientation and focus. At present there are 
no projects being carried out under the BMFT's materials 
research program. 
<H5>  Geesthacht GKSS research center GmbH </H5>
  The foci of this institution are in the environmental and 
climate research sector. In addition, over recent years, 
materials research has also been assuming increasing value for 
GKSS' activity. In 1992, federal basic financing for the GKSS in 
the materials research sector totaled DM30.5 million. That 
equals a 28 percent share of the total BMFT contribution for the 
GKSS' materials research. On the other hand, the formerly 
prevailing focus on research in the sector of reactor safety is 
trending downwards. By contrast, materials research is receiving 
special importance in the environmental technologies sector. 
  Even in the future, materials research will take on high 
status for GKSS. Despite a topping out of the budget figures, 
therefore, the institute for materials research is not impacted 
by personnel cuts. The materials research is concentrated on 
(refractory) metallic materials with prominence given to 
intermetallic compounds (titanium aluminide) and materials for 
maritime engineering. 
  On the basis of incentive financing in several projects of 
the materials research program, the GKSS is intensively engaged, 
occasionally being in overall charge, in a number of combined 
projects with basic financing resources. 
  The long-term strategy of GKSS 2000 projects a concentration 
on the foci of "materials research," "environmental and climate 
research" and "environmentally friendly separation and process 
engineering" with a reduction in engineering sciences. 
<H5>  German Aerospace Research Institution e.V. [DLR] </H5>
  The DLR was originally set up for the organization and 
development of aerospace research. Since then it has become 
active also in the field of communications engineering and in 
the sector of environmental and climate research. One of the 
DLR's 21 institutes, the DLR institute for materials research in 
Cologne-Porz, is occupied exclusively with researching aerospace 
materials. Considering its focus on the specific requirement of 
aerospace engineering, the institute for materials research sees 
little importance in transferring materials engineering know-how 
to other sectors or other transportation platforms like rail and 
automobile. The institute employs 90 employees, including 45 
scientists. The institute's primary function is as a link 
between basic research represented above all at the universities 
and the Max-Planck Society institutes and the product and 
processing development pursued mainly by industry. Hence 
activity is focused on (basic) research topics having an applied 
orientation. 
  The DLR's materials research activities, therefore, are 
concentrated and focused on aerospace and energy engineering. 
Especially important in the aviation sector are aluminum, 
aluminum-lithium alloys, and fiber reinforced synthetic 
materials. In primary components in the future carbon fiber 
reinforced synthetic materials, above all, will be increasingly 
used. So-called high-temperature resistant superalloys will be 
mostly used for the manufacture of drive trains. Materials 
development for space is oriented towards the requirement of 
greater heat-resistance. Fiber-reinforced ceramic surface 
coating and carbon-fiber reinforced composites have enabled 
advances in this field. In all the indicated sectors DLR is 
engaged in promising research activities. 
  Supplementing the activity of the materials research 
institute, the DLR also comprises the institute for construction 
and construction research in Stuttgart and the institute for 
structural mechanics in Braunschweig dedicated to research 
activities on new materials. The DLR was a participant in a 
number of MATFO program combined projects with financing from 
project support funds. 
<H5>  Society for Heavy Ion Research GmbH [GSI], Darmstadt </H5>
  The GSI's activities in heavy ion research for materials 
research have a basic orientation and focus. In terms of focus, 
the bases are supposed to be created for an understanding of the 
ion beam mix, material structuring and nuclear-trace filter 
engineering. Reflecting the thrust of the research, the 
materials research activities at the GSI have exclusively basic 
financing. In 1992, BMFT basic financing for materials research 
totaled DM4.4 million (= 4.1 percent of the institute's BMFT 
financed budget). No projects were conducted by the GSI under 
the MATFO program. 
<H5>  Hahn-Meitner Institute Berlin GmbH [HMI] </H5>
  The HMI's tasking is research into the properties of 
condensed matter, focusing on structural research and 
photochemical energy conversion. Research is also conducted in 
the specialized fields of nuclear physics and information 
engineering. Materials research activities are carried out in 
the two specialized fields of structural research and 
solid-state physics. In the specialized field of solid-state 
physics, the materials research activities are related to 
discrete flaws in semiconductors and electronic structures, with 
some overlap with KFA solid-state research themes noticeable. In 
1992, DM20.8 million were allocated at the HMI out of the BMFT's 
basic financing for materials research (20.6 percent of the 
BMFT's basic financing for the HMI's budget). No projects were 
implemented under the MATFO program. 
  The above-described basic research institutions occupy an 
important position in Germany's research scenario and they 
constitute an important component of the nation's total R&amp;D 
capacity. On the basis of the basic research tasking originally 
assigned to them since they were founded, they have increasingly 
done preliminary work in new fields of research and developed 
expertise in some fields such as environmental and climate 
technology as well as production engineering, information 
engineering, and non-nuclear energy technologies. 
  It was precisely in the materials research sector that 
capital, personnel and financial foci were developed at the GFE. 
To the extent that the GFEs' objectives and strategies and those 
of the future MATFO program can be successfully coordinated 
better with one another and combined into a coherent overall 
strategy for materials engineering, a more powerful research and 
innovation combine can be developed. This opens up 
opportunities for increasing the effectiveness and efficiency of 
Germany's materials research. 
  Exploitation of those opportunities, however, requires 
consistent implementation of restructuring efforts in the GFE 
and their effective integration in combined projects. Above all, 
we welcome the current efforts of the GFE to focus more 
intensively their future materials research capacities on the 
needs of industrial users and to try out new forms of financing 
and research organization. 
  For the GFE in Germany to give a decisive impetus to 
materials research calls for even more intensive incorporation 
into the context of industrial research activities and into an 
efficient working association involving research, training, and 
industrial use. If greater sensitization to the requirements of 
materials users and if the restructuring of the institutes that 
has already been initiated are successfully and consistently 
realized, the GFEs' materials research activities will be able 
to exert a long-lasting, strong impact in the future on the 
development of materials engineering in Germany. 
<H5>  3.3.5 Survey of the status and growth of materials research </H5>
in the new federal states 
  In the area of the new federal states over the past decade 
it 
has been possible in the materials research sector to establish 
at various institutes some research foci even enjoying worldwide 
renown. In the former GDR, some materials research fields 
(ceramics, composite materials, non-destructive testing process) 
acquired a key role in the nation's research planning. In the 
wake of reunification, therefore, Germany's research scenario 
underwent an enrichment of its potential. Even the analyses of 
science council lead to a generally favorable assessment, albeit 
greatly diversified on the basis of centers and 
institutes[.sup]19[/]. As in the former states of the FRG, 
the materials research capacities and expertise in the states 
are concentrated in a few centers that are, above all, however, 
influenced by the central research planning of the former GDR. 
The important ones in this context are: 


    -  Sachsen state (Dresden, Chemnitz, Freiberg and Zwickau) 
  -  Sachsen-Anhalt (Halle and Magdeburg) 
  -  the former institutes of the Academy of Sciences [AdW] in 
Berlin 
  -  and Thueringen (Jena and Ilmenau). 
  In this context, Dresden is the most important for materials 
research in the new states. In past years numerous materials 
research activities were concentrated there, (ZfW, Dresden TU, 
Prof. Ardenne Research Institute, Rossendorf nuclear research 
center, etc.), and they will continue to be pursued even after 
their extensive restructuring in 1991/1992. At Dresden TU and in 
the immediate purview of the TU, the following institutes, among 
others, are under development: 


    -  the institute for macromolecular and textiles chemistry 
  -  the institute for polymers research e.V. 
  -  the institute for materials sciences 
  -  the institute for solid-state mechanics 
  -  the institute for textiles and clothing engineering 
  After the restructuring of the ZfW, of the Prof. Ardenne 
research institute and the Rossendorf nuclear research center, 
numerous new institutes arose involving various platforms (FhG, 
MPG, Blue List, etc.) that have demonstrated expertise in 
specific fields of materials research. 
  The Bergakademie in Freiberg also appears to hold promise 
for 
future German materials research. Special emphasis is given 
there to innovative production and processing technologies plus 
modeling of processes and materials structures. Meanwhile, the 
Bergakademie is undergoing restructuring, with development of 
materials research receiving considerable emphasis. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-73A>        Table 3.16: Distribution of MATFO projects among universities and institutes in the new states of </FIG>

  In Sachsen-Anhalt state, the materials engineering focus is 
at Halle, Magdeburg and Merseburg. In early 1992 at Halle, the 
Max-Planck institute for microstructural engineering commenced 
its activity. Its employees were all from the former GDR's 
Academy of Science's institute for solid-state physics and 
electron mircoscopy that had been dissolved. The newly founded 
institute's fields of active are basic research in the sector of 
smallest-dimension solid-state physics, that is, the structure 
and properties of small particles and thin layers, crystal flaws 
and interface engineering, solar energy, and materials research. 
  Some of the universities and institutes participated in the 
current MATFO program after unification. Table 3.16 presents a 
survey of the allocation of project funding. By the cutoff date 
of 31 December 1991, universities in the new states had received 
a support funding commitment totaling DM7.3 million, equivalent 
to a 5.4 percent share of total university support. Those funds 
are allocated especially among the universities of Dresden, 
Jena, and the Freiberg Bergakademie. Moreover, under the MATFO 
program the former institutes of the Academy of Sciences 
received a total of DM7 million for funding of 30 projects. 
  In light of the current institutional and political 
processes 
of change that are occurring, it is premature to undertake a 
definitive description and assessment of the situation for some 
of the centers. But even a preliminary uptake allows some 
conclusions to be drawn. 
  In the wake of reunification, Germany's materials science 
was 
enriched by a number of well-trained materials scientists. In 
the early stages the situation is impacted by the difficulties 
of restructuring that will probably lead to considerable 
processes of adaptation for a number of years. The growth in 
research capacity, however, is essentially appropriate for 
imparting added impetuses to materials research in Germany. 
  Two essentials are needed basically to implement that 
potential. First, the relevant institutes in the new states have 
to be brought up to a West German standard as speedily as 
possible in terms of its equipment. Second, there must, above 
all, be an integration of those institutes into the existing 
materials research scenario. To do that, the existing East 
German research institutes, building on established past foci, 
need to continue pursuing those foci and systematically expand 
their expertise towards a complementary national division of 
labor. 
<H5>  3.3.6 Survey of materials training in the FRG </H5>
  Considering the increasing strategic significance of 
materials technology, it is essential to continue consistently 
to develop university training in the materials and materials 
sciences sector to be able over the long term to have available 
a sufficiently large pool of qualified next-generation 
engineers. In many instances the professional status of the 
materials scientists is still not projected very transparently, 
especially since there is still no sufficiently clear image of 
the training situation and later field of professionalization. 
Increasingly even interested firms are asking for orientation 
assistance. In this context, the remarkable fact is that the 
relatively recent specialty of "materials science" encompasses a 
very heterogeneous and interdisciplinary field of activity that, 
unlike traditional engineering sciences, cannot fit in well with 
the stock qualifiers. Elaboration of a training strategy in the 
materials science and allied disciplines is also a leading 
contender for development of a national R&amp;D strategy in the 
materials research sector. To do so, in turn, requires first of 
all an assessment of the current status of training at the 
universities. 
  In the FRG, materials related training is carried out in 41 
specialized sectors at a total of 32 scientific universities 
(not counting specialized universities). Jointly, they offer an 
extremely broad spectrum of courses, programs of study or 
enrichment programs[.sup]20[/]. Training, in this context, is 
effected only partially via a course of studies for materials 
sciences or engineering or materials sciences or engineering. 
Quite frequently it is a part of some other course of studies 
like machine building, production engineering, or 
specializations in the natural sciences (see table 3.17). 
  The least coursework is organized in its own materials 
science sector of specialization/department. At some 
universities, materials related instruction is offered by 
various departments. To realize any assistance with orientation, 
such a plethora of training offers needs to be structured on the 
basis of a variety of distinguishing criteria. 
  One of those criteria may first be the question whether the 
materials training is done in its own independent course of 
studies or is included in an outside course of studies, for 
example, physics, chemistry, machine building, electrical 
engineering. On this basis, at least 14 of the 41 areas of 
specialization involved in materials training conduct an 
independent course of studies in materials. The 
over-proportionately high number of universities among them in 
the new states is remarkable: there are six such centers. In 
terms of their formal structure and degree designations, 
however, those courses of study are not directly comparable with 
one another. 
  A further distinction can be made on the level of the 
courses 
and enrichment coursework. Mostly, in subject areas offering an 
autonomous course of studies in materials was a detailed 
breakdown of the coursework undertaken. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-75A>        Table 3.17: Survey of training in the materials sciences sector at German </FIG>



<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-76A>        Table 3.17 (continued): Survey of training in the materials sciences sector at German </FIG>

  With seven different courses each, the RWTH Aachen, Berlin 
TU 
and the university of Erlangen-Nuremberg have the most extensive 
training menu. Among the east German universities, the Freiberg 
Bergakademie and Dresden TU deserve notice with seven and five 
courses, respectively. At other universities where materials 
engineering is included in other coursework, a number of 
materials engineering enrichment programs are occasionally 
offered. Meriting special importance in this connection are the 
Munich TU machine building curriculum with six enrichment 
programs and the Clausthal TU metallurgy and materials sciences 
curriculum with 10 different enrichment alternatives. 
  So far, regulation of the degree designations has proved 
less 
transparent. Other subject areas generally confer a degree 
reflecting the designation of the respective course. Many 
universities, all the same, conduct materials related enrichment 
coursework as a supplement to the degree title (Bayreuth 
University, Bochum Ruhr-University, Hamburg-Harburg TU). 
Universities in the new states frequently confer their degree in 
accordance with the curriculum (Chemnitz, Freiberg, Ilmenau). 
Despite training that emphasizes materials, many universities do 
not award any degree with a materials related designation (e.g., 
Karlsruhe University, Munich TU). 
  An assessment of the subjects in basic and principal courses 
can yield insight into the nature of materials training at 
German universities. The basic course curriculum, with relative 
uniformity, includes approximately 15 subjects at all 
universities with materials related training. Accordingly, major 
emphasis is universally placed on imparting mathematical 
knowledge. Distinct differences, however, are evident in the 
rest of the courses. Depending on the focus of the coursework, 
the respective core subjects occupy the broadest scope, that is, 
thermodynamics for machine building, physical chemistry for 
chemical engineering, electrical engineering for electrical and 
information technologies and computerization, etc. With 15 or 
more semester credit hours, materials related subjects receive 
considerable emphasis even in the basic course at a few 
universities (Berlin TU, Chemnitz, Dresden, Freiberg, Magdeburg, 
Merseburg, Stuttgart). 
  Besides university training, the training and advanced 
training on the skilled worker and college levels also are 
decisive for assessing the personnel situation and its 
development in the materials engineering sector. A study 
commissioned by the OECD (1992) arrives at a favorable 
assessment in this respect on the situation in the FRG. In the 
metallic materials and polymers sectors, in fact, Germany enjoys 
an extremely diversified training and professionalization system 
that facilitates continuing advanced development and use at all 
stages of the net product chain. By contrast, the 
professionalization situation in the ceramics and composites 
materials sectors seems to be less diversified and full of gaps 
in some areas. According to the OECD study the development 
status of the training and professionalization system on the 
university, but, above all, on the non-university level, is a 
quite crucial determining factor for promising national 
innovation strategies in the materials engineering sector. 
