<H5>  4. Importance of Materials and Processing Technologies for </H5>
German Industry 
  At present there is no doubt that a decisive factor in 
ensuring a country's future prosperity is the safeguarding and 
enhancing of the competitiveness of companies on the world 
markets. If companies as well as the government are to be able 
to safeguard this competitiveness in an arena marked by a high 
dynamic for change on the political, social, economic, and 
technological levels, they have to adapt to such changes and 
actively help shape them. 
  A highly industrialized country like the FRG, with a weak 
raw 
materials basis, but with a good supply of fixed capital, an 
established basis of know-how, and a high level of education, 
should use its existing relative strengths in know-how 
intensive, future-oriented sectors of technology to concentrate 
on areas where such strengths can be most effectively used. But, 
as chapter four describes in detail, the leading industrial 
nations have the same marginal conditions as the FRG and 
therefore consider similar sectors of technology future-oriented 
and endeavor to develop them. So it is all the more necessary 
for the FRG to concentrate existing resources effectively and 
efficiently on technology sectors that Germany views as 
future-oriented and develop them as rapidly as possibly (chapter 
4.1). 
  Because of their central importance for the future 
development of many sectors, materials, and processing 
technologies are viewed internationally as particularly 
future-oriented technology sectors. It is imperative to 
safeguard and develop the position achieved in this 
broad-spectrum sector of technology to exploit the potential for 
differentiation in internationally important and attractive 
sectors and thereby permanently enhance the competitiveness of 
German industry (chapter 4.3). 
  (1) In all leading industrial countries, research and 
development in the field of high performance materials and the 
associated production and processing technologies enjoy very 
high significance since they 
  - have high development and application potential 
  - are, in many cases, the prerequisite for new or definitely 
improved technical designs, even allowing for ecological issues, 
and therefore 
  - afford firms in practically all sectors of industry an 
opportunity to realize strategic competitive advantages (chapter 
4.3). 
  (2) Technological developments in such important industrial 
sectors as automobile manufacturing, electronics/electrical 
engineering, energy engineering, machine and appliance building, 
or chemistry are often based on high performance materials. 
Maintaining and developing the FRG's current, often favorable, 
competitive position in such industrial sectors and the 
associated export results (percentage of international exports: 
automobile manufacturing, 22 percent; electrical engineering, 18 
percent; energy engineering, 16 percent; electronics, nearly 10 
percent), can be safeguarded through the solid basis of know-how 
in this future-oriented technology sectors (chapter 4.3). 
  (3) In order to realize the potential of high performance 
materials, in the future, in the materials and processing 
technologies sector, above all, it will be necessary to overcome 
the gap still existing between materials development and further 
processing or the manufacture of components, so as to ensure the 
transfer of know-how from research and development to innovative 
products and systems (chapter 4.2). 
<H5>  4.1 International comparison of key technologies </H5>
  Analyzing the fields of technology that the world's leading 
industrial countries consider to be future-oriented, one detects 
a broad agreement on and prioritization of the following sectors: 


    -  materials and processing technologies 
  -  electronics 
  -  information and communication technologies 
  -  biotechnology 
  -  energy production technologies. 
  The troika of countries (EC, U.S., and Japan) especially 
intensely pursues those technological fields, wherein the 
individual countries have created individual focuses in order to 
push the development of selective technologies in those sectors. 
  Basically, a distinction must be drawn among various types 
of 
technology that are positioned along the technologies timeline 
curve. Mastery of key and cutting-edge technologies, that is, of 
technologies in a relatively early stage of development, in 
contrast to basic technologies, affords a quite considerable 
diversification of potential vis-a-vis competitors and is 
therefore of rather particular importance for safeguarding and 
developing firms' future competitive position (see chart 4.1). 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-79A>        Chart 4.1: Types of technologies and their positioning in the technological life </FIG>

  The rapidly growing demand and the anticipated market 
potential of products that directly or indirectly depend on the 
indicated technologies compel firms to obtain access to key and 
cutting-edge technologies in those technological fields. This is 
a development that is supported for macro-economic 
considerations by official support programs in leading 
industrial nations. concurrent with this market-pull optic, the 
know-how and results from academic basic research and industrial 
research act as a technology-push leading to a high rate of 
innovation and dynamism in those fields of technology. 
International technological competition is thereby further 
intensified. Strong positions in the indicated fields of 
technology have clearly positive impacts on companies, sectors, 
and ultimately even nations. 
  To safeguard and even to develop advantageous competitive 
and 
technological positions, the leading industrial nations, above 
all, the U.S., Japan, and Germany, in industry and on the part 
of government, expend quite sizable funding on R&amp;D (see 
charts 
4.2 and 4.3). It is not possible precisely to attribute the 
described R&amp;D expenditure to the six indicated technological 
fields, especially the industrial outlays. The underlying 
assumption, however, must be that a rather sizable amount goes, 
directly or indirectly, into the indicated fields of technology. 
  Based on chart 4.2, the U.S. is the world leader by a wide 
margin in terms of absolute R&amp;D outlays. In 1990, the U.S. 
invested $151 billion in R&amp;D, followed by Japan with $67 
billion 
and the FRG with $32 billion. In past years (1985-1990), rates 
of increase in absolute outlays for R&amp;D were the highest in 
Japan. France, the FRG, U.S., and Great Britain follow at a 
distinct distance. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-80A>        Chart 4.2: Comparative illustration of absolute outlays for R </FIG>

  If, on the other hand, the relative R&amp;D outlays of the 
individual countries are considered relative to gross domestic 
product [GDP] (see chart 4.3), it then turns out that in 1990, 
Japan, the U.S., and FRG invested between 2.8 percent and 3.1 
percent of their GDP in R&amp;D. Remarkably, Japan's relative 
R&amp;D 
outlays have risen significantly, that is, from 2.77 percent 
(1985) to 3.07 percent (1990) relative to GDP whereas those of 
the U.S. and FRG fell or rose only slightly. 
  Because of numerous problems of delimitation, it is possible 
to make only a rough estimate of how much of that is invested in 
the respective countries in R&amp;D on materials and processing 
technologies. The underlying assumption has to be that the U.S. 
is officially investing the most financial resources in the 
world in R&amp;D on materials and processing technologies. In 
recent 
years, Japan and the FRG have launched nearly comparable 
official resources into the field of materials and processing 
technologies. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-81A>        Chart 4.3: Comparative illustration of relative R </FIG>

  In the future, both the U.S. and Japan plan to increase 
financial resources for R&amp;D on materials and processing 
technologies. The FRG, on the other hand, is in a 
decision-making stage regarding R&amp;D investments in materials 
and 
processing technologies. 
  Remarkably, the troika of countries gives priority to nearly 
the same sectors in materials and processing technologies, with 
the following the most prominent: 


    -  high-performance metals and alloys 
  -  high-performance ceramics 
  -  high-performance polymers 
  -  high performance composite materials 
  -  magnetic materials 
  -  superconducting materials 
  -  electronic materials 
  -  optical materials 
  -  biocompatible materials. 
  Within those groups, the leading industrial states are 
oriented towards the following issues: 


    -  development of new materials 
  -  further development of existing materials 
  -  improvement of production and processing technologies 
  -  systems innovations 
  New thematic fields like computer design and computer 
simulation and materials recycling so far have only sporadically 
been included in materials research. 
<H5>  4.2 Status and development trends in materials and process </H5>
technologies area 
  Generally speaking, materials are solid substances having 
technically useful features. The materials that are used as the 
basic materials for technical products must be selected on a 
targeted basis in keeping with the specific requirements profile 
of the respective application and be optimized in terms of 
materials and energy consumption, reliability, quality, 
durability, environmental demands and recycling possibilities. 
Hence, components and systems should be realized that meet the 
steadily increasing requirements in the various areas of 
application. 
  It is becoming increasingly obvious, in fact, for 
high-performance materials that the separation of materials 
development and advanced processing and component production 
does not make sense and that it is more appropriate to link 
systems or components design and construction with materials 
development and their production and advanced processing 
methods. For example, in powder metallurgy or in the ceramics 
sector, new production processes endeavor to influence the 
microstructure and micro-configuration in order thereby to 
inject specific property profiles. Newly developed processing 
technologies endeavor advantageously to transfer to the 
component the property profiles thus obtained from the basic 
materials. This is realized, for example, by assembling a number 
of processing steps into a single processing step within 
processing technology or by means of an integrated process 
management that combines production and processing steps. 
Directly associated with this also are automation designs and 
quality assurance systems that decisively impact the 
reproducibility, reliability and economy of components 
production. 
<H5>  4.2.1 Defining Germany's technological position in selected </H5>
materials and process technologies 
  Under a portfolio analysis, the FRG's relative technological 
position, in an international comparison of important and 
attractive materials and processing technologies, was defined 
semi-qualitatively with the greatly fragmented materials sectors 
aggregated into the following core sectors: 


    -  high-performance ceramics 
  -  structural ceramics 
  -  functional ceramics 
  -  high-performance polymers 
  -  structural polymers 
  -  functional polymers 
  -  high-performance metals 
  -  structural metals 
  -  functional metals 
  -  high-performance composites 
  -  high-performance glassware 
  The portfolio depicted in chart 4.4 describes, on the one 
hand, the attractiveness of the indicated selective 
high-performance materials and processing technologies using the 
criteria of potential for advanced development, probability of 
dissemination and realizable synergistic effects. On the other 
hand, the FRG's relative technological position is defined on 
the basis of criteria for the degree of technological mastery 
along the net product chain, resource strengths and R&amp;D 
efficiency. The size of the circle drawn for each group of 
materials reflects the respective international market volumes 
at semi-finished and component stages. 
  The following picture emerges for the high-performance 
technologies being studied, based on the portfolio analysis that 
was conducted: all the analyzed technologies have relatively 
high technological attractiveness. This stems from a sizable 
potential for advanced development, a high probability of 
dissemination and above-average synergistic effects on other 
technologies that all assessed groups of materials display. 
  Contrastingly, Germany's relative technological position in 
those groups of high-performance materials turns out to be quite 
diversified. In an international comparison involving 
high-performance polymers, the FRG occupies a strong 
technological position, since German firms and research 
institutes have embarked on a large number of new directions in 
this sector and have realized internationally recognized 
research results. This surely is based first on a strength that 
has developed historically and secondly, the materials research 
program has also made a significant contribution to it. 
  On the other hand, in the field of high-performance 
composite 
materials and high-performance functional ceramics, the FRG 
presently occupies only a feeble to average relative 
technological position. The risk here is that catching up with 
the technology leaders, the U.S. and Japan, may be a wasted 
effort in the future. On the whole, in the other materials 
sectors under consideration the positions are favorable to 
average. There is a mastery of important processes and there 
does exist a basic know-how and keeping up with the leading 
nations of the U.S. and Japan in materials engineering could be 
sustained. In some sectors leadership positions could even be 
realized, this too, moreover, surely creditable to the materials 
research program. 
  Generally, however, it must be remarked that the singular 
strengths have not been developed broadly enough and the R&amp;D 
results in the individual net product stages have not been 
consistently linked one to the other. It must also be pointed 
out that Japan and the U.S., precisely our most important 
competitors, have intensified their technological position in 
the fields of high-performance materials over past years. On the 
whole, the U.S. and Japan are still considered the leaders in 
the field of high-performance materials -- also a result of 
considerable official support. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-83A>        Chart 4.4: Determining the relative technological position of the FRG in high-performance </FIG>

<H5>  4.2.2 Status and development trends in selective materials </H5>
and processing technologies 
<H5>  4.2.2.1 General survey </H5>
  In the course of history, especially, however, in the 
twentieth century, a large number of examples can be cited that 
can elucidate the importance that materials hold for advanced 
technical and social development. It is evident that 
technological quantum leaps result in many instances from the 
development or new or definitely improved materials. 
  Although clearly outlined areas of application have emerged 
for each of the three major groups of materials, there are 
numerous possibilities, where the various materials are in 
competition with one another and ultimately, the ideal 
world-real world relationship among application-specific 
requirements and materials-specific properties determines the 
respective choice. 
  As illustrated in chart 4.5, three main groups of materials 
are distinguished at present: 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-84A>        Chart 4.5: Schematic survey of the most important groups of materials </FIG>

  The division of materials into three main groups is 
ultimately linked to the atomic structure and the predominant 
bonding forces from which, in principle, the basic properties of 
such materials are derived. 
  As already explained at the outset of the chapter, materials 
development, particularly in past decades, has undergone 
astounding development. This development, arising from specific 
new requirements from the various sectors of industry and 
through sizable R&amp;D efforts to develop new and even better 
materials, has ultimately even established a group of materials 
that is characterized by a particular performance spectrum. It 
is often difficult to distinguish these materials from 
traditional or established materials and their important 
modifications as well. This also explains the plethora of 
terminology for such materials that range in the 
English-language literature from "new materials" via 
"engineering materials, "customized materials" to "Advanced 
Materials," to document only a small segment of the host of 
designations noted on this point. 
  Ultimately, all those terms have one thing in common: they 
describe materials whose properties profile is characterized as 
new or having special performance. For example, there are 
superalloys that are mechanically resistant even at high 
temperatures or resistant to chemical influences, ceramics have 
been distinctly improved in terms of their strength and have 
thereby become considerably more interesting as structural 
materials, or, as a result of high-temperature superconductivity 
for ceramic materials, it will be possible in the future to 
develop entirely new fields of application. In the plastics 
sector, there now are available materials with considerably 
improved high-temperature resistance or electrical conductivity 
as a result of new or improved materials. Even in the composite 
materials sector there are developments that range far beyond 
the production of compounds via mechanical processes and that 
target the on-site production of compounds during synthesis. 
  Such especially effective materials should henceforth be 
designated as high-performance materials and accordingly be 
defined thus: 
  High-performance materials are synthetic materials whose 
properties profiles may generate new, promising structural and 
functional application possibilities and enable the realization 
of new technologies. 
  The term high-performance material appears at this point to 
make complete sense even if it refers to the improvement of 
materials and their establishment in selective areas of 
application. Still, it must be borne in mind that the goal is to 
broaden as rapidly as possible the application of 
high-performance materials that are developed in order to meet 
the future challenges from the various applied sectors. Only 
broad dissemination in various markets guarantees the 
high-performance material producer, processor and consumer an 
appropriate volume of turnover and a Return-on-Investment on the 
considerable development cost for such materials. To sum up: 
Today's leading-edge technology, with its uncertainties, has to 
strive to become a key technology with its significant potential 
for diversification, but ultimately, it has to strive to become 
a basic technology and thereby the basis of entire industrial 
sectors. A MITI support initiative, the JISEDAI program, that 
also supports materials technologies, clearly describes this 
unambiguous objective: Program for Future Basic Technologies. 
  Although many materials experts accept this definition, 
still 
there are definitional difficulties or even arbitrariness in 
distinguishing, for instance, between high-performance materials 
and improved traditional materials. This shows up, above all, in 
the realization of market volumes for such products. Chart 4.6 
presents us with total present and future turnover for 
high-performance materials in the respective groups of materials. 
  The international market for high-performance materials as 
basic materials (e.g., ceramic and metallic powder, granulated 
polymers, etc.) is projected at nearly DM8.0 billion for 1990. 
Basic polymer materials reflect DM3.0 billion of that amount, 
with DM2.0 for basic ceramic materials, DM1.8 billion for basic 
metallic materials and DM1.3 billion for basic materials for 
high-performance composite materials. By the year 2,000, market 
volume for high-performance materials as basic materials will 
more than double to nearly DM18.0 billion. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-86A>        Chart 4.6: Projected international market volume for high-performance materials as basic materials </FIG>

  The preceding chart already indicates the importance that 
the 
next stages of net product, that is, production of semi-finished 
products and components, have. Internationally, their 1990 
market value is projected at nearly DM65.0 billion. 
High-performance polymer semi-finished products and components 
with DM24.0 billion hold the greatest significance among them, 
leading high-performance ceramics with DM23.0 billion, 
high-performance metals with DM11.0 billion and high-performance 
composites with DM7.0 billion. High-performance materials 
semi-finished products' and components' market volume will more 
than double to nearly DM150 billion by the year 2,000. 
  The following annual average rates of growth can be 
projected 
in the future in the field of high-performance materials: 


    -  high-performance ceramics - 9 percent 
  -  high-performance metals and alloys - 11 percent 
  -  high-performance polymers - 9 percent 
  -  high-performance composite materials - 5 percent 
  In the final analysis, the rates of increase result from 
intensified dissemination of those materials into the specialty 
markets (e.g., aerospace) as well as into the mass markets 
(automobile manufacturing, electrical engineering, electronics, 
etc.). Essentially, however, those high-performance materials 
constitute the basis for developing or realizing new 
applications and technologies, e.g., optoelectronics, medical 
engineering. The preceding projection is unable to take into 
account the strategic importance of high-performance materials, 
i.e., their key role in the realization of new future 
technologies. For the future economic development, especially of 
industrial countries, independent access to such "key 
components" is of critical importance. 
  Remarkably, in the numerous technical discussions, 
interviews 
with experts and at seminars, no significant new R&amp;D topics 
were 
mentioned. Instead, the consistent -- occasionally incremental 
-- advanced processing of basically familiar R&amp;D topics is 
assigned major importance in materials research. 
<H5>  4.2.2.2 High-performance ceramics and glasses </H5>
<H5>  4.2.2.2.1 High-performance ceramics </H5>
  With the exception of single-atom carbon-based ceramics, 
ceramic materials are crystalline compounds of metals with 
non-metals or semi-metals. The raw materials for the production 
of ceramics are among the most common elements and compounds in 
the earth's crust, so that the supply of raw materials for the 
production of those products is guaranteed for the long term. 
Chart 4.7 provides a survey of the most important ceramic 
materials. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-87A>        Chart 4.7: Materials-oriented division of high-performance ceramic materials </FIG>

  High-performance ceramics are based essentially on oxide and 
non-oxide compounds, although in the field of silicate ceramics 
some new developments are of interest. Unlike traditional 
ceramics they are produced from high purity synthetic raw 
materials. 
  Such ceramic materials possess a number of properties that 
predestine them for high-performance applications and 
consequently, facilitate the development of new, promising areas 
of application: 


    -  high strength and resistance 
  -  high wear resistance 
  -  good resistance to corrosion 
  -  low specific weight 
  -  chemical resistance at high temperatures and 
  -  depending on the type of material, low to high electrical and 
thermal conductivity 
  In terms of applied aspects, high-performance ceramics can 
be 
divided into structural or design materials, featuring their 
mechanical, thermal and chemical materials properties in their 
applications and functional materials that find application on 
the basis of their electrical, magnetic, optical, and biological 
properties. 
<H5>  Structural ceramics </H5>


    -  Oxide ceramics 
  Oxide ceramic materials are polycrystalline materials of 
pure 
oxides or oxide compounds that display high purity and are 
normally free of glass phase. 
  Technically, the most import compound among the oxide 
ceramics is aluminum oxide (Al[.sup]2[/]O[.sup]3[/]). 
Through selection and optimization or modification of the 
respective manufacturing process, Al[.sup]2[/]O[.sup]3[/] 
powder can be produced having property profiles whereby an 
extraordinarily broad range of application can be developed. 
Thickly sintered material, exceptional for its high resistance, 
hardness, temperature and corrosion resistance, for example, can 
be used as fire-resistant material, for corrosion-resistant or 
highly critical mechanical parts in the manufacture of machinery 
or equipment. Additional possible applications range from 
insulation, cutting tools, abrasives up to structural components 
for medical implants. Other oxide compounds with a less complex 
property profile are more suited for specific functional sectors 
of application. 
%Non-oxide ceramics 
  Among non-oxide compounds, modifications of carbon -- 
graphite and diamond as well as carbides, nitrides, borides and 
silicides -- are of interest. Because of the high number of 
covalent atomic bonds such materials possess a high melting 
point, high Young's modulus index, high resistance and hardness 
and in many cases excellent electrical and heat conductivity and 
resistance to aggressive media. By far the greatest technical 
importance attaches to silicon nitride 
(Si[.sup]3[/]N[.sup]4[/]) and silicon carbide (SiC), above 
all, as components for chemical equipment, in materials 
processing, high-temperature engineering and the manufacture of 
engines. 
  A sizable problem in the use of high-performance ceramics 
components is disadvantageous properties typical of ceramics 
such as brittleness, frequently low thermal-shock resistance, 
defective reproducibility of materials' and components' 
benchmarks and expensive processing with its associated costs. 
Such disadvantageous properties still lead to low reliability 
and are an object of considerable R&amp;D efforts. 
  To increase fracture toughness and resistance major advances 
are targeted, for example, through optimizing the structure or 
through insertion of a second phase in basic ceramics materials 
that have a positive impact in the micro-sector on resistance to 
the development of fractures. In the case of 
Si[.sup]3[/]N[.sup]4[/], for example, one way is 
reinforced conversion through insertion of ZrO[.sup]2[/] 
particles. However, fracture toughness again declines as 
temperature increases. Another possibility is reinforcement 
using long fibers, even in combination with the reinforced 
conversion. In these ways it is possible to increase not only 
fracture toughness but also tensile strengths as much as 
fourfold compared with monolithic ceramics. But the production 
processes are complicated and that significantly contributes to 
the expensiveness of such materials. 
  In any event, quality assurance in the production of basic 
materials and components is of major importance for increasing 
reliability. The goal here is the reduction and avoidance of 
structural flaws. Critical in this setting, above all, is a dust 
and pollution free environment, the use of high purity and 
highly fine powder and new production technologies that 
facilitate targeted manipulation of the microstructure. 
<H5>  Functional ceramics </H5>
  Among functional ceramics, the oxide compounds are the most 
important. Because of their particular properties profiles -- a 
combination of typical ceramic structural properties with quite 
special physical properties -- they are suitable for a growing 
number of specific applications, e.g., in electronics, data 
storage and processing and in energy, measurement, and control 
engineering. 


    -  Ceramics with special electrical properties 
  The traditional electrical application of ceramics as 
insulators (e.g., Al[.sup]2[/]O[.sup]3[/]) is currently 
supplemented by a number of electrically conductive ceramics. By 
now there are available semiconductors (e.g., SnO[.sup]2[/]), 
ceramics having metal-like conductivity (SiC and 
TiO,[.sup]2[/]), ceramic ion conductors 
("_b_-Al[.sup]2[/]O[.sup]3[/]," ZrO[.sup]2[/]) and 
high-temperature superconducting materials based on Ba-Cu-O rare 
earths. 
  One of the most important developments, above all, for 
sensor 
engineering, is piezo-electric ceramics. These ferro-electrical 
ceramics alter their electrical properties based on a slight 
mechanical deformation and they deform under the application of 
an electrical field. But ion conductors like ZrO[.sup]2[/] 
are already employed in many cases as sensors, e.g., as lambda 
probes in controlled catalyst systems. In this case the change 
in the oxygen concentration in the exhaust effects a change in 
the electrical properties. 
%Ceramics having special electro-optical properties 
  Lead-lanthanum-zirconium-titanate [PLZT] ceramic at layer 
thicknesses in the cm sector is even transparent to light with 
optical properties depending on the direction of an applied 
electrical field. One use, for instance, for optical storage, is 
conceivable here. Even ceramics with non-linear optical 
properties, e.g., ZnSe and ZnS, are of interest and are being 
research in this context. 
%Ceramics with special biological properties 
  Al[.sup]2[/]O[.sup]3[/], ZrO[.sup]2[/], 
Si[.sup]3[/]N[.sup]4[/] and SiC are primarily used as 
structural components for implants. Apatite, calcium phosphate 
and apatite glass ceramics that are produced from molten glass 
through the formation of crystal grains, are used as 
biocompatible coating or non-critical mechanical implants. 
Ceramic implants are used because of their toleration by the 
body, high resistance to pressure, chemical resistance and wear 
resistance. 
  Biocompatibility is playing an increasing role in this 
connection. Inert ceramics are virtually entirely ignored by the 
immune system, bioactive ceramics chemically react and bond with 
their environment and reabsorbed ceramics are metabolically 
degradable. 
%Ceramics having high heat conductivity 
  Ceramics having high heat conductivity are used as substrate 
ceramics (platform material for chips). Aluminum nitride is a 
promising material in this context. It possesses as much as ten 
times more heat conductivity than aluminum oxide, which is being 
used now. 
<H5>  High-performance ceramics production processes </H5>
  Chart 4.8 summarizes the most important processing 
principles 
in the individual net product stages of high-performance 
ceramics: 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-89A>        Chart 4.8: Important net product stages and processing principles in the production of ceramic </FIG>

  As a rule, most high-performance ceramic source materials in 
the form of powder are synthesized. Since the properties of the 
final product are already decisively influenced by the basic 
materials, it is necessary reproducibly to produce powder 
according to specification. This linkage in many cases also 
determines the optimum powder process. 
  There is a generally increasing tendency to establish 
chemical production processes for ceramic powder and sometimes 
even ceramic components, for example: 


    -  the sol-gel process (production of powder from 
solution) whereby high-purity fine-grained powder can be 
produced via the processing steps (production of alcoholate, 
drying and milling, as required) 
  -  reaction spray process (production of powder from solution) 
whereby multi-component powders for oxide ceramics are 
generated, or 
  -  reaction sintering (solid-state gas-phase reaction) whereby, 
for instance, in the course of the sinter process chemical 
conversions can be induced, for example, reaction bound 
Si[.sup]3[/]N[.sup]4[/] [RBSN] or also 
  -  gas phase synthesis. 
  After the powder is processed by the appropriate 
pulverizing, 
washing or granulating steps and also the addition of sinter 
materials, the powder undergoes shaping, with traditional 
methods being used for modern materials. The selection of the 
shaping process is determined by the shape, size and ultimately 
the unit number of the component or semi-finished product to be 
produced. Dry pressing in steel matrices is best suited for 
geometrically simple parts with limited dimensions, while 
isostatic pressing in flexible forms yields sophisticated 
geometries. Hollow solids of any dimension are shaped by slip 
casting. Lastly, injection-molding technology makes it possible 
to produce components having sophisticated geometry in large 
numbers of units. 
  The compaction or sinter process associated with the shaping 
has to be adapted individually to each component. Stay-down 
time, temperature, and the ambient atmosphere are of utmost 
importance here. Simultaneous shaping and sintering are done 
using axial hot processing in graphite matrices or hot isostatic 
pressing [HIP] via all-round pressure using an inert gas. A 
special process is the above-mentioned reaction sintering in 
which the shaped solid only comes into contact with the reactive 
partner during the sinter process. 
  In many instances the extremely high requirements for 
ceramic 
materials in the various fields of application frequently 
require follow-on processing of the sintered work piece. Because 
of the high toughness and brittleness of the material this can 
be done only with diamond tools and it is extremely 
time-consuming and, as a result, cost intensive. 
<H5>  Fields of application for high-performance ceramics </H5>
  The applied alternatives for high-performance ceramics are 
primarily determined by their properties (see chart 4.9). On the 
basis of those, a distinction can be drawn between function 
ceramics on one side and structural ceramics on the other side. 
  In functional ceramics, functional material properties like 
electrical, optical, magnetic, and biological properties are 
uppermost. Functional properties are particularly pronounced in 
the case of oxide ceramics, but specialty non-oxide ceramics 
like ZnS, ZnSe and CuGaSe[.sup]2[/] are important here too. 
On the basis of those properties such materials are intensively 
used in all sectors of electronics, electrical engineering, 
communications and computer technology and medical engineering. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-91A>        Chart 4.9: Selective fields of application for high-performance ceramics </FIG>

  In the case of structural ceramics, on the other hand, 
structural properties are uppermost, for instance, 
mechanical-thermal properties, chemical-thermal properties and 
nuclear properties. Such properties are especially pronounced in 
the non-oxide ceramics SI[.sup]3[/]N[.sup]4[/] and SiC and 
in some oxide ceramics like Al[.sup]2[/]O[.sup]3[/], 
ZrO[.sup]2[/], UO[.sup]2[/] and ThO[.sup]2[/]. Based on 
the required property expression, structural ceramics can be 
used, for example, heavily in machine building, in the chemical 
industry, energy engineering and in automobile manufacturing. 
<H5>  Market growth </H5>
  In 1990 the international market for high-performance 
ceramic 
materials as basic materials is estimated at nearly DM2.0 
billion. By 1995, an increase in demand up to nearly DM3.1 
billion is forecast and by the year 2,000 that is likely to more 
than double to more than DM4.8 billion. If the next net product 
stages in the high-performance ceramics sector are taken into 
account, that is, ceramic semi-finished products/components, 
then international market volume is projected to be nearly DM23 
billion (1990). By the year 1995 that market volume is likely to 
rise to DM35 billion and by the year 2,000 to nearly DM55 
billion. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-92A>        Chart 4.10: Projected international market volumes for high-performance ceramics as </FIG>

  In 1990, Japan had the lion's share of the market at nearly 
58 percent of the international market volume totaling DM23 
billion for high-performance ceramics. Next came the U.S. at 30 
percent and Europe at 12 percent. The FRG has an approximately 
five percent share of the international market for 
high-performance ceramics. 
  Functional ceramics are the most important with nearly 80 
percent market share of total market volume. The remaining 
market shares are divided among structural ceramics (13 percent) 
and ceramic coatings (8 percent). By the year 2,000 there will 
be no basic change in the leading position of functional 
ceramics among high-performance ceramics, since especially 
dynamic branches of industry like the electrical and electronics 
industry will ensure the sales of functional ceramics. 
  The growth in demand for structural ceramics, in contrast, 
is 
projected to be smaller since dissemination in mass applications 
in the automobile industry is still not occurring without delays. 
  In this connection the conspicuously significant things are 
primarily the disadvantageous properties inherent in ceramics, 
e.g., brittleness as well as deficient quality and consistency 
of the components, excessive costs and lack of experience with 
reliability. In most instances of application, therefore, 
recourse is had to further developed metallic materials instead 
of high-performance ceramics. 
  Significant growth from DM1.8 billion (1990) to DM6.7 
billion 
in the year 2,000 is project for ceramic coatings. Ceramic 
coatings are expected to overtake structural ceramics in market 
volume in the year 2,000. A basic reason for this is likely to 
be the fact that, in the case of ceramic coatings, the 
advantages of high-performance ceramics can be exploited without 
the material drawbacks inherent in ceramics actually surfacing. 
<H5>  Development trends </H5>
  The following development tendencies appear to be 
particularly meaningful in the case of high-performance ceramics 
for the ability to target and further develop existing 
properties: 
  - materials-related 


    -  increasing fracture toughness 
  -  increasing tolerance for flaws 
  -  improving high-temperature resistance 
  -  piezo-electric ceramics 
  -  electro-optical ceramics 
  -  high-temperature superconductors 
  -  ion conducting ceramics 
  - processing-related 


    -  production and clean room conditions 
  -  chemical production processes (e.g., sol-gel process, 
gas-phase 
synthesis) 
  -  near-net-shape production process 
  -  optimizing existing production and processing processes to 
enhance quality, increase reliability and reduce costs 
  -  coating technologies. 
  Functional ceramics in particular offer very great 
development potential for future advanced development. This is 
based on the combination of typical ceramic properties with 
special electrical, optical, and biological properties. Should 
this development potential be realized, diverse applications and 
fields of application will open up. 
  Even structural ceramics offer major development potential. 
Advanced development in this connection will primarily have to 
concentrate on increased fracture toughness, reliability and 
cost reduction, whereby not only will it be possible to further 
develop niche sectors but a penetration into mass applications 
is also likely to be successful. 
  Even the advanced development of ceramic coatings affords 
opportunities which, if realized, could open up mass markets, 
e.g., automobile manufacturing, machine building, energy 
engineering. 
<H5>  4.2.2.2.2 High-performance glassware </H5>
<H5>  Survey </H5>
  In contrast to ceramic materials, glasses are materials that 
are in a state of frozen-in, undercooled melting, that is, a 
meta-stable state. Further discussion will focus on inorganic 
specialty glassware, essentially silicate glassware. 
  Because of their even more pronounced brittleness, compared 
with ceramics, glasses have no importance as structural 
materials except in the form of fiber reinforcement. 
  In compensation, high-performance glassware does display a 
broad spectrum of functional properties that make them 
interesting for numerous new, promising applications. 


    -  Glassware having special optical properties is used for 
communications fibers, for photo-masks in semi-conductor 
production as well as laser medium and laser lens. There could 
be interesting future applications for glassware having 
non-linear optical properties, e.g., in optical computers. 
  -  Glassware having special electrical properties is used, for 
example, for the encapsulation of semi-conductor components. Ion 
conducting glassware for pH-sensor or thin-film battery 
applications are in the research stage. 
  -  Glassware having special thermal properties has extremely low 
heat expansion and are therefore finding application in 
telescope mirrors and precision optics. Included among these too 
are glass ceramics and partially crystallized glassware. 
  -  Glassware having special biological properties is not only 
glass ceramics but also porous glassware, above all, as bone 
implants and replacement teeth. They are of particular interest 
as appropriate substrate material for biotechnology. 
<H5>  High-performance glass production process </H5>
  High-performance glassware is produced by melting 
high-purity 
natural or synthetic raw materials. The sol-gel process is 
important primarily for coating technology. Simple shaping in a 
state of low viscosity facilitates economical production. 
Follow-on processing is simpler for glass because of it basic 
reduced toughness compared to ceramics. 
<H5>  Market growth </H5>
  In 1990, the international market for specialty glass 
totaled 
nearly DM12 billion, distributed among the following product 
groups: 


    -  TV glass (CRT glass) - 43 percent 
  -  opticalglass - 7 percent 
  -  chemical/pharmaceutical industry glass - 21 percent 
  -  other fields of application (e.g., light-conducting fibers) - 
29 percent 
  In a narrower sense, however, only about 30 percent of 
specialty glass can be included among actual high-performance 
glassware. That is equivalent to a market volume of nearly DM4 
billion. Current market volume for such high-performance glass, 
totaling approximately DM4 billion, will increase to nearly 
DM7.5 billion by the year 2,000. This market growth, totaling 
nearly 6.5 percent per year, is assessed quite differently, 
however, depending on market segment. An annual average growth 
rate of 7-15 percent is projected for the product groups of 
optics/opto-electronics. For other applied sectors for 
high-performance glassware, annual rates of increase of 3-5 
percent are projected. 
  It is noteworthy that future development in the troika is 
very highly polarized. Whereas optical and optoelectrical 
applications are uppermost in Japan, in western Europe the 
focuses for high-performance glassware are on the chemical and 
pharmaceuticals as well as home appliances sectors. In this 
context, the U.S. occupies a middle position. 
  In the high-performance glass sector Japan has concentrated 
on servicing new future-oriented growth markets. Western Europe, 
in turn, is concentrating on supplying traditional industrial 
sectors. 
<H5>  Development trends </H5>
  The following development trends appear to be particularly 
promising in the future for high-performance glass: 


    -  glass with non-linear optical properties 
  -  ion conducting glass 
  -  light conducting glass 
  -  glass with extremely low heat expansion (precision optics) 
  -  porous glass (biotechnological substrate material) 
  The above indicated development trends could be the basis 
for 
an ability to participate more actively in new future-oriented 
growth fields like optoelectronics, for example. 
<H5>  4.2.2.3 High-performance polymers </H5>
<H5>  Survey </H5>
  On the basis of their physical properties polymers can be 
divided into duroplasts, thermoplasts and elastomers. Duroplasts 
harden as the result of an irreversible chemical interlinking 
reaction and are noted for their high strength and heat 
resistance, although they are hard to process. Thermoplasts 
liquefy when heated and harden when cooled. Since this reaction 
is reversible, thermoplastic polymers can be processed 
relatively well. Thermoplasts represent nearly 65 percent of 
total synthetics production. In elastomers the polymer chains 
are weakly interlinked using the "vulcanization" process. Those 
materials are noted for quite elastic ductility and simultaneous 
stability of shape. 
  Chart 4.11 provides a survey of the most important polymers 
in engineering. 
  While standard polymers are definitely mass products, 
technical polymers are primarily used as design and functional 
materials. High-performance polymers, in turn, display 
properties profiles that range far beyond standard polymers and 
technical polymers and open up new, promising structural and 
functional possibilities for application. 
  Depending on their type, they are noteworthy above all for 
their: 


    -  high thermal stability 
  -  stability of shape 
  -  low specific weight 
  -  chemical resistance 
  -  mechanical strength 
  -  specific electrical and optical properties. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-95A>        Chart 4.11: Materials-oriented division of high-performance polymer materials </FIG>

  In terms of applied aspects, high-performance polymers can 
be 
divided into: 


    -  structural polymers - wherein mechanical, thermal, 
chemical, and nuclear properties are foremost and 
  -  functional polymers - that find application, above all, 
because 
of their electrical, optical, magnetic and biological properties. 

<H5>    Structural polymers </H5>
  Steadily increasing in importance among structural polymers, 
above all, are the high-temperature resistant polymers that can 
be used in a temperature range in excess of 150 degrees C. 
Corresponding requirements result, among other things, from the 
miniaturization of components in the electronics industry where 
higher power density and the associated temperature level of 
technical parts are becoming a growing problem. Even in 
automobile and aircraft manufacturing there are increasing 
requirements for materials that blend low weight, exceptional 
mechanical properties and high, long-term useful temperatures. 
  - Polymer SPs (PEI, PAI, PI, Bismaleinimide) 
  Because of the imide group's and the aromatic molecule 
groups' stability, the polymer SPs have a characteristic 
properties profile: 


    -  high strength at a temperature range from -270 degrees 
to +300 degrees C 
  -  very good long-lasting temperature resistance 
  -  very good wear resistance 
  -  good dielectric properties 
  -  high radiation resistance 
  -  low gas evolution losses in high vacuum 
  -  good chemical resistance 
  -  high flame resistance 
  A wide range of polymer SP materials is currently 
commercially available. Besides pure polymer SPs, there are 
modifications with amide, ether or ester groups. The temperature 
resistance of imide materials that essential depends on the 
glass transition temperature, degree of interlinking and 
thermo-oxidative resistance, increases in the series PEI PAI PI. 
  Polyetherimide [PEI] is a thermoplast and the simplest to 
process of the imide materials. The ether groups among the imide 
groups provide this material with exceptional fluidity and 
correspondingly problem-free processability. 
  Polyamideimide [PAI] is included among the duroplasts. The 
amide groups produce a certain flexibility and ductility. The 
material is at the top of temperature-resistant 
injection-molding synthetics. Processing is correspondingly 
sensitive. 
  Duroplastic polymer SPs [PI] can only be processed with 
difficulty because of their physical properties. Advanced 
processing is also hard as a result of the insolubility and the 
duroplastic behavior of the chemically "ready" polymer SPs. For 
this reason, among others, soluble polymer SPs are produced 
through polycondensation and -addition and the resulting 
products, e.g., fibers, sheets and powder, are produced from the 
polymer solution. 
  Bismaleinimide [BMI], a duroplast, affords another approach 
to solving the processing problems. In its case, the functional 
monomers or low molecular prepolymers, whose basic building 
blocks are interlinked via imide functions, are polymerized and 
networked during the processing. Various modifications of the 
bismaleinimides through variations of comonomers lead to 
materials that are, for example, less brittle and tolerant of 
high temperatures. 
  - Polyetherketones (PEK, PEEK, PAEK) 
  The tight linear linkage of aromatic ring structures via 
oxygen bridges through oxidative coupling leads to highly 
liquescent, partially crystalline thermoplasts like 
polyetherketone[PEK], polyetheretherketone [PEEK] and 
polyaryletherketone [PAEK] having an exception properties 
profile: 


    -  high rigidity and strength across a very wide range of 
temperatures 
  -  permanent temperature resistance up to 260 degrees C 
  -  good electrical insulation capacity 
  -  exceptional resistance to hydrolysis 
  -  low flammability 
  -  very good resistance to high-energy radiation. 
  - Polysulphones (PSU, PES) 
  In the case of polysulphones the interlinking of aromatic 
ring structures via SO[.sup]2[/] bridges is realized through 
polycondensation. The result of this is hard, amorphous 
thermoplasts whose mechanical and thermal properties are 
comparable with those of polyetherketones and that also possess 
an entire line of special properties: 


    -  good electrical and dielectric properties (PES, above 
all) 
  -  high resistance to chemicals, IR, _b_, _g_ radiation 
  -  high permeability for microwaves 
  -  high flame resistance with low smoke development 
  -  clear, slightly yellowish transparency 
  This group of products is of interest, above all, for the 
kind of applications where transparency is also required from 
highly critical mechanical, electrical and thermal parts. 
  - Polyphenylenesulphide (PPS) 
  Polyphenylenesulphide is a partially crystalline, covalent 
thermoplast whose degree of crystallinity and hence the 
properties of the preform depend very much on the processing 
temperatures. 
  In this material the properties are characterized by the 
linking of aromatic ring structures via S bridges through 
polycondensation: 


    -  high strength, rigidity and hardness 
  -  permanently useful temperatures up to 240 degrees C 
  -  good scuff resistance 
  -  chemical resistance 
  -  high flame resistance 
  -  good insulating properties 
  This material finds application anywhere that very highly 
critical mechanical, electrical, thermal, and chemical preforms 
are required. 
  - Fluoropolymers 
  Fluoropolymers are noted for the following properties: 


    -  exceptionally high chemical resistance 
  -  very good electrical insulating and dielectric properties 
  -  non-combustibility 
  -  special resistance to atmospheric corrosion 
  -  very low coefficients of friction 
  -  anti-adhesive 
  -  usable over a wide temperature range (-200 to +300 degrees C) 
  Their applied possibilities, however, are limited because of 
their difficult processing and high production costs. 
  - Liquid crystal polymers [LCP] 
  These self-reinforcing polymers constitute a new category of 
material. They are characterized by a state of high molecular 
orderliness. In the solid state they are regular and highly 
ordered fibers of the same polymers interleaved in the LCP 
matrix. Their exceptional mechanical properties are comparable 
to those of composite materials, e.g., in the case of liquid 
crystal polyesters [LC-PET], strength, rigidity and resistance 
could be increased nearly 300-1000 percent compared with PET, 
albeit anisotropically. Moreover, they can be processed on 
traditional thermoplast processing machinery and no bonding 
problems between fiber and matrix surface. 
  However, LCP can only be synthesized with difficulty for 
higher yield and are correspondingly expensive. They are 
projected for promising applications in the electrical industry, 
optoelectronics and in the manufacture of vehicles and aircraft. 
  Another approach to the development of new polymer materials 
with new possibilities for application is the advanced 
development of appropriate polymers from the category of 
technical synthetics as well as the polymer blends where 
synergistic improvements in properties are attempted through the 
blending of appropriate polymers. In this case the boundaries 
between technical polymers and high-performance polymers 
inevitably become fluid. 
  - Polycarbonates with high heat resistance [Co-PC] 
  These new copolymers are amorphous thermoplastic synthetics 
that display similar properties as polycarbonate although they 
possess a thermoform resistance up to 239 degrees C. By 
appropriate blending of polycarbonates with traditional 
bisphenol A-Polycarbonate the entire application range of 
thermoform resistance between 150 degrees C and 239 degrees C 
can be covered. 
  - Blends 
  Blending technology enables combinations of properties 
wherein the advantages of the individual components are combined 
into new properties profiles that the respective basic 
components do not realize. For example, there are blends from 
Polycarbonate, polyester and elastomers for the manufacture of 
aircraft, blends from glass fiber reinforced polymer SP and 
specific elastomers, in which high rigidity is combined with 
impact resistance. 
  Polymer blends may be single phase (components able to blend 
with one another), multi-phase (components partially blendable) 
and "forcibly coupled" (components completely incapable of 
blending). In the latter instance, inter-penetrating networks 
are involved wherein two polymer networks fully independent one 
of the other are produced in such a way that they mutually 
inter-penetrate. 
<H5>  Functional polymers </H5>
  Increasingly gaining in importance are polymers with quite 
specific functional properties that up until the present were 
either uncommon or even unknown. For example, electrical 
conductivity instead of insulation, or even rapid chemical and 
physical change under the influence of light instead of 
inertness to radiation. 
  Such polymers include: 


    -  polymers with special electrical properties 
  -  Electrically conductive polymers, e.g., polypyrrol, 
polyaniline or polyacetylene, that acquire their conductivity 
only after doping (i.e., conversion with powerful oxidation or 
reduction agents), are already used in the form of flexible 
sheets for the production of new, rechargeable batteries. The 
most recent conductive polymers can also be heated occasionally 
to 300 degrees C without decomposing. 
  -  Piezo-electric polymers are based on fluoropolymers (PVF, 
PVDF) and because of their elasticity they have distinct 
advantages compared with conventional crystals and ceramics and 
are of interest for the communications mass market (e.g., 
microphones, telephone earpieces). 
  -  Polymers with special optical properties 
  -  polymer beam waveguides based on polymethylmethacrylate 
[PMMA], polystyrol [PS] or polycarbonate [PC] already constitute 
a cost-effective alternative to glass fibers for close range 
optoelectronic data processing. 
  -  Polymers for optical data storage for some time now have 
been used as photopolymers in the form of light or electron beam 
sensitive masking material in microchip production. The 
development, above all, of special liquid crystal polymers (side 
chain LCP) is very promising here. 
  -  Polymers as optical sensors change their optical 
properties under the influence of gases and vapors and are used 
in sensor systems for solvents. 
  -  Polymers having special biological properties 

    Besides platform materials for fixing of enzymes 
(biocatalysts) and biosensor system components, 
non-thrombogenous polymers, above all, for direct contact with 
the blood and polymers based on fluoropolymers as substitute 
blood are also of interest. 
  In concluding, ultra-thin polymer films also deserve mention 
at this point. They are still in the basic research stage, but 
their applications, e.g., as high resolution photoresists in the 
production of micro-electronics or in optical computers already 
appear feasible and highly promising. Because of their diverse 
physical properties they also hold promise for biosensors and 
medical engineering. 
<H5>  High-performance polymers production process </H5>
  The properties of high-performance polymer components stem 
from the optimized combination of a process of synthesis and 
advanced processing. Chart 4.12 illustrates the most important 
processing principles in the individual net product stages of 
high-performance polymers. 
  High-temperature resistant thermoplasts, above all, raise 
the 
issue of economical processability. These materials are highly 
viscous in the processing sector and as a result are free 
flowing to only a limited extent. Interdisciplinary cooperation 
between materials development and production engineering is 
gaining more and more importance here to solve this key problem 
in the processing of high-performance polymers. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-98A>        Chart 4.12: Important net product stages and processing principles in the production of </FIG>

  The fundamental challenges in the processing of synthetics 
are primarily the reduction of production costs for the products 
that are produced and improved product quality. In this context, 
the boundaries between the discrete net product stages become 
increasingly blurred. So-called direct processing integrates 
several processing steps. The reaction extruder can be mentioned 
here, whereby polymer reaction, synthetics processing (e.g., 
inclusion of flame retardant additives) and shaping (extrusion) 
are combined into a single processing step. 
  In the case of the optical beam waveguide, the optical 
properties could be improved through integrated process 
management. Direct processing is closely linked to automation 
designs, on-line quality controls and systems of quality 
assurance. 
  In the shaping process, innovative processing variations in 
injection molding, above all, deserve notice: core melting 
engineering, dual-component injection molding, internal gas 
pressure process and inter-spray engineering. 
<H5>  Fields of application for high-performance polymers </H5>
  The possible applications of high-performance polymers are 
as 
diverse as the combinations of properties that are often already 
united in a single one of those materials. Hence, only a survey 
of applications and useful fields for the most important 
materials will be given here. A systematic approach can be based 
on a division of applied aspects, depending on whether a 
mechanical, thermal, chemical or nuclear properties profile is 
foremost or whether the application is determined by electrical, 
optical or biological properties. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-010L-99A>        Chart 4.13: Selective fields of application for high-performance polymersarket growth </FIG>

<H5>   Market growth </H5>
  For 1990, the international market for high-performance 
polymer materials as basic materials is projected to be nearly 
DM3.0 billion. By the year 1995, that market volume is likely to 
increase to nearly DM4.5 billion and by the year 2,000 another 
increase is forecast, up to nearly DM7.0 billion. 
  If the next net product stages of high-performance polymers 
are analyzed, that is, semi-finished products/components, then 
international market volume for 1990 is projected to be nearly 
DM24.0 billion. Internationally, that market volume is likely to 
rise by the year 1995 to DM37.0 billion and by the year 2,000 to 
nearly DM56.0 billion (see chart 4.14). 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-100A>        Chart 4.14: Projected international market volume for high-performance polymers as </FIG>

  The DM24.0 billion market volume for high-performance 
polymers is distributed among the leading industrial nations as 
follows: the U.S., at 37 percent, holds the lion's share of the 
market, followed by Europe with 34 percent and Japan with 22 
percent of international market share. On the international 
market for high-performance polymers, the FRG holds an 
approximately 15 percent share. 
  A listing of high-performance polymer consumption by 
branches 
demonstrates, on a first estimate, a clear focus in two 
branches. Nearly 70 percent of high-performance polymers are 
used in Europe in electrical engineering/electronics and in 
vehicle manufacturing. Other branches, e.g., machine building, 
telecommunications, medicine and aerospace are of significantly 
less significance. 
<H5>  Development trends </H5>
  Acquiring increasing importance are polymers having quite 
specific functional properties. Foremost here are polymers 
having special electrical and optical properties. In this 
context, liquid crystal polymers (side chain-LCP) are of 
particular interest as well as ultra-thin polymer films and 
non-C based polymers. 
  An additional line of development is polymers having 
customized combinations of properties. They are realized by the 
production of blends, the synthesis of ordered copolymers or 
block copolymers or a combination of such lines. A particularly 
interesting development in the field of blends is 
interpenetrating networks [IPN]. 
  Rather considerable significance attaches to the reduction 
of 
production costs and improved product quality. The development 
trend here is the integration of several processing steps that 
is closely linked to automation designs, on-line quality 
controls and systems of quality assurance. 
  In the realization of such development potential, diverse 
new 
applications open up, above all, on the mass market for 
electrical engineering/electronics. Even polymers having 
customized combinations of properties afford a sizable potential 
for development targeted, above all, on mass applications in 
vehicle construction as well as on new possible applications in 
electrical engineering/electronics. 
<H5>  4.2.2.4 High-performance metallic materials and </H5>
semi-conductors 
<H5>  4.2.2.4.1 High-performance metals and alloys </H5>
<H5>  Survey </H5>
  Metals are characterized by a large number of electrons in 
motion. This results in many of the properties specific to 
metals, e.g., high electrical conductivity, good reflectivity 
and high heat conductivity. Metals crystallize in highly 
symmetrical grids of high density. The manner and fashion in 
which the grids are joined one to the other (mostly 
three-dimensionally body centered or three-dimensionally plane 
centered) influence many of the mechanical properties. In this 
connection, it is precisely the flaws in the regular arrangement 
of the grid levels that decisively determine such properties as 
ductility and brittleness or even high-temperature behaviors. 
Currently, the targeted influencing, above all, of this 
microstructure through new alloys and new production and 
processing methods is leading to the development of new, 
high-grade metallic materials. 
  Chart 4.15 provides a survey of the most import metallic 
materials in engineering 
  Depending on production quantities and turnover, steel tops 
all structural and functional materials around the world. The 
useful temperature range for modern steels ranges from -270 
degrees C in freezing techniques (austenitic steels) up to a 
maximum of +1,200 degrees C (ferritic superalloys) in the 
combustion chambers of jet engines. Steel technology has 
advanced so far by now that further development predominantly 
concentrates on improving properties that play a crucial role in 
component behaviors in the respective applied sectors. Such 
further developments are occurring primarily in the fields of 
weldable steels, superplastic moldable steels and dual-phase 
steels, whereby the latter possess high strength and 
simultaneously good moldability. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-101A>        Chart 4.15: Materials-oriented division of high-performance metallic materials </FIG>

  On the other hand, fresh developments, above all, among 
non-ferrous metals, fit in with high-performance metals and 
alloys that open up new, promising applied alternatives on the 
basis of their properties profiles. 
<H5>  Metallic structural materials </H5>
  Development goals for structural materials among 
high-performance metals and alloys, among whose application 
mechanical, thermal and chemical properties are foremost, are, 
above all, weight reduction, definite increase in strength and 
rigidity and even higher useful temperatures with improved 
resistance to oxidation and corrosion. 
  Equivalent requirements are engendered, for instance, by the 
development of increasingly more effective and fuel-efficient 
engines and gas turbines in the automobile industry and 
aerospace and even energy output. 
  - Aluminum alloys 
  The light metal, aluminum [Al], possesses a number of 
properties that justify its special significance in many fields 
of engineering: 


    -  high availability 
  -  low density 
  -  high specific-weight strength 
  -  good chemical resistance 
  -  good ability to be reshaped 
  -  castability 
  Its lack of heat resistance and surface qualities (when used 
up to 300 degrees C) is a drawback and for this reason it can be 
used practically only when alloyed. 
  The combination of the lightest of all metals, lithium [Li], 
with aluminum leads to a group of materials that is of major 
interest, above all, for weight reduction considerations. 
Aluminum-lithium alloys having 2.5 percent lithium have a weight 
savings of nine percent and only a 20 percent higher specific 
rigidity compared with conventional Al alloys. The maximum 
percentage of Li currently totals eight percent in the 
laboratory. Using modern production technologies, for example, 
rapid congealing or mechanical alloying, it is possible to 
increase the percentage of lithium perhaps even higher. 
  Li's high reactivity is a problem for the production of 
Al-Li 
alloys. Working with them calls for an inert atmosphere (helium) 
and heedfulness of safety considerations (danger of explosion, 
toxic vapors). 
  - Magnesium alloys 
  Because of magnesium's low density compared with aluminum, 
magnesium alloys too are interesting as lightweight design 
materials. Traditional magnesium alloys, however, are 
characterized by low strength, low ductility and high 
susceptibility to corrosion. But as of now, using powder 
metallurgical processing and the addition of yttrium and 
neodymium enhance magnesium alloys to the point where they 
approximate the strength and ductility grades of high-strength 
aluminum alloys. 
  Magnesium-lithium alloys are undergoing research, above all, 
in the field of combinations of light-metal alloys with 
compound-forming gases like oxygen, nitrogen and hydrogen. 
Three-dimensional body centered magnesium-lithium basic alloys 
with an Li content of 31-50 percent display very low density. 
But their use in light construction is extremely limited because 
of high susceptibility to corrosion and rapid loss of matrix 
strength above room temperature. 
  - Titanium alloys 
  In the series of light metals, Mg-Al-Ti, Titanium [Ti] 
displays the greatest density and the highest strength. Titanium 
alloys are characterized by 


    -  high specific-weight strength 
  -  high oscillatory resistance 
  -  high fracture toughness 
  -  high creep resistance 
  -  good corrosion resistance 
  Development goals here are high-temperature resistant, creep 
resistant titanium alloys that can replace the very difficult 
superalloys in many applications. Maximum useful temperatures 
are situated at approximately 70 percent of its allotropic 
conversion temperature (nearly 650 degrees C). 
  - Superalloys 
  Superalloys (mostly Ni- or Co-based) are based on two phases 
whose grid parameters diverge only slightly from one another and 
this leads to consistent, elastic grid tension. There is only a 
slight interface tension between the phases. Displacement 
motions in the material are rendered difficult. The result is 
such exceptional properties as: 


    -  good thermal resistance 
  -  useful temperatures up to 1,200 degrees C 
  -  high strength 
  -  very good corrosion resistance 
  Through the production of single-crystal 
(non-intercrystalline) structures, the creep resistance of a 
component can be increased even further and intercrystalline 
stabilizing elements like Hf, Zr and B can be dispensed with. A 
possibly drastic reduction of carbon also causes an increase in 
melting temperature and as a result, higher useful temperatures. 
The single crystal structural development of Ni-based alloys has 
already been introduced into the production of turbine buckets 
in aircraft. 
  Superalloys based on wolfram, molybdenum and tantalum, whose 
melting points are more then 2,500 degrees C, are still in the 
development stage. Problems here arise, above all, from the 
inadequate corrosion resistance of such metals. 
  - Intermetallic compounds 
  Intermetallic compounds are virtually stochiometrically 
combined alloys that, on the basis of the nature of their 
bonding, fall between metals and ceramics. In recent years, they 
have attracted growing interest in the quest for new 
high-temperature materials with better high-temperature 
resistance than the most advanced Ni-based superalloys. Foremost 
among them are primarily nickel aluminide Ni[.sup]3[/]Al and 
titanium aluminide Ti[.sup]3[/]Al. Using appropriate 
additions of alloys and thermomechanical processing, the 
inherent brittleness of most intermetallic compounds could be 
definitely reduced at low temperatures (below about 680 degrees 
C). The specific strengths of both aluminides at all 
temperatures remain higher than those of Ni-based superalloys. A 
remaining problem is their unsatisfactory resistance to 
oxidation and corrosion above 800 degrees C. 
  Other prominent intermetallic compounds that display not 
only 
good high-temperature resistance but also good resistance to 
oxidation at a planned useful temperature range are: _b_-TiAl 
and NiAl, intermetallic compounds of the Ti-Al-Si and Ni-Cr-Al 
systems with surprisingly high melting points, NbAl[.sup]3[/] 
and TiAl[.sup]3[/], whose brittleness at low temperatures, 
however, is still pronounced. 
  - Oxide-dispersion solidified alloys [ODS alloys] 
  Dispersion solidification is an additional approach to 
increasing the useful temperatures of metallic materials besides 
the avoidance of granular interfaces or optimizing of the 
intercrystalline cycle (e.g., single-crystal alloys and 
appropriately congealed alloys). In dispersion-solidified alloys 
the displacement motion is also interfered with by thermally 
stable, finely distributed ceramic particles. 
  ODS-Ni-based alloys have now realized absolute useful 
temperatures of up to 90 percent of the melting point. For 
aluminum alloys they are now at approximately 50 percent of the 
melting point and therefore still afford considerable 
development potential. Even the dispersion solidification of 
intermetallic phases is the subject of intensive development 
activity since new properties profiles and, consequently, new 
fields of application for those materials are now emerging. 
  In conclusion, two other special materials deserve mention. 
Because of their rather special structural properties they have 
drawn increasing interest. 
  - Memory metals 
  Memory metals are memory-shaped alloys based on Cu-Zn or 
Ni-Ti and most recently even on Fe-Ni. They possess two stable 
states that, depending on the temperature, adapt themselves 
through a reversible martensite-austenite structural 
transformation. This effect is exploited, for example, in 
release elements in space, for pipe connections or highly 
reliable plug-and-socket connections in electronics. 
  - Foam metals 
  In the quest for especially light metallic materials in 
recent years foam metals were developed on the model of foamed 
plastics. In this process, for example, pores are introduced 
through the admixture of a gas separation propellant into a 
rapidly cooling molten aluminum. Closed-pore structures can be 
used for their mechanical properties. Open-pore foam metals are 
available for applications where highly specific surfaces are 
required (filters, catalysts). 
<H5>  Functional metallic materials </H5>
  Among high-performance metals and alloys, it is above all 
the 
exceptional electrical and magnetic properties of the functional 
materials that are foremost among the applied aspects. 
  - Superconducting metallic materials 
  At very low temperatures below 20 K, various metal alloys 
are 
superconductive, that is, their electrical resistance drops to 
zero. The very high current densities of superconducting metal 
alloys facilitate the manufacture of extremely powerful 
electromagnets. Superconducting materials are also used for 
rectifiers and transformers. Meanwhile, a large number of 
different materials are available, including NbTi with very high 
ductility or Nb[.sup]3[/]Sn. Besides new alloys, development 
goals are also, above all, new production techniques. For 
example, production is done in the case of Nb[.sup]3[/]Ge by 
means of chemical vapour deposition [CVD] from a metal chloride 
blend onto a band. Nb[.sup]3[/]Ga and Nb[.sup]3[/]Al are 
melted from the metals by means of a laser beam on a band 
surface. 
  New superconducting materials are metal oxides and ceramics, 
for instance, based on Ba-Cu-O rare earths whose superconducting 
properties are already being used under 100 K and that therefore 
have to be cooled only with liquid nitrogen (instead of with 
liquid helium). Besides the high cost of production, it is, 
above all, the brittleness of such materials, for example, in 
terms of producing wire for magnetic coils, that is a problem 
for application. 
  - Permanent-magnet materials 
  The development of permanent magnets is characterized by 
endeavors to augment maximum energy density by increasing 
residual magnetism or the coercive field strength. Rare earth 
permanent-magnet materials are of primary significance here. 
Co-Sm-based permanent materials having a nearly sevenfold higher 
energy density compared to traditional hard ferrite materials 
are already in commercial use. 
  New Fe-Nd-B-based developments are even manifesting a 
ninefold higher energy density and are superior to all other 
permanent-magnet materials in the magnetic level. 
  - Low-retentivity materials: amorphous and nano-crystalline 
metals 
  Low-retentivity materials are characterized by reduced 
coercive field strengths. Not only are traditional Ni-Co-Fe 
alloys, but, above all, amorphous metals interesting for use, 
e.g., in transformers, magnetic heads and flexible magnetic 
shieldings. They are produced by extremely rapid cooling of the 
molten material (up to nearly one million degrees per second) 
with the amorphous liquid structure "frozen in" as it were and 
the result being metallic glass. Their properties depend, above 
all, on the composition of the alloy and can be influenced by 
targeted heat processing. They possess considerable hardness and 
wear resistance, high tensile strength and great elasticity. 
Whereas, in the case of conventional amorphous alloys (e.g., Fe, 
Co or Ni and Si or B) the amorphous state is stable up to 
approximately 400 degrees C, the latest AL-based metallic 
glasses are indicating stability up to 520 degrees C. 
  - Nano-crystalline metals 
  Nano-crustalline metals are polycrystalline materials that 
are created from crystallites having a diameter of less than 10 
nm. They result from the appropriate selection of alloy 
composition and heat processing through crystallization of 
originally amorphous metals or through powder metallurgy with 
very fine-grained powders. A sizable percentage of the volume of 
the material in this inter-amorphous and crystalline state 
consists of granular boundaries. Initial research results 
indicate very interesting physical properties, particularly in 
low-retentivity behavior. 
<H5>  Production process for high-performance metallic materials </H5>
  The modern production and processing method has crucial 
significance for the targeted influencing of the microstructure 
and micro-configuration. Conventional alloys are able to be 
produced in this way that previously were impossible and that 
distinctly improve the properties of such alloys. For the first 
time ever, many new alloys could be realized by means of the new 
production processes. The most important of these are described 
below. 
  - Powder metallurgy 
  Powder metallurgy, as a modern production process, has 
acquired considerable significance in recent years. It is 
characterized by the production of powdered alloys and 
subsequent compaction of the powder into semi-finished products 
and components. 
  Chart 4.16 is a compilation of the most important processing 
principles in the individual net product stages of 
high-performance metallic materials. 
  pick 

<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-105A>      Chart 4.16: Important net product stages and processing principles in powder </FIG>

  In addition to good structural homogeneity and chemical 
homogeneity, the advantages of powder metallurgy are, above all, 
the ability to produce fine-grained structures, near-net-shape 
component production, the possibility of producing special 
structures (e.g., having ceramic particles for dispersion 
solidification) and the alloying of non-blendable metals. 
  A major problem in the powder metallurgical production of 
materials is the increased risk of structural flaws (e.g., 
ceramic inclusions due to contaminated powder, pores due to 
inadequate sinter density, etc.). Development is targeting new 
technologies for the production of even cleaner powder and a 
better understanding of the cyclical processes in powder 
compaction. 
  - Directional solidification 
  Directional solidification is one of the most important new 
production processes. In it, alloys are produced in such a way 
through appropriate crystallization of the cast material in the 
casting mold that all the granular boundaries run parallel to 
the external single-axis charge, e.g., in a radial direction for 
rotating turbine buckets. Using a similar process, components 
wholly free of granular boundaries (e.g., single-crystal bucket) 
can be produced. Directional solidification also enables the 
production of eutectic superalloys (e.g., Ni-Al-Mo) wherein an 
alloy component forms long fibers in the matrix of the other 
components that are aligned in the direction of the 
solidification. 
  - Rapid solidification 
  Through rapid chilling of the molten alloy meta-stable 
alloys 
can be produced, whose properties occasionally differ 
considerably from those of the corresponding equilibrium phases. 
To cool the melted material rapidly enough, cooling rates of 
approximately 100 to 10[.sup]6[/] K/second are required. This 
is realized through application onto good heat-conducting 
contact surfaces: e.g., a copper wheel or a flow of gas or a jet 
of water for the production of powders for atomization. The 
dimension of products produced in this way, however, is limited 
because of the high cooling rates. Powder particles on order are 
smaller than about 60 nm and the metallic glass produced using a 
copper wheel (melt spinning) can be produced only in the form of 
strips or sheets with thicknesses of less than 100 nm. 
Amorphization using thin-film solid-state reactions [SSR] 
constitutes one approach to solving this problem. It is a 
process that is still in the research stage. Research has 
demonstrated that with appropriate alloy elements and selection 
of reactive conditions, metastable equilibriums, that is, 
amorphous phases can be regulated, also through a pure 
controlled-diffusion solid-state reaction. So far, this has 
essentially been successful with alternating vapor deposition 
thin films (respective thicknesses of several nm). This process 
is interesting, above all, for the production of compact 
amorphous materials that are no longer restricted in their 
dimensions. 
  - Mechanical alloying [MA] 
  Mechanical alloying is used primarily to produce powders 
having fine dispersion solidified oxide particles [ODS powders]. 
However, this process finds application even in the production 
of amorphous powders and non-blendable alloys. In that case, 
small particles of the metals to be alloyed are put in a ball 
mill rotating at high speed. The steady process of bonding and 
breakup of he metal particles by the steel balls results in a 
very fine, homogenous powder that can be further processed in an 
appropriate powder metallurgical manner. 
<H5>  Areas of application for high-performance metallic materials </H5>
  Applications for high-performance metallic materials 
reflect, 
through their diversity, the increasingly predominant position 
that metals and alloys are assuming among the materials. 
  The reason for this is primarily the extraordinarily high 
capability for recycling, not to mention the many years of 
experience and established production, processing and repair 
processes. Chart 4.17 provides a survey of the most important 
areas of application. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-107A>        Chart 4.17: Selective properties and areas of application for high-performance metallic </FIG>

<H5>  Market growth </H5>
  For 1990, the international market for high-performance 
metallic materials as basic materials is projected to be nearly 
DM1.8 billion. By the year 1995, this market volume is likely to 
increase to nearly DM3.0 billion and by the year 2,000 to nearly 
DM4.0 billion. 
  At the next net product stage, namely, semi-finished 
products 
and components, an international market volume totaling DM11.0 
billion was projected for 1990. By the year 1995, that market 
volume is forecast to increase to DM19.0 billion and in the year 
2,000 to nearly DM30.0 billion (see chart 4.18). 
  In the next decade, an annual average growth rate of nearly 
10 percent is projected for high-performance metals and alloys. 
Deep differences surface when the anticipated annual growth 
rates for the individual high-performance metals are analyzed. 
For example, an annual three percent growth is projected 
internationally for titanium and titanium alloys. For 
aluminum-lithium alloys, on the other hand, an annual average 
growth far in excess of 10 percent is projected. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-108A>        Chart 4.18: Estimated international market volume of high-performance metallic </FIG>

<H5>  Development trends </H5>
  Foremost for high-performance metallic materials is first 
the 
increase in the useful temperatures of alloys already being used 
up to their natural limits (melting point, allotropic conversion 
points) and the improvement, above all, of fatigue properties. 
Also taking on increasing importance is making available new 
sorts of high-performance metallic materials like 
high-temperature intermetallic compounds and alloys having a 
nano-crystalline structure whose physical properties differ 
significantly from crystalline and amorphous materials and make 
completely new applications appear possible. 
  At present, new production and processing technologies are 
playing an essential role in targeted structural influencing. 
Directional solidification allows production of materials having 
granular boundaries that run parallel or materials without 
granular boundaries. Rapid solidification facilitates the 
production of fine alloy powder for powder metallurgy as well as 
production of meta-stable alloys. 
  In powder metallurgy there are developments that target the 
integration of a number of processing steps: in the Osprey 
process, powder production and compaction are combined into a 
single operational step primarily solving the problem of powder 
contamination. 
<H5>  4.2.2.4.2 Semiconductors </H5>
<H5>  Survey </H5>
  Unlike metals, semiconductors are materials whose electrical 
conductivity vanishes at lower temperatures and at technically 
interesting temperatures (approximately 25 degrees C) falls 
between metals and insulators. 
  The covalent bonding of semiconductors can react in an 
especially sensitive way to various stimuli (thermal, electrical 
or optical) and that is what essentially underlies their major 
physical and technical significance. Whereas the intrinsic 
conductivity of semiconductors is mostly undesirable, the 
extrinsic conductivity induced by the targeted insertion of 
impurities (doping) make them extremely significant for most 
applications. 
  Because of their complex structures and the associated 
positional dependency of the properties for semiconductor 
components, the reproducibility of structures and properties has 
to be guaranteed down to submicro-regions. 
  Semiconductor components are far superior, primarily in 
speed 
and conductivity, to vacuum tubes. From a materials-oriented 
optic, semiconductors may be divided into elemental and compound 
semiconductors. However, nano-structured semiconductors and 
non-conductive metals, in which the chemical properties of the 
material that is used is not foremost, are increasingly an 
object of research. 
  - Elemental semiconductors 
  In semiconductor engineering and microelectronics, silicon 
continues to hold sway. With its high chemical and structural 
resistance and refined methods of isolating and seeding large 
single crystals, it embodies nearly optimum properties. 
  Fresh developments in the field of silicon technology are 
based primarily on four materials: polysilicon, silicide, 
silicon on sapphire [SOS] and silicon on insulator [SOI] 
materials. 
  Polysilicon consists of a large number of tiny 
crystallites and differs in its intrinsic properties from single 
crystal silicon. It is an insulating platform and filler 
material, constitutes the startup substance for monocrystalline, 
semiconducting films and with a boost from doping can be varied 
in its conductivity from nearly intrinsic conductivity to good 
conductivity. 
  Metal silicides are compounds between silicon and 
metal. They possess not only high hardness but also, in most 
cases, high-temperature stability and are generally used 
wherever polysilicon resistances are unacceptably great because 
of increasing levels of integration. 
  SOS materials consist of a vapor deposition silicon 
film on a monocrystalline Al[.sup]2[/]O[.sup]3[/] platform 
(sapphire), that display polycrystalline and now increasingly 
monocrystalline structures. The result is an ability to realize 
higher package densities, signal speeds and switching operations. 
  SOI materials are advanced developments of SOS 
materials. Sapphire as well as monocrystalline silicon are used 
as the platform materials of the approximately 100 nm thick 
silicon films. However, this necessitates the production of an 
amorphous insulating film from SiO[.sup]2[/] or 
Si[.sup]3[/]N[.sup]4[/]. 
  - Compound semiconductors 
  Unlike elemental semiconductors, compound semiconductors are 
composed of the molecules of a compound. The most important 
class of compound semiconductors consists of compounds of the 
elements of groups III and V of the periodic table: 
  III: aluminum [Al], boron [B], gallium [Ga], indium [In] 
  V: antimony [Sb], arsenic [As], phosphorus [P] 
  One important and thoroughly studied representative of these 
semiconductors is gallium arsenide [GaAs]. Because of the 
sizable platform mobility compared with Si, the results are 
higher switch speeds and lower energy requirements. The 
production and acquisition of acoustic signals are also possible 
as well as conversion and advanced processing of electrical and 
optical signals. This guarantees GaAs and compound 
semiconductors a prominent position in the field of 
optoelectronics. 
  Offsetting these advantages, however, among other things, 
are 
significantly difficult production and the quandary that 
occasionally, mature Si technologies are not applicable to GaAs 
and the development of new processing technologies is required. 
  In addition to binary compound semiconductors there are also 
ternary and quaternary ones, that is, containing three or four 
elements. The special importance of these compounds resides in 
the possibility of being able to regulate the band interval and 
lattice constants of a material over broad ranges independently 
of one another. The most important representative of III-V 
ternary compound semiconductors is aluminum-gallium-arsenide. 
For quaternary, it is indium-gallium-arsenide-phosphide. From 
class II-VI semiconductors, some photoconductors, namely, zinc 
sulphide and cadmium sulphide, are primarily of interest. The 
sole representative of IV-VI compound semiconductors is silicon 
carbide in monocrystalline form and possessing high temperature 
resistance. 
  One of the most important and most interesting innovations 
in 
semiconductor technologies is the production of heterostructural 
crystals and heterostructural superlattices. This entails, for 
example, appropriately combining two (binary) II-V compounds 
with one another alternately in nano-thin films. The result is 
artificial structures in which platform mobility is drastically 
enhanced ("hot electrons"). In such artificial structures the 
possibilities for variation are extremely broad. And for the 
most part, there still exist unexplored possibilities for the 
development of new materials having new sorts of electrical and 
optical properties that cannot be realized on the basis of the 
source materials and ordinary crystals. 
  - Nano-structured semiconductors 
  In nano-structured semiconductors the chemical properties of 
the material being used are no longer uppermost but rather 
"smallest dimension effects," that is, essentially, quantum 
effects. Through appropriate structuring, control of platform 
mobility across a geometric parameter, that is, nanometer-range 
film thicknesses, is realized. 
  - Non-conducting metals [SIMIT effect] 
  The effect of non-conducting metals 
(Sized-Induced-Metal/Insulator-Transition) only becomes 
noticeable when the structure is reduced to nanometer 
dimensions. Beginning with a threshold value of approximately 
two m the conductivity of the metal grains drops off 
proportionately to the crystal volume. 
  In the nanometer range, the metal thereby turns into an 
insulator and a "non-conducting metal." Through the targeted 
insertion of non-conductive metallic particles into the ceramic 
platform material, totally new materials having customized 
electrical and magnetic properties can be produced, especially 
as absorbent materials in HF engineering. The new, simply 
structured and extremely small "Cut off wavelength-" transistor 
[COW] represents one early application. 
<H5>  4.2.2.5 High-performance composite materials </H5>
  Composite materials are typical representatives of new, 
customized materials. By combining various materials or groups 
of materials, it becomes possible to merge favorable properties 
into a single component that cannot be realized with any of the 
materials in isolation. Such properties include, among other 
things: 


    -  high strength 
  -  high rigidity 
  -  low specific weight 
  -  resistance to materials fatigue 
  -  favorable creep behavior 
  -  low thermal expansion at high thermal cycling 
  -  good chemical resistance and corrosion resistance (composites 
with polymer and ceramic matrices). 
  Chart 4.19 presents a materials-oriented division of 
composite materials. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-110A>        Chart 4.19: Materials-oriented division of high-performance composite materials </FIG>


  High-performance composite materials include materials 
having 
a polymer, ceramic, or metallic matrix. 
  Besides the nature of the matrix, the geometry of the 
reinforcing elements is a criterion for classification. 
Essentially, the latter are: 


    -  particles 
  -  short fibers, whiskers or platelets 
  -  long fibers. 
  Particle reinforcement is used primarily for metals. Short 
fibers (mm/cm range), whiskers (m range), crystals or 
platelets are employed mostly for production engineering motives 
although their reinforcement effect is limited. This also 
applies to molecular composites, e.g., self-reinforcing liquid 
crystal polymers [LCP] or precipitation hardened metals. Only 
perfectly parallel direction short fibers as of a specific 
length/diameter ratio approach the reinforcement properties of 
continuous long fibers. 
  For actual high-performance applications, therefore, 
long-fiber reinforced composite materials are mostly employed. 
  Combining two or more materials into a single composite 
levies some basic requirements on the components of the 
composite: e.g., chemical and mechanical tolerance, adequate 
bonding and interlacing among components, coordination of the 
components' fusion temperatures. 
  While tensile strength/impact resistance and fracture 
toughness of fiber composite materials primarily depend on the 
fibers, temperature resistance, cross-sectional strength and 
functional properties are mainly determined by the matrix. The 
choice of matrix impacts quite decisively the composite 
material's useful temperature range. 
  Fiber-reinforced polymers are currently the most extensively 
developed and disseminated composite materials, while metal and 
ceramic composite materials are still mostly in the research 
stage. 
<H5>  Composite materials having polymer matrices </H5>
  Duroplasts are currently used as the chief matrix material, 
polyester resins and phenol formaldehydes, but, above all, epoxy 
resins. They allow useful temperatures up to approximately 130 
degrees C. The use of polymer SPs and bismaleinimides has 
already been proven for some applications involving temperatures 
up to 250 degrees C. The development of liquid crystal 
duroplasts targets not only increased useful temperature but 
primarily increased fracture toughness. The disadvantage of 
duroplastic matrices resides in their relative brittleness and 
their protracted polymerization (curing). Also, once cured, 
additional shaping is no longer possible. 
  The new thermoplastic matrices (especially polysulphones, 
polyetherimides and polyetherketones), on the other hand, can be 
reshaped as semi-finished products in heated forms similar to 
sheet metal ("organic sheet"). Besides increased impact 
resistance, they also display a better heat/humidity ratio 
(heating on top/humidity absorption on bottom) that makes them 
interesting, above all, for aircraft construction and the 
vehicle industry. New high-performance thermoplasts that 
manifest permanently useful temperatures comparable to the 
duroplasts, however, are almost 10 times more expensive and 
complicate the production of composite materials primarily 
because of their high fusion viscosity. Currently, glass, 
aramide and carbon fibers are technically important as 
reinforcing materials for polymers. 
  Among glass-fiber reinforced plastics [GFK] only those 
having 
specialty glass fibers [HS glass] manifest reinforced property 
profiles that facilitate new, promising applications and for 
that reason they are the only ones included among 
high-performance composites. 
  Carbon-fiber reinforced plastics [CFK] have had major 
engineering significance for several years now, above all, in 
the aviation industry where they chiefly replace high-strength 
aluminum alloys. The CFK, because of the respective C-fiber 
properties, afford high strength and rigidity with low weight 
and also the possibility of adjusting heat expansion through 
variation in the phase orientation from positive to slightly 
negative, a property that allows for rather special applications 
(e.g., in the manufacture of radio telescopes). 
  A drawback to CFK having a duroplastic matrix in 
high-performance applications is their continued inadequate 
impact and crack resistance as well as the tendency to absorb 
humidity. Under dynamic stress the laminate structure 
experiences flaws that degrade its strength. 
  Aramide-fiber reinforced plastics [AFK] generally find 
application where strength combined with low weight is called 
for at a permanent useful temperature up to 150 degrees C. Among 
the plastic fibers, polyethylene- and polybenzineglyoxaline are 
receiving increasing importance. 
<H5>  Composites having metallic matrices </H5>
  Fiber reinforced metals are still mostly in the development 
stage. They are put to use where rigidity and impact resistance 
but, above all, good heat conductivity and high permanent useful 
temperatures are called for. Development activities are 
concentrated on: 


    -  light metal alloys (magnesium, aluminum, titanium) 
  -  high heat resistance alloys (nickel, cobalt) 
  -  refractory alloys (wolfram, molybdenum, niobium, tantalum) 
  -  materials with special physical properties (conductor 
materials 
like silver, copper; magnetic materials like iron, nickel, 
cobalt; semiconductors like germanium, silicon) 
  -  superalloys. 
  As a light construction material, fiber-reinforced aluminum 
is the most widespread of the fiber-reinforced metals. 
  Carbon, boron, boron nitride, beryllium and steel fibers 
plus 
silicon carbide and aluminum oxide whiskers are mainly used as 
reinforcing fibers. 
<H5>  Composites having ceramic matrices </H5>
  Foremost in the development of ceramic-fiber composites is, 
above all, improvement of fracture toughness and resistance to 
temperature changes. This is most of all a problem of fine 
tuning the fiber-matrix boundaries of the fiber composite. 
  Not only aluminum oxide but also, above all, silicon carbide 
and zirconium oxide have proved their worth as matrix materials. 
Also under development as matrix materials are carbon and glass 
and glass ceramics. SiC, carbon and 
Al[.sup]2[/]O[.sup]3[/] fibers are mostly used as 
reinforcing fibers. 
  A major problem with ceramic composites is the thermal 
stability of the available fibers that rapidly declines in 
oxidizing atmospheres above 1,200 degrees C. The single 
exception is carbon fiber. But even it requires a coating 
because of its susceptibility to oxidation. The higher thermal 
stability of most whiskers and platelets is, among other things, 
an important reason for their inclusion in ceramic matrices. 
  Carbon-reinforced carbon [C/C] currently displays the 
highest 
temperature resistance in non-oxidizing atmospheres (up to 
nearly 2,000 degrees C0 of all the technically available design 
materials). Intensive research efforts are underway for 
protection against oxidation. It also has a relatively low 
specific weight making this material interesting above all for 
high-temperature light construction. Other intrinsic fiber 
reinforced ceramics having a similar property profile, e.g., 
SiC/SiC, have already been established for applications in 
weapons engineering. 
<H5>  Production process for high-performance composite materials </H5>
  Chart 4.20 lists the most important processing principles 
under the individual net product stages of high-performance 
composite materials. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-112A>        Chart 4.20: Important net product stages and processing principles in the production of composite </FIG>


  - Plastic composites 
  Most large surface auto body parts presently are produced by 
absorbing or pressing the liquid resin into a closed mold filled 
with the fibers (resin transfer molding [RTM]). 
  Even in other processes like winding, pultruding, fiber 
injection, among others, liquid resins are used with the fiber 
strands undergoing a resin bath before being embedded. Since 
braiding and interlacing need adequate time and the handling of 
molten or dissolved resins is very complicated, prepregs 
(=pre-material) are generally produced at present with 
processing into preform or semi-finished product being based on 
those. Pressing is the most economical method for larger numbers 
of pieces with liquid resins or liquid prepregs (sheet molding 
compounds [SMC]) also being used. The latter are reliquefied 
under pressure and heat and facilitate the production of 
different wall thicknesses. The autoclave process enables 
production of high-grade parts with different wall thicknesses, 
any directions and sizes, consisting of laminates of precut, 
viscous prepreg textured surfaces that are annealed and cured in 
an oven cycle (e.g., the Airbus' rudder unit). 
  - Metallic composites 
  In fusion filtration the preform is produced in a mold 
hardened with reinforcing fibers by absorbing, casting or 
pressing the molten liquid matrix material. 
  Diffusion welding is possible via hot pressing, film coating 
or explosive welding. In this setting the matrix material is 
almost exclusively in the form of film. In hot isostatic 
pressing and extrusion, the matrix material is preferably 
introduced as powder. Like prepregs, tapes are produced as 
pre-material. In directional solidification of alloys, fiber and 
matrix solidify simultaneously from the molten material and the 
result is a structure having higher temperature resistance with 
none of the problems that otherwise can surface in the 
production of fiber composite from the interaction between fiber 
and matrix. 
  - Ceramic composites 
  The powder method is preferably employed for short fiber and 
whisker reinforcement. It comprises the processes of modern 
ceramics technology. A drawback is the shear stress that results 
and possible damage to the fibers from the sharp-edged powder 
particles of the matrix material when compacting under pressure 
(hot press, internal gas pressure, hot isostatic pressing) or 
without pressure (sintering). In the So-gel process, prepregs 
are produced by impregnating fiber casing plies in sol or 
solutions/dispersions in a wet winding process and subsequent 
drying. 
  In liquid phase siliconizing for the production of C/SiC 
composites a C/C composite with appropriate C-matrix structure 
is transformed with molten liquid silicon under inert gas at 
1,500-2,000 degrees C. 
  Chemical gas phase precipitation (chemical vapour 
infiltration [CVI]) is used for the production of SiC/SiC and 
C/C composite materials that currently display the top qualities 
in crack-spread behavior, crack resistance, heat resistance and 
thermo-shock behavior. In this context, the composite results 
from chemical gas phase impregnation in a porous fiber casing at 
a maximum 1,100 degrees C. The drawback in this process is the 
continued protracted processing time (up to six weeks for 
large-size components). 
  Basically, when fiber-reinforced composite materials are 
produced, the thermal and chemical stress of the reinforcement 
components constitutes a major problem. For that reason those 
production processes are gaining in importance where processing 
temperatures are declining and chemical corrosion can be avoided. 
  An additional problem resides in the fact that, first, 
because of anisotropy in production of a component costly and 
sophisticated computations are needed until the most favorable 
production and optimum structure of the laminate is discovered. 
Second, in producing parts, the planned arrangement of the 
fibers has to be realized with utmost precision by the 
production since even the slightest deviations have serious 
effects on the platform effectiveness of a film. For that 
reason, what matters most here is the development of computer 
simulations and design methods for designing with anisotropic 
materials and automated designs for high-precision production. 
<H5>  Applied fields for high-performance composite materials </H5>
  The possible applications for high-performance composite 
materials stem from the functional and structural properties of 
those materials with the latter being the determining factors as 
chart 4.21 demonstrates: 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-114A>        Chart 4.21: Properties and applied fields for high-performance composite materials </FIG>


  Virtually only the PMC, among the high-performance composite 
materials, find application, primarily in electronics/electrical 
engineering, on the basis of functional properties. Applications 
based essentially on structurally properties apply to MMC and 
CMC in high-temperature resistant components for aerospace and 
in military engineering. So far, only PMC have been able to 
establish themselves in civilian applications primarily on the 
basis of their comparatively low price levels. 
<H5>  Market growth </H5>
  In 1990, the international market for high-performance 
composite materials as basic materials totaled nearly DM1.3 
billion. By the year 1995, that market volume will increase to 
nearly DM1.6 billion and by the year 2,000 to nearly DM2.0 
billion. 
  In 1990 the market volume for high-performance composite 
semi-finished products and components was five times the size as 
that for the corresponding basic materials. Specifically, in 
1990, it totaled nearly DM7.0 billion. By the year 1995, this 
market volume will have increased to nearly DM8.9 billion and by 
the year 2,000 to nearly DM10.8 billion (see chart 4.22). 
Allowance must be made in this context for the fact that nearly 
90 percent of the market volume reflects high-performance 
composites having polymer matrices. Only about 10 percent of the 
total market, in 1990 equal to a turnover, internationally, of 
nearly DM600.0 million, reflects the other sorts of 
high-performance composite materials. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-115A>        Chart 4.22: Projected international volume of high-performance composites as basic </FIG>

  Starting from a low basis, average annual growth rates for 
high-performance composite materials having metallic or ceramic 
matrices are projected at 12 percent and for carbon matrix 
composites, at seven percent up to the year 2,000. Growth is 
being shored up by increasing demand from the aerospace sector. 
Annual growth rates are restricted to three percent for 
high-performance composites having a polymer matrix as long as 
the recycling problem is not satisfactorily resolved. 
  The division of the international market by regions shows 
the 
dominance of the U.S. that has a 55 percent market share. With 
22.5 percent each, Japan and Europe have equal shares in the 
international market for high-performance composite materials. 
In Europe, in turn, France is the leader with a 7.7 percent 
international market share. Next come England with 4.1 percent 
and Germany with 3.8 percent. 
  The DM6.4 billion international market for high-performance 
composites having an organic matrix was distributed essentially 
among the following three market segments: 


    -  Aerospace - ca. 50 percent 
  -  Sports and leisure - ca. 23 percent 
  -  Industrial applications - ca. 15 percent 
  The remaining applications are distributed among a 
multiplicity of industrial sectors. 
<H5>  Development trends </H5>
  Uppermost for high-performance composite materials is 
increasing the permanent useful temperatures, improving the 
temperature resistance of the fiber matrix boundary surfaces 
(for ceramic composites) and improving the mechanical properties 
but also, above all, multi-functional composites, new structural 
designs and hybrid composites. 
  For multi-functional composites not only are components to 
increase strength and rigidity inserted but also sensors and 
actuators that make it possible to detect and possibly even 
influence the status of the material. 
  The goal of new structural designs is, above all, the 
production of multi-directional, resilient composite materials. 
The three dimensional fiber structures required for this can 
possibly be realized using modern weaving techniques (textile 
pre-processing). 
  Fiber composites having different sorts of fibers are 
encompassed by the hybrid composites. But composites also 
structured from several layers of various materials, for 
instance, sandwich configurations (e.g., 
aramide-aluminum-laminate [ARALL]) are acquiring more and more 
significance. The composition of film materials having 
functional gradients changes continuously from front to rear and 
this displays correspondingly different properties. 
  For synthesis and advanced processing, time and cost 
effective synthesizing designs even for large volume components 
of complex geometry are the object of development. The 
development goal for high-performance composites having a 
polymer matrix is, above all, advanced development and 
automation of the processing technologies in terms of quality 
assurance and mass production and the associated cost reduction. 
<H5>  4.3 Competence in materials technologies -- an important </H5>
factor in maintaining competitiveness 
  The assessment of German industry's competitive position 
conducted under a portfolio analysis leads to the conclusion 
that strong positions are currently being maintained in 
attractive branches. One exception to this, however, is 
electronics where German industry, on an international 
comparison, occupies only a weak position. 
  Our analysis demonstrates that materials technologies, 
high-performance materials and the components and systems 
resulting therefrom have a considerable impact on the 
competitiveness of the most important industrial branches and 
consequently are able to make a significant contribution towards 
safeguarding their future competitive positions. On the basis of 
numerous examples it can be demonstrated that there also exists 
a sizable R&amp;D potential in materials and the systems 
developed 
from it where the exploitable potentials transcend branches. The 
complexity, interdisciplinary and long-term aspects of many of 
these topics justify concerted action under government guidance 
and support. 
<H5>  4.3.1 Position of Germany's industrial sectors in the </H5>
international competitive arena 
  Maintaining and developing competitiveness is at the core of 
economic and industrial policy considerations and strategies. 
Competitiveness is a prerequisite for a multitude of 
micro-economic parameters, from a company's profitability to 
guaranteed jobs and even macro-economic factors and ultimately 
all the way up to the prosperity of entire nations. 
  The definition of competitiveness and its impact on the 
status of companies, branches and nations have been elucidated 
by numerous authors in many models. The common, albeit greatly 
simplified, denominator of such variegated viewpoints continues 
to be: competitiveness in industrial sectors is expressed as the 
capability to offer products having specific performance 
advantages, either a product characteristic or just the price. 
This approach to dealing with competitiveness naturally applies 
especially on the company level. On that level it is describable 
and quantifiable by means of comparative analyses of firms' 
market, cost, and technology positions. 
  On a higher level, for instance, the branch level, 
competitiveness is describable in a more highly aggregate 
manner, for example, through the capability of that branch to 
play a leading or particularly active role in international 
competition. On such a level, criteria such as export share, 
growth in export share or perhaps the branch's trade balances 
have to be adduced to describe or specify the competitiveness. 
  An especially high level of aggregation in the present 
discussion is the national level or even the level of the troika 
in which arguments are traded over the capability of a country 
or a troika to impact international competition. To be sure, on 
this level export and trade balance considerations play a role, 
but it is also necessary to introduce regulatory and ultimately 
capital market conditions into the deliberations. 
  Analyzing, from an international optic, what industrial 
sectors will hold particular significance now and in the future 
and assessing their branch attractiveness on the basis of 
criteria such as production volume, market growth, profitability 
and barriers to market access, the outcome is branches such as 
  -electronic products 
  -chemical products 
  -plastic and rubber wares and 
  -pharmaceutical products 
  that are especially attractive. These are followed by 
industrial sectors like machine building products, road vehicles 
or electrical engineering products (see chart 4.23). Less 
attractive, using these assessment criteria, are branches like 
mining or iron and steel. To be sure, from a supply perspective 
they are important, but in terms of their earnings potential 
they are relatively unattractive, at least for highly 
industrialized states. It is precisely such branches that 
characteristically have to be artificially kept "alive" by means 
of subsidies in virtually all leading industrial nations. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-117A>        Chart 4.23: Determining Germany's competitive position in internationally important </FIG>

  The FRG's international competitiveness in the entire sector 
of industrial goods, when assessed from an export optic, 
continues to remain high and Germany occupies a leading position 
alongside Japan and the U.S., that is, precisely the nations 
with the highest R&amp;D activities. In 1989 OECD countries 
exported 
processed industrial merchandise valued at DM2,862 billion. The 
FRG (17.4 percent) followed by the U.S. (14.7 percent) and Japan 
(14.2 percent) held the lion's share of those exports. Other 
industrial countries like France, Great Britain, and Italy with 
export shares of 8.4 and 7.2 percent had considerably less 
importance. 
  R&amp;D-intensive wares yielded a picture resembling that 
of the 
processed industrial products. The former include advanced 
technologies[.sup]21[/] and high-value 
technologies[.sup]22[/]. In 1989 OECD countries exported 
R&amp;D-intensive goods valued at nearly DM1,262 billion. At 20.7 
percent, Japan had the lion's share of them followed by the FRG 
(19 percent) and the U.S. (17.8 percent). Other industrial 
countries, e.g., Great Britain, France, and Italy had 
considerably less importance. Their international trade share 
fell between 7.4 and 5.2 percent. 
  Even the supplementally conducted semi-quantitative, 
branch-specific determination of Germany's competitive position 
from a market, technology, cost and human resources point of 
view, in sectors like the chemical industry, plastic and rubber 
goods, machine building products, road vehicles and 
pharmaceutical products, produced a relatively strong position. 
The same consideration indicated not only average positions in 
the sector of non-ferrous metals and semi-finished products or 
in aerospace vehicles but also the weak position in electronics, 
a branch with high attractiveness, more than DM1,500 billion in 
turnover and a considerable broad-spectrum function, that is, 
impacts on the effectiveness of other sectors. Hence, in 
addition to this relatively positive current balance, the 
strategic position of various industrial sectors has to be 
considered that will have considerable impact on future analyses 
of the competitive position. In important key and leading-edge 
technologies with significant leverage on individual industrial 
sectors the FRG sometimes comes up short in an international 
comparison. For example, in most sectors of electronics and 
information and communications technology Japan is the leader, 
while the U.S. and Germany at best are able to fall back on 
strengths in specific sectors of such important technological 
fields. In Germany, the technologies for the production of 
semiconductor and electronic components are poorly developed and 
the effects are already being felt in the machinery and 
telecommunications industry. Biotechnology, certainly one of the 
twenty-first century's most important technologies, has not even 
been able at all so far to secure a foothold in Europe and in 
Germany whereas it has been developed in the U.S. and Japan. As 
already explained, in the case of equally important materials 
technologies it has been possible in Germany to maintain the 
distance with the leaders, Japan and the U.S. 
  The impact of a host of developments in the indicated fields 
of technology in the meantime is leading to productivity 
disadvantages for Germany vis-a-vis international competitors. 
Japanese firms, for instance, are currently producing typical 
products in the electronics sector or even road vehicles almost 
30 percent more cheaply than European firms with the major part 
of this cost advantage resulting not from labor costs but from 
advantages from computer-based and consistently optimized 
design, configuration and processing methods, that is, through 
the consistent application of electronics. 
  The obvious strategic gaps existing in the FRG's technology 
portfolio could, over the medium to long term, lead to a 
worsening of its international competitiveness. For this reason, 
strategies should be developed and implemented on the national 
level that will result in a balanced technology portfolio. That 
presupposes safeguarding the competitive position of strong 
branches and development of at least a strategic position in 
electronics. 
<H5>  4.3.2 Impact of high-performance materials on selective </H5>
industrial sectors 
  It immediately follows from the facts and their correlation 
presented in chapter 4.3.1 that the FRG's future prosperity 
requires the maintenance and development of competitiveness in 
specific industrial sectors. Ultimately this means, first, 
offering products with better performances at competitive 
prices. Secondly, it also means adapting to gradually or 
abruptly changing general conditions in general or to their 
expressions in typical branches and to master as best as 
possible the respective specific competitive bases of any 
industrial segment. 
  To be sure, (global) competitors in the upcoming decades 
will 
have to deal with altered general conditions. In the highly 
industrialized countries there is an increasing requirement for 
a more intelligent approach to energy either directly by 
government or indirectly through increasing consumer pressure. 
Also in the industrial countries a steadily growing awareness of 
the environment is developing. Concurrently with that there is 
increasing need, for example, for mobility and communication. 
These developments imply an entire cluster of effects on the 
various branches. 
  The competitive basis of any industrial sector is 
specifically expressed for each one. Our research in the 
preparation of the present study has shown, however, that 
certain basic factors have equally great importance for all 
segments, albeit with different emphasis: 
  - price/performance ratio of the product 
  - product or system quality 
  - innovation rate and adaptability 
  - environmental friendliness 
  - satisfying specific consumer wants 
  - producer image, references. 
  To be able to realize strategic competitive advantages in 
intensive international competition vis-a-vis competitors, firms 
will have to orient themselves on such basic factors and derive 
from them their specific critical success factors whereby 
competitive advantages can be elaborated in terms of the basic 
factors. 
  The future-oriented fields of technology described at the 
outset of chapter four will have quite a considerable impact on 
the basic factors determining competitiveness and the specific 
critical success factors resulting therefrom. Based on our 
research and its results this also applies in a special manner 
to materials technologies. 
  As chart 4.24 illustrates succinctly and qualitatively, 
materials technologies in most industrial sectors have 
significant or considerable importance as a basis for 
competitiveness. This may come about directly, e.g., via the 
innovation rate or their adaptability or indirectly through 
positive influencing of production or operational costs, 
environmental friendliness or producer images. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-119A>        Chart 4.24: Illustration of the importance of high-performance materials technologies for </FIG>


  Chart 4.24 makes it clear that both the producer (and/or 
reprocessing industry) of basic materials, chemical industry 
(polymers, ceramics, composites) and iron and steel 
(high-performance materials) as well as the consumer industries 
like machine building, manufacture of road vehicles, etc., and 
sectors like energy engineering and especially aerospace are 
specific participants in materials technologies. In each case, 
what is uppermost is the direct use of high-performance 
materials as structural components, occasionally substituting 
conventional materials or indirect use in systems that could not 
be realized without the existence and use of high-performance 
materials with their specific property profiles. Through the use 
of selective examples this will be more closely described below. 
  - Road vehicle manufacturing example 
  There is no mistaking the applied potential of 
high-performance materials as structurally and functionally 
oriented high-performance materials in the manufacture of road 
vehicles and the potential for differentiation resulting 
therefrom that Japanese rivals are increasingly developing. 
  The following selective technological fields have direct or 
indirect impact on the future differentiation of competitors in 
the road vehicle manufacturing sector: 


    -  quality assurance systems 
  -  interrelated and follow-on processing technologies 
  -  CAD/CAM/CIM systems 
  -  alternative vehicle designs 
  -  alternative drive train designs 
  -  smart vehicle infrastructure systems. 
  High-performance materials are required at the most varied 
points for the realization of the systems and technologies just 
indicated. To this effect, in turn, they basically may be used 
directly in road vehicles. In this case structural materials are 
uppermost, for example 


    -  aluminum alloys 
  -  magnesium alloys 
  -  engine ceramics 
  -  composite materials 
  or find indirect application in road vehicles, namely, 
through the employment of new systems that cannot be realized 
without the application of high-performance materials. For this 
purpose, functional materials are pre-eminently called for. 
Examples of this are: 


    -  materials for electronic controls 
  -  materials for high-grade sensors 
  -  materials for optoelectronic systems. 
  For high-performance materials to be directly utilized in 
the 
manufacture of road vehicles, high-performance materials will 
have to force traditional materials out of their long-standing 
fields of application. History indicates that this will occur 
only at a snail's pace. Often a traditional material is not 
replaced by a high-performance material because the features of 
traditional materials are significantly improved under pressure 
from competing materials. For cost, quality and recycling 
reasons or for lack of experience with new materials, 
high-performance materials are therefore not used or used only 
hesitantly. 
  On the basis of the very many expert interviews that were 
held, however, it may be anticipated that in the future, the 
following high-performance materials will intensively be used 
directly in the manufacture of road vehicles: 


    -  high-performance steels 
  -  light metals 
  -  high-strength aluminum alloys 
  -  magnesium alloys 
  -  non-reinforced high-performance structural polymers 
  -  high-performance ceramics 
  -  materials having improved sound absorbing, optical, 
insulating 
and vibration-damping features. 
  In the unanimous opinion of the experts, high-performance 
composite materials, particularly GFK, CFK, AFK and hybrid 
configurations, initially will experience no significant 
expansion since steel products for applications in the 
manufacture of road vehicles are superior to them in many sorts 
of respects. But if the general legislative conditions (e.g., 
upper limits on fuel consumption) are altered then a drastic 
change could occur also for such materials. 
  On the other hand, when high-performance materials are 
indirectly employed, i.e., via new systems in the manufacture of 
road vehicles, those systems are mostly realizable only through 
the utilization of high-performance materials. From the outset, 
cost and recycling motives are of secondary importance here. 
Therefore there are very good possibilities here for the use of 
all functional materials made out of polymers and ceramics as 
well as semiconductors. From a road vehicle manufacturing optic 
the following technologies are of special interest in the 
processing technologies sector: 


    -  further development of near-net-shape technologies 
  -  powder metallurgy 
  -  foundry technology 
  -  etc. 


    -  optimizing production and processing technologies with 
the goal of cost reduction, enhanced quality and waste reduction 
for basic materials, semi-finished products and components 
  -  technologies for surface treatment of materials 
  -  CAD/CAM 
  -  bonding techniques 
  -  development of materials recycling processes 
  - Machine building sector 
  The technical development of machine building is currently 
concentrated basically on integrating new technologies, 
especially in he (micro-) electronic and information technology 
sector into machine building products with the following broad 
themes being of particular interest: 


    -  electronic controls 
  -  sensor technology 
  -  advanced precision bearings 
  -  laser technologies 
  -  artificial intelligence 
  -  optoelectronics 
  -  robot technology 
  -  software developments. 
  Depending on whether structurally or rather functionally 
oriented applications are foremost in this qualitative survey, 
the result is starting points for product improvements using 
high-performance materials, especially from the following 
sectors: ceramics (coatings, bearings, ceramic cutting 
materials), composite materials (CFK components in highly 
stressed structures) and systems having a high amount of 
optical, electronic or magnetic materials (measurement and 
control engineering, sensors engineering). Through such product 
developments opportunities emerge for further differentiations 
and diversifications too for machine building in processing 
technologies: 


    -  further development of near-net-shape technologies 


    -  powder metallurgy 
  -  foundry technology 
  -  etc. 


    -  optimizing production and processing technologies with 
the goal of cost reduction and enhanced quality 
  -  CAD/CAM 
  -  coating technology 
  -  surface treatment of materials. 
  - Electrical engineering industry example 
  To be able to describe the importance of high-performance 
materials for the electrical engineering industry, it is 
necessary to distinguish two segments of electrical engineering 
products, since they levy different requirements on the 
materials that are used: 


    -  energy engineering 
  -  general electrical engineering. 


    -  Energy engineering 
  Unlike any other systems technology, energy technologies are 
very tightly linked to the political environment. This expresses 
itself, for example, in the form of the market prospects for 
traditional and new energy technologies being determined very 
greatly by the shaping of environmental legislation and the 
development of primary energy prices, that is, by factors over 
which the firms themselves have only slight influence. 
  Firms active in energy engineering therefore are primarily 
concentrated on (allowing for the above indicated marginal 
conditions): 


    -  increasing the efficiency of traditional energy systems 
  -  pushing the development and implementation of new energy 
systems 
  Increasing the efficiency of traditional energy systems is 
principally concentrated on converting the primary energy system 
that is used with as little loss as possible into useful energy 
in order thereby to realize an increase in the efficiency of the 
system as a whole. At present in industry the efficiency level 
is at approximately 10 percent (primary energy to useful 
energy). In this context, however, the following subsystems have 
to be distinguished, namely, energy acquisition, storage, 
conversion, and energy use. 
  The goal of developing and implementing new energy systems 
is 
to create energy systems that can be used economically as 
"inexhaustible" sources of energy. 
  The realization of such developments therefore basically 
depends on the availability of appropriate high-performance 
materials and processing technologies. Currently available 
high-performance materials are able only partially to satisfy 
the requirements for energy technologies that undergo advanced 
development or that are new. Advances in the sector of materials 
and processing technologies therefore are closely coupled with 
the realization of new energy systems and therefore with energy 
savings and efficient energy use. 
  In this respect, the following technological sectors in the 
energy engineering sector will have special importance in the 
future: 
  -photovoltaics 
  -solar cells 
  -high-performance heat pumps 
  -superconductivity 
  -(electro-) chemical energy storage devices (hydrogen 
storage 
device, battery systems) 
  -electrical and electromagnetic storage devices 
  -fusion technologies. 
  There is no question but that special importance will be 
attributed to high-performance materials in the above indicated 
technological sectors. Simply for more efficient use of solar 
energy it makes sense to further develop the production, 
advanced processing and systems integration of amorphous and 
polycrystalline silicon and (further) develop alternative 
photovoltaic systems (CuInSe[.sup]2[/], CdTe). 
  Among others, the following specific materials starting 
points emerge for realization of the fusion design: 


    -  advanced, high-temperature and radiation resistant 
steels 
  -  nickel-based superalloys 
  -  carbon-fiber reinforced plastics [CFK] for magnetic 
suspension 
  -  refractory metals (niobium, tantalum, molybdenum, etc.) 
  -  SiC, TiC coatings on metals and graphite 
  -  _g_-Li AlO[.sup]2[/] and Li[.sup]2[/]SiO[.sup]3[/] 
  -  high-performance ceramics (oxides and nitrides) 
  -  magnetic materials 
  -  superconducting materials. 
  - General electrical engineering 
  Even in the sector of traditional energy production in the 
context of increasing the efficiency level of stationary 
turbines there emerge a host of materials-based starting points 
for differentiating competitors. There are, for instance, 
concrete areas of application in traditional power plants and 
especially combination power plants where an increase in the gas 
input temperature of the gas turbines can yield significant 
increases in the thermodynamic efficiency level. 
  In the general electrical engineering field efforts are 
concentrated on making electrical engineering systems more 
effective, smaller and more reliable and enabling them to 
continue to be produced at as low a cost as possible. To realize 
this will, in the future, increasingly require high-performance 
materials and the processing technologies for them. 
  Semiconductor materials, high-performance functional metals, 
high-performance functional polymers, high-performance ceramics, 
superconductive materials and selective structural materials are 
especially important for general electrical engineering. The 
development and use of semiconductor materials resembles that 
for micro-electronics. 
  Magnetic materials and conductive materials are uppermost 
among the high-performance functional metals. Increasingly, 
among magnetic materials, the following materials will be of 
special interest: 


    -  metallic glass 
  -  permanent magnets 
  -  hard magnetic materials 
  -  magnetic powder 
  -  magnetic rotors 
  -  superconducting magnets 
  In the field of high-performance functional polymers the 
material's electrical conductivity or non-conductivity will be 
especially prized. For the most part, at present, duroplastic 
materials are being applied here. Because of the continuing 
increase in effectiveness, increased requirements for 
temperature resistance will be imposed on polymers in electrical 
engineering applications, and in the future that could lead to 
increased use of high-performance duroplasts. 
  In the development and use of high-performance functional 
ceramics in the general electrical engineering sector the 
principal attraction is electrical insulation, super conducting 
properties and piezo-electric properties. Of special importance 
here, for instance, are: 


    -  various high-performance ceramic substances 
  -  ceramic insulation coatings 
  -  superconducting ceramics 
  -  ceramic piezo-electric materials 
  From a general electrical engineering optic the following 
materials developments also appear meaningful: 


    -  improvement of the magnetic properties of magnetic 
materials and their integration into the system as a whole 
  -  development of high-temperature resistance, ceramic 
insulation 
coatings 
  -  development of new ceramic superconductors 
  -  development and optimization of composites that can 
simultaneously assume different functions, e.g., electrical 
insulation and heat conductivity. 
  - Electronic products example 
  The increasing automation and computerization of all sectors 
of our lives will lead to electronic products having a 
significant impact by the millennium on all internationally 
important branches. This development becomes clearer once all 
important key and leading-edge technologies of the specific 
branches are analyzed. The lion's share of the key and 
leading-edge technologies there is in fact directly tied in with 
electronic products. 
  It is anticipated that jobs in traditional branches will be 
lost to the further impact of electronic products. They probably 
will only partially be able to be offset by new jobs emerging in 
the electronics industry or the supply industry for it. The 
availability of specific high-performance electronic materials 
is a prerequisite for being able in the future to produce 
currently existing electronic products more efficiently and cost 
effectively. Two developments requiring high-performance 
materials will be considered and described more closely below. 
They are: 


    -  micro-electronics 
  -  optoelectronics. 
  - Micro-electronics 
  Current endeavors in micro-electronics are targeted on the 
ability to craft more effective, smaller and reliable complex 
electronic systems and simultaneously produce them at lower 
cost. High-performance materials, especially functional 
materials and the processing technologies for them, play a 
decisive role in this context. 
  According to chart 4.25 semiconductor materials, 
high-performance ceramics and glass and high-performance 
polymers are of interest for micro-electronic components and 
systems. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-123A>        Chart 4.25: Selective high-performance materials for use in electronic </FIG>


  Silicon (crystalline silicon, amorphous silicon, 
etc.)currently reigns supreme among semiconductor materials. In 
the opinion of the experts this will continue even into the 
future since considerable possibilities for advanced development 
still are associated with silicon technology. Other 
semiconductor materials like gallium arsenide, the most 
important of the II-V semiconductors is interesting only in 
micro-electronic systems niches where its speed (three to 10 
times greater than silicon) is fully effective. II-VI 
semiconductors, on the other hand, are mostly in the research 
stage. 
  High-performance ceramics and glass hold exceptional 
significance for micro-electronic components and systems. They 
are presently used mostly as insulators. Ceramic, 
superconducting materials are a promising field. Their use could 
resolve the issues both of a lossless power supply and heat 
buildup in electronic systems. 
  At present, polymers are mostly used for metal protection of 
chips. At the moment, this field of application is dominated by 
traditional polymers. Because of the trend to greater 
miniaturization and its associated greater heat buildup, 
enhanced temperature-resistant polymers, that is, 
high-performance polymers will be used in the future. There is 
also an endeavor to radically redesign chip structure through 
the combination of conductive and non-conductive polymer films 
and this will result in further opportunities for 
high-performance polymers. 
  - Optoelectronics 
  The markets for communications systems will continue to 
expand in upcoming years because of increasing demand for 
information. This is resulting in a growing interest in 
high-performance light transmission and optoelectronic systems 
that display a number of advantages compared with conventional 
copper wires: 
  -high bit transfer rates 
  -protection against interference 
  -weight savings 
  -protection against eavesdropping 
  -low attenuation of the transmitted signal. 
  To transmit light signals, the electric signals have to be 
converted into appropriate light signals by using, for instance, 
a laser. Those are then transmitted via a glass or polymer fiber 
to a decoder that reconverts the light signals into electric 
signals. Optical computers are a future goal of optoelectronics. 
  A plethora of high-performance materials are required for 
the 
realization of optoelectronic systems. Selective 
high-performance materials that hold special importance for 
optoelectronics are listed in chart 4.26. 
  According to chart 4.26, semiconductor materials, 
high-performance ceramics and glass and high-performance 
polymers are of interest for optoelectronic components and 
systems. Those are the same groups of materials as for 
micro-electronics, although optoelectronic systems levy other 
requirements on materials and this leads to the prioritizing of 
other materials. 
  Among semiconductor materials, gallium arsenide is far 
superior to silicon because of its good light emitting and 
absorbing properties. Gallium arsenide holds the greatest 
significance for optoelectronic systems. Other semiconductor 
materials are of only secondary importance. 
  In optoelectronic systems high-performance polymers are 
frequently used as a medium for light transmission. Because of 
the currently still very sizable light attenuation of polymer 
light conducting fibers, they are used only for Local Area 
Networks. Glass is preferred for longer routings because of its 
low light-attenuation property. 
  High-performance ceramics are used for the realization of 
optoelectronic ICs. In this way, high-performance materials are 
used directly in optoelectronic systems and these are then used 
in a large number of applied fields because of the expected 
sizable broad impact of optoelectronic systems. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-124A>        Chart 4.26: Selective high-performance materials for use in optoelectronic </FIG>


  The described possibilities for differentiation having 
materials relevance in the industrial segments that were also 
described, naturally have major implications for the business of 
the producer of basic materials for high-performance materials, 
that is, on the chemical and metal producing industries. Both 
industrial sectors therefore must see to it that the appropriate 
basic materials are available in sufficient quantities to meet 
user and supplier requirements in terms of quality and price. 
Since precisely those industries have to make a sizable R&amp;D 
outlay for the development of new production processes although 
they are situated right at the start of the net product chain 
and only enjoy low margins there, not only does the question 
arise at this point regarding official R&amp;D support as is the 
case to a considerable extent in the materials research program 
precisely for those industries, but also regarding strategic 
alliances and partnerships (in the development sector) that are 
likely to result in cost reduction and lowered risk with 
concomitantly more rapid market dissemination. The catalyst 
factor for establishing such alliances and even their 
coordination would be one of the most important tasks in any 
future support for materials technologies. 
Footnotes: 
  21. Based on the FhG-ISI definition, advanced technologies 
typically have at least 8.5 percent of turnover invested in 
R&amp;D 
  22. Based on the FhG-ISI definition, high-value technologies 
typically have between 3.5 and 8.5 percent of turnover invested 
in R&amp;D 
<H5>  5. Guidelines for Future Support of Materials Research in </H5>
Germany 
  Because of their strategic significance, their 
broad-spectrum 
nature and their potential, high performance materials and the 
associated manufacturing and processing technologies are among 
the most important key technologies supported by government. 
Even for nearly all the FRG's industrial manufacturing sectors, 
they are important factors in maintaining and developing future 
competitiveness, whether as the basis for establishing new 
technical designs or for improving existing technologies and 
systems. 
  Countering the great potential of high performance 
materials, 
their great significance for the competitiveness of individual 
companies, as well as the entire economy, are the frequently 
long times for dissemination into the respective markets, 
uncertainties surrounding the realization of radical new 
technical designs and the associated corporate risks. For this 
reason, as well as consideration of intensive government support 
activities in all important industrial countries, it both makes 
sense and is necessary to have a further government support 
initiative in pre-competitive sectors. 
  As an industrial policy activity, future support of 
materials 
research in Germany should include the following fundamental 
strategic goals: 


    -  safeguarding Germany's technological competence as a 
critical factor for success in international competitiveness 
  -  acquiring leading technology positions in selective fields of 
application for high performance materials that are 
strategically important for German industry 
  -  accelerating the dissemination of high performance materials 
and the components and systems produced from them into the 
appropriate market segments as well as assisting German industry 
to maintain and develop its international competitiveness 
  -  taking long term ecological factors into consideration 
chapter 
(5.1). 
  Any future support initiative should tie in with the results 
that have been realized so far under the materials support 
program and with a view towards a more intensive strategic 
orientation with precisely defined strategic goals, as well as 
reorientation of the topical foci and organization of program 
development and implementation, it should also encompass: 
  (1) focusing the program on application foci matching the 
chosen technology strategy (chapter 5.2) 
  (2) reorienting topical foci on materials as integral 
components of systems solutions and taking net product stages 
into consideration (chapter 5.3) 
  (3) prioritizing proven support instruments, especially 
direct support of specific combined projects in contrast to 
non-specific or indirect support activities that have turned out 
to be less efficient (chapter 5.2) 
  (4) substantive systematic and/or institutionalized 
alignment 
with other support activities (chapter 5.4) 
  (5) Adapting program organization to new requirements by 
establishing program management and program administration under 
the purview of the BMFT (chapter 5.3) 
  (6) establishing modern methods of R&amp;D control and 
project 
management for program management and administration (chapter 
5.3). 
<H5>  5.1 Strategic preliminary remarks </H5>
  The industrial nations of western Europe are currently 
facing 
crucial challenges in the sector of foreign, economic, 
structural and technological policy. This primarily entails 
completion of Europe's process of integration, the development 
and stabilization of efficient economic systems in the countries 
of central and eastern Europe and maintaining the 
competitiveness of western Europe's industry. 
  For the FRG in particular this entails: 


    -  completing the unification of Germany, allowing for the 
difficult process of restructuring in the new states of the FRG 
and 
  -  safeguarding the competitiveness of Germany's key branches on 
the international market. 
  R&amp;D and the technological progress resulting therefrom 
are 
indisputably major factors in safeguarding and developing the 
competitiveness of industrial outfits whose industries are 
internationally active in technologically promising markets. 
Continual R&amp;D is indispensable to ensure that the economy's 
net 
product is adequate even over the long term to be able to cover 
rising costs for growing social, economic and ecological 
demands. This surely entails both the efficiency of basic 
research and effective and efficient research on the verge of 
application. But quite certainly the ability to transfer 
know-how and results of R&amp;D as rapidly as possible into 
production processes and into market accessible products plays a 
major role. 
  As indicated in the previous chapter, the FRG occupies a 
leadership position in the R&amp;D sector alongside Japan and the 
U.S. Simultaneously, those nations have the top export 
statistics and enjoy absolute top positions among the world's 
leading industrial nations. In addition to this current balance, 
the strategic position of those countries, as well as the troika 
in general, has foreseeable effects on the future positioning of 
the indicated countries. Japan has bee able to realize a high 
level of industrial efficiency precisely in high technologies 
and, as a result, the ability virtually to optimize innovations 
having market and competitive impact. Japan, therefore, is 
currently, for example, the leader inmost sectors of electronics 
and information and communications technologies, while the U.S. 
and Europe plus Germany at best are able to fall back on 
strengths in specific sectors of such important technological 
fields. In Germany, the technologies for the production of 
semiconductor and electronic components are poorly developed and 
the effects are already being felt in the machinery and 
telecommunications industry. Even biotechnology, another of the 
twenty-first century's key technologies, has not been able so 
far to secure a foothold in Germany. 
  In the case of equally important materials technologies it 
has been possible in Germany at least to maintain its position 
relative to the leaders, Japan and the U.S. and in some sectors 
it remains abreast or has carved out strong niche positions. The 
FRG, therefore, is a major contender in the competition among 
the industrial states to develop and commercially exploit 
materials technology. The current materials research program 
could lay the basis for generally ensuring it a role to play in 
the top league of the materials nations. Unless the 
pre-requirements are comprehensively utilized and assisted over 
the long term with appropriate support activities there will be 
no success in successfully utilizing the potential that was once 
developed and definite backsliding will be preprogrammed. 
  The further development and support of materials technology 
are so important precisely because very sizable impetuses and 
spill-over effects on virtually all sectors of the processing 
industry result from them. Of all the key technologies at the 
close of the twentieth century, materials engineering is the one 
with the greatest degree of interlinkage with other engineering 
fields and with the highest degree of positive external effects. 
However, this means that independent development of materials is 
not profitable enough but can only be considered economically 
promising when viewed in association with subsequent systems 
activities and advanced processing methods. 
  This addresses the requirement for sustained assistance for 
the development of the supply of new materials and their 
utilization, especially considering g the extensive support 
activities in Japan and the U.S. Technology development and 
support therefore has to attain a critical mass, but 
simultaneously it has to be focused through an especially smart 
process on attractive systems markets and applied sectors in 
which national competitive advantages can be buttressed. 
  It is precisely the successful development of systems 
markets 
on the national level that facilitates high net product, 
generation of above-average yields and the re-accumulation of 
finances and impetuses in the national R&amp;D system. Japanese 
and 
U.S. materials developments are successful precisely where they 
are included in successful national growth and export sectors. 
Any support strategy therefore has to consistently apply the 
necessary R&amp;D measures in key technologies, but it must also 
quite decisively indicate the sectors in which the greatest 
prospects for success in the future commercial use of such key 
technologies are located, taking into account the problem of EC 
assistance. 
  Since sticking with basic technologies with their low 
potentials for differentiation and development does not 
constitute any long-term viable alternative, what will, instead, 
be crucial for the future will be the extent to which the FRG is 
able to assert itself in key and leading-edge technologies in 
strategically important fields of technology like 


    -  electronics 
  -  information and communications technologies 
  -  biotechnology 
  -  energy engineering 
  -  materials technologies 
  since these, at least for the most part, will be the basic 
technologies of the upcoming decade and will therefore impact 
the prosperity of entire branches. Ultimately it entails 
preparing and introducing the renunciation of old technologies 
and the development of a consensus on the prioritizing of high 
technologies. 
  In this context, the total net product chain of the 
respective advanced technologies, that is, from producer of 
basic materials through components manufacturer, process 
engineering and final user industries, should be involved in the 
formation of the consensus. Even though it remains a moot 
question whether successful industrial outfits have to research, 
develop, master and economically exploit every possible 
technology on their own or whether, in the context of an 
international division of labor it is not sufficient for 
individual technologies that they are able to use them, there is 
prevailing agreement that highly developed industrial countries 
need a balanced technological portfolio to safeguard their 
competitiveness. 
  It is crucial for the success of any national support 
strategy to determine the technological fields and applied 
sectors of materials engineering in which national strengths can 
be maintained or developed and where backsliding should be 
avoided and, if appropriate, it is hopeless any longer to chase 
after the train as it pulls away. 
  The coordination of nationally promising technological 
fields, applications and systems markets can only be introduced 
through a dialog involving the appropriate decision makers from 
the private sector, research and politics. The strategic goal of 
building a consensus among the major players is to elaborate and 
implement an appropriate technological strategy in all key and 
leading-edge technologies identified as critical in order to 
safeguard the impact of R&amp;D, to bring back into play the high 
development and investment costs that occasionally reach into 
the billions, in order to benefit from the learning curve 
effects of new technologies and to ensure early spin-offs. 
  The necessary strategic and consensus-oriented support 
policy 
in the materials technology sector and their application has to 
run the entire gamut of modern support instruments as has 
already successfully been practiced for years on a basis of each 
for its own. This means that regulatory interventions, financial 
stimuli, the development of an innovation-oriented 
infrastructure and the support of public demand for innovative 
products have to be employed to a balanced extent and proportion 
relative to one another. Their systematic application and their 
mutual coordination, as well as the assessment of their direct 
and indirect effects, however, seem still, in the future, to 
need further optimizing. Even the medium to long term effects on 
which companies and technological policy activities are focused, 
are presently at best qualitatively describable. 
  Ultimately, the complex technological policy toolkit and 
fundamental, strategic planning and action targeted on 
safeguarding the long-term competitiveness of Germany's industry 
is not possible without the knowledge and the inclusion of the 
respective parties and partners both in the official and in the 
industrial sectors. This means that the government's 
technological policy planning and the strategic planning of 
companies as management instruments have to be in a 
complementary relation to one another and this is thoroughly 
consistent with the principle that gives order to the market 
economy. 
  Therefore, technology policy resulting from such a 
complementary collaboration among all participants in an 
institutionalized dialog will incorporate the following 
principles: 


    -  the principle of the consistency of R&amp;D policy with 
other broad constitutional and political principles 
  -  the principle of limiting government interventions to 
exceptional cases each of which is subject to considerable 
startup pressure 
  -  the subsidiary principle, that is, solving problems on the 
lowest possible decision-making level and the one that is close 
to the taking of action 
  -  the principle of openness to innovations and maintenance of 
competitive structures in research and in the private sector 
  -  the principle of flexibility, of learning and tolerance for 
mistakes 
  -  the principle of the best possible coordination of the 
appropriate activities in a European and international context. 
<H5>  5.2 Most crucial guidelines and principles for designing </H5>
future materials research support 
  In the context of developing guidelines and principles for 
any future design for materials research, various possible 
procedures and alternative designs are roughly assessed and 
compared with one another. The alternatives range from stopping 
support all the way up to continuation of it with different 
support and procedural designs. 
  On the basis of the conclusion of our activities and talks 
with the experts, the hands-off alternative, namely, stopping 
support for materials research appears to be a purely 
theoretical variant that entails a great loss in effectiveness 
and risks. Besides the arguments described in chapter 5.1, 
putting a stop to support, precisely in today's difficult 
economic environment, would have definitely negative 
consequences for materials research. It would foreseeably entail: 
  - the shelving of firms' major R&amp;D projects involving 
medium 
to long term orientation 
  - the reduction of risky R&amp;D projects in industry 
although 
these are a prerequisite for the market introduction of 
promising products in eight to 10 years 
  - jeopardizing the just recently established cooperative 
structures involving industry, SMEs and academic research that 
were developed in the context of current combined research and 
  - ultimately, jeopardizing the current results of the MATFO 
program and as a result, ineffective use of support resources 
afterwards. 
  For this reason, in our opinion, it will be indispensable, 
even in the future, to solve the problems that need to be 
addressed, in close cooperation among the private economy, 
research institutions and support institutions. Based on 
experience, this cooperation will only come about if the 
participants simultaneously contribute financial and personnel 
resources. 
  Hence, various support designs and instruments are 
conceivable for future support of materials research: 
  1. improvement of the general conditions 
  2. infrastructural support 
  3. institutional support 
  4. indirect or indirectly specific support 
  5. direct project support. 
  Prioritizing one or more of those options and the respective 
mix of appropriate instruments primarily depends on which 
objectives and problems are foremost. Each of the various 
support policy instruments manifests a different effect relative 
to optimum support of the objectives formulated in chapter 5.1 
in the materials research sector and in terms of respectively 
efficient use of support resources (see chart 5.1). In order to 
be able to realize an appropriate weighting, the various forms 
of support are dealt with after being differentiated on the 
basis of their specific starting points. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-128A>        Chart 5.1: Effectiveness of different support instruments in the materials research </FIG>


  1. Activities to "improve general conditions" have rather 
high leverage, but are difficult to incorporate into a support 
design. Thus, there is no disputing the importance of legal 
regulations like emission regulations, use and production 
prohibitions, recycling regulations or even occupational safety 
and health measures have a great impact, both positive and 
negative, on the development and establishment of modern 
materials technologies. Even a shortening of the time period for 
the authorization process, the introduction of a standardization 
of, for instance, testing techniques, introduction of German 
industrial standards [DIN] and the harmonization of laws and 
regulations having materials relevance on the national and 
international level, particularly in a European context. Early 
inclusion of international experts from research and industry in 
the debate over new laws and ordinances and the extension of 
patent lifetimes in an international context are also starting 
points for the improvement of general conditions. 
  2. Infrastructural support through information and 
documentation facilities, patent information and assessment 
centers and technology transfer centers was already a component 
of the current MATFO program. Its primary goal was the exchange 
of information and know-how and the erection of demonstration 
centers. Its importance is deemed rather low by the materials 
experts we queried (see chapter 2, chart 2.4), not least because 
the main target group of those facilities, heavily 
technology-oriented SMEs, have not played a central role, at 
least in the past, in the materials research sector. Since the 
respective centers also are already in existence, in our 
opinion, there is only a slight need for support that should 
have as its goal, above all, familiarization and, consequently, 
greater use of those facilities. 
  3. Institutional support whose goal is the support and 
development of institutes set up specifically for materials 
research activities, e.g., large research institutions, is 
assigned little importance by materials experts in terms of a 
single objective that entails, above all, the effective transfer 
of the results of application-oriented research to production 
processes and ultimately to marketable products. This applies 
not least to the primarily scientific and theoretical focus of 
such institutions. In the case of the large research centers 
there is also the often limited structural flexibility inside 
such institutions due to their size and this makes it difficult 
to focus on the applied orientation of materials development and 
systems innovation. 
  4. Indirect support through tax breaks, special write-offs, 
investment incentives (subsidizing personnel and investment 
costs, etc., for certain R&amp;D fields) are, in our view, and in 
the opinion of the materials experts we polled, of only limited 
suitability for the current form of materials research support. 
These support instruments result in a very wide scattering of 
support resources and simultaneously reduced selectivity of the 
application of the resources. As a result of the broad leeway it 
allows in crafting innovative projects, goal establishment and 
monitoring of results, above all, becomes extraordinarily 
complicated. For this reason, this support instrument makes 
sense only in connection with very carefully selected support 
criteria entailing a high probability of direct dissemination of 
materials development into the production of marketable products. 
  5. In direct project support, on the other hand, precisely 
defined support goals and support criteria are possible. It 
facilitates targeted focusing of the applied resources that 
should be the principal characteristic of any future support 
design, considering the objectives in the materials research 
sector described in the introduction. Only with this support 
instrument can defined and quantifiable goals be established and 
monitored. This is an advantage that should be exploited without 
reservation for the efficient use of limited support resources. 
Consistent further development through supportive project 
management and R&amp;D control can continue definitely to 
increase 
the effectiveness of this support instrument. 
  6. Moreover, for about a decade now, indirectly specific 
support has been used in a number of technological fields 
(applied micro-electronics, production engineering, etc.). This 
is especially focused on the dissemination phase, is heavily 
medium-term oriented and typically involves low expenditure on 
testing and administration. Hence, this instrument has a 
targeted effect in terms of selecting a rather specific 
technology. Up until now the indirectly specific support 
instrument has still not been employed in Germany in the 
materials technology sector. 
  Against the backdrop of the results of this study, according 
to which the strengths of the currently determined research 
results are situated, above all, at the inception of the net 
worth chain in the basic research sector having an applied 
orientation, but where the effective transfer to specific 
applied fields is still pending, in our opinion, the most 
efficient support instrument by far is direct project support in 
a context elaborated and coordinated with all participants. It 
should be accompanied by measures to improve the general 
conditions and, with lesser emphasis, technology transfer and 
information exchange. In addition to this, consideration can be 
given to supplemental indirectly specific support for individual 
project components, especially where dissemination and the 
inclusion of SMEs are foremost. Still, the direct project 
support toolkit should still remain uppermost. 
  Above all, support of combined research with its associated 
R&amp;D cooperative activities has generally proven its worth and 
should, in any event, be continued. Incidentally, this is a 
development that can be observed internationally. 
  Assessment of the current materials research program has 
demonstrated, however, that any future support concept should 
entail some major reorientation activities: 


    -  greater strategic orientation with precisely defined 
strategic goals and systematic or institutionalized substantive 
coordination with other support activities in the materials 
sector 
  -  unambiguous focusing on projects and activities that 
correspond 
to the selected technological strategy and close the presently 
existing strategic gaps 
  -  directing the program towards applied foci in which basic 
research topics having an applied orientation are elaborated 
  -  establishing a mix of instruments whereby the different 
program 
foci can be supported in an optimum manner providing for 
targeting on international R&amp;D cooperative activities as well 
  -  management of the program using substantive and efficient 
program and project management 
  -  medium to long term integration of all support activities 
having materials relevance in a materials framework program 
involving uniform management and implementation. 
  To match the systems nature and the importance of applied 
orientation of materials research, any future supported should 
be designed as an "integrated program for materials and systems 
innovation". 
  In view of the high cost of development and the lengthy 
dissemination times in the current program and to ensure proven 
continuity over time, it makes sense to have another ten-year 
interval as the duration of the program. Henceforth, however, 
support should be crafted as two five-year phases with 
appropriate program assessment. A differentiated program 
structuring, as proposed in chart 5.2, should significantly 
contribute towards implementation of the recommended greater 
strategic focus of the program. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-131A>        Chart 5.2: Proposed timeline and milestones chart for any -future materials and systems </FIG>


  Before launching the first phase, the fundamental focus of 
the program should be agreed upon and established with 
strategic, technological and technology policy objectives. 
Concurrently, measurement and assessment criteria should be 
agreed upon for analysis and assessment of the first part of the 
program to be undertaken in the context of an interim 
assessment. The results of the interim assessment are then 
simultaneously the basis for possibly necessary course 
corrections or changes in the (strategic) objectives. 
  Just as in the current materials research program, regular 
symposiums could be held as supporting measures for such a 
concept. On such occasions, however, not only should information 
on projects be exchanged, but also the strategic aspects of 
international materials research and support for it and the 
resulting implications of the same as well as discussion of the 
program status and needed course corrections should be discussed 
during such symposiums. Another supporting measure besides 
support providing incentives for the participants to collaborate 
with the program is the elaboration of strategic data in the 
research and industrial implementation sector. A materials 
monitoring system [WMS] should be set up for this purpose, 
combining data on: 


    -  technology trends in the materials technology sector 
  -  market trends in major applied branches 
  -  data on competitor behavior 
  -  a comparison of support policy strategies in individual 
countries. 
  What matters most under the umbrella of WMS is that the 
resulting "Technology and Marketing Intelligence" turns out to 
be as undistorted, direct, product related and inclusive of the 
relevant knowledge platforms as possible. It should not be 
confused with the establishment of a data base system that turns 
out to be multi-phased, protracted and mostly neutralized. A 
model of the way a modern materials monitoring system should 
function is the data processing process introduced in Japan's 
support institutions and projects[.sup]23[/]. 
  Overall management of the materials monitoring system should 
reside with the above-mentioned program management. This 
acquires the necessary data through strategic study groups and 
the issuance of reports. Important data gathering activities 
should also include regular trips made by groups of researchers 
and industrialists to Japan, the U.S. and other countries of 
importance in materials research. But it is crucial from the 
outset that the necessary "Technology and Marketing 
Intelligence" is a substantial component of the top 
decision-making level of program management. It has to become a 
major agenda item for the "materials strategy" study group just 
as are the workshops on foci and areas of activity (see the 
following descriptions in chart 5.6). 
<H5>  5.3 Thematic foci for future materials research support </H5>
  The implementation of a future support program carrying out 
the tasks described in the previous chapter (5.2), requires a 
reorientation of subject and development goals. In this context, 
a new subject should range from a material's maximum properties 
all the way to materials as optimum systems components. This 
type of subject facilitates an equalization of materials 
development, design, configuration and other possible variables 
of a component and as a result also its ability to be integrated 
into a system. For this reason, any future program for materials 
and systems innovation should concentrate on foci in which the 
systems function depends to a great extent on materials' 
properties and that simultaneously assumes a key role in the 
FRG's competitive position. These include, for example: 


    -  energy engineering 
  -  transportation design 
  -  information and communication technology 
  -  micro-electronic systems 
  -  optoelectronic systems 
  -  medical engineering. 
  Undoubtedly one of the major challenges of the future under 
energy engineering will be, above all, the rational use of 
energy and the utilization of fossil energy sources employing 
new energy systems. Tackling this task is inconceivable without 
highly developed materials and their ongoing further 
development. In this context there will be different demands for 
different categories of materials for each of the various energy 
systems (e.g., advanced fossil power plant technologies, fuel 
cells, solar energy). The specific demand will result from the 
conditions under which the energy systems have to function. 
  For mobility, one of the hallmarks of modern societies, 
rapid 
and reliable means of transportation are essential. These 
increasingly have to address requirements for increased safety, 
fewer harmful emissions and more economical fuel consumption. 
Associated development aimed at weight savings or even new drive 
trains (such as zero-emission-vehicles) will call for a plethora 
of materials innovations, e.g., selection of materials for 
lightweight components, fuel cells, energy storage devices, 
magnetic propulsion systems, as well as materials solutions in 
new combustion designs. 
  To a special extent even information and communication 
technology products depend on systems-capable high-performance 
materials. They range from semiconductor materials, chip housing 
materials (ceramics, polymers, gold) for integrated circuits via 
glass, liquid crystals, magnetic materials as systems components 
all the way up to key materials for networks, just to mention a 
few at this point. There is not questioning the special 
importance of micro-electronic and optoelectronic systems and 
their enormous broad-spectrum character. However, this is a 
fundamental issue for the future structural positioning of the 
FRG. Discussing and responding to it are beyond the scope of 
this study. 
  The medical engineering sector places high demands on the 
ability of different types of materials to be integrated into 
systems. For example, in this critical branch, in the case of 
implants, it is not the maximum properties of the individual 
materials that is required but optimum coordination, design and 
quality control of the different materials. 
  The fresh focusing and structuring of a future support 
design, as proposed in chart 5.3 and favored by many materials 
experts, basically constitutes a shifting of the axes towards an 
applied and systems oriented structure involving issues that 
transcend materials compared with the current MATFO program with 
its materials-related structure. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-133A>        Chart 5.3: Proposed basic thematic structure for a future materials and systems innovation support </FIG>



  The individual program sectors having an applied orientation 
in this context are chosen in such a way that there is no direct 
link to a branch (to avoid support for branches). Instead, 
broad-spectrum functions are covered as much as possible since 
their positive impacts are capable of encompassing a large 
number of branches and consequently are likely to increase 
competitiveness in general. In the various sectors, it is 
possible to cover the entire net product chain from basic 
materials up to components and systems, respectively. Compared 
with basic materials, the market and turnover potential for 
components that is often higher by a factor of 500 to 1,000 
would justify not only the thematic implementation of a future 
support program but also the allocation of appropriate funding 
for research. 
  Essentially, where it makes sense, there should be a 
possibility for competition among various materials in the 
various net product stages in order to realize optimum 
solutions. On the component and systems levels the synergistic 
effects of complementary materials should also be exploited. In 
the future, as a reflection of specific systems requirements, 
there must be a targeted advanced development of materials 
property profiles (see chart 5.4). It is also necessary -- and 
this is the unequivocal result of our research -- to create the 
prerequisite conditions for future (market) dissemination of 
materials and systems innovations and therefore prioritization 
of topics such as: 


    -  component quality and reliability 
  -  consistency in the qualities of specific materials, 
semi-finished products and components 
  -  lowering of materials and processing costs 
  -  advanced development of processing technologies. 
  The issue of which components and systems should ultimately 
be included in the design of the new program, in addition to 
mere materials development, has to be resolved on the 
decision-making level of program management. This will initially 
entail considerable need for coordination with other support 
programs or timely discussion of initiatives. The average 
requirement for a future materials and systems innovation 
program, however, decisively depends on what systems entailing 
what technological complexity will be integrated in such a 
program, with the spectrum ranging from small micro-electronic 
systems that have not yet been covered in the in microsystems 
engineering program, all the way up to complex systems like 
alternative drive train designs. 
  Besides the sectors having an applied orientation, other 
program sectors, albeit with less emphasis, should be projected 
in which it is possible to seize upon new fields of application 
and other materials-based fundamental topics. 
  The limit for official support is, for instance, as 
currently 
in the materials research program, to be found in basic research 
having an applied orientation. Chart 5.5 schematically lists 
this for each stage of net product using appropriate 
hatch-marking with the support program being the link between 
institutionalized basic research (universities, MPG and DFG 
support) and industrial, applied research. In principle, each of 
the described net product stages terminates in a mature product 
that simultaneously constitutes the "raw material" for the next 
stage. During the development time of each product, in general, 
the basic research themes decrease in favor of 
application-oriented research themes. Ultimately, direct 
research support should always keep in view the basic nature and 
applied-orientation of basic research since applied research 
that is purely product related is essentially a corporate 
responsibility. Such basic and/or applied orientation research 
themes could be pursued both as projects along the net product 
chain as well as within each of the individual net product 
stages. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-135A>   Chart 5.4: Selective examples of properties-oriented thematic foci for a future support </FIG>




<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-136A>          Chart 5.5 Schematic illustration of the support focus of a future support design </FIG>


<H5>  5.4 Program organization and support principles </H5>
  Any future support design should have its goal the 
establishment of a strategically focused program organization 
guaranteeing both an appropriate prioritizing of themes and 
(over the medium term) a comprehensive, systematic management 
and coordination of all FRG activities in the materials research 
sector. 
  Program organization should provide three levels for 
realizing normative, strategic, and operative management (see 
chart 5.6). 
  - Program management: 
  The BMFT should set up a program management with a majority 
of the members from the BMFT. To ensure coordination of 
strategic issues at the highest level members from other 
pertinent ministries, e.g., the BMVg and BMWi, should also be 
represented. The program management committee will be assisted 
by a high level group of advisors whose members will be experts 
from industry, associations, and non-industrial research. 
  The responsibilities of the program management should be: 


    -  strategic focusing of the entire program after the 
pattern of respective European, U.S., and Japanese support 
programs and establishment of the general conditions 
  -  establishment of specific program objectives, establishment 
and 
organization of program sectors, engendering and dismantling 
major individual projects and groups of directly associated 
projects 
  -  implementation of a portfolio management as an apparatus of 
strategic management providing a target profile of the program 
structure and implementing target/attainment comparisons on the 
basis of criteria that are provided, for example 
  - basic/applied orientation 
  - attractiveness/risk profiles 
  - branch/application foci and 
  - research fields and program sectors. 
%supra-jurisdictional coordination of various BMFT program 
activities in the materials technologies sector that should be 
institutionalized on the department and division chiefs level 
and initially should be used to coordinate the various support 
activities for increased efficiency of official support 
activities 
%over the medium to long term, transfer of the management of all 
support activities having relevance for materials under a single 
authority. 
  - Program control 
  A fulltime program manager should be responsible for program 
control. His staff will manage the individual program sectors. 
The program manager will report to the program management 
committee. 
  In this way, program control is the link between the 
decision-making level and the operative level where the actual 
project activity occurs. The essential responsibility of program 
control should be program implementation in conformity with the 
goals. This is a responsibility that has both a strategic and an 
operative character. Program control will be assisted by 
alternating experts from the materials technologies sector 
(program foci and fields of activity workshops). 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-138A>        Chart 5.6: Proposed basic table of organization for a future support design </FIG>

  Concrete responsibilities of program control should be: 


    -  establishment of fields of activity under the program 
foci 
  -  project selection reflecting the strategic objective 
  -  preparing a decision on approval of major projects or groups 
of 
projects by the program management committee 
  -  Obtaining expert advice for a technical and scientific 
assessment of project applications 
  -  control and coordination of projects using R&amp;D control 
resources 
  -  portfolio management in individual program sectors and across 
program sectors. 
  The actual project activity should be carried out in fields 
of activity under program foci. Based on the experiences of the 
current program, the basic principles of any modern project 
management should be established in all projects. This 
presupposes appropriate 


    -  goal-oriented project definition (objectives, strategic 
significance, competitive environment, time and cost planning) 
  -  structural organization of the project (organizational 
structuring of the project with project managers and those 
responsible for the activity packages) 
  -  organization of the project cycle (preliminary project 
survey, 
project survey, milestones system, release of resources at major 
milestones, conclusion of the project) and 
  -  project control (portfolio analysis, budget planning and 
monitoring). 
  To meet the objectives in the best way possible on the 
operative, that is, the project level, and to resolve the 
putative tense relationship between basic research and applied 
industrial development, the materials and systems innovation 
program should project three parallel types of projects for 
support: 


    -  type A projects: projects having a broad-spectrum 
character and an applied orientation 
  -  type B projects: basic-oriented support involving long term 
potential for great usefulness 
  -  type S projects: special projects having a high level of 
innovation. 
  Type A projects should be allocated nearly 70 percent of 
support funding; type B projects, in turn, should henceforth be 
provided with approximately 20 percent of support funding. 
Additionally, about 10 percent of the budget should be set aside 
for special projects that are only inadequately covered by type 
A and B projects, but over the long term facilitate interesting 
and unconventional developments. For all three types of 
projects, support activities and projects have to be quite 
differently focused (see charts 5.7 and 5.8). 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-140A>        Chart 5.7: Proposed budget allocation for a future support design </FIG>

  - Type A projects: projects having a broad-spectrum 
character 
and an applied orientation 
  The future support focus of the BMFT's materials and systems 
innovation program should aim at application-oriented projects 
having a highly synergistic and broad-spectrum character. 
Projects should mainly be supported that generate know-how of 
interest equally to a number of firms and research institutes 
but that can be realized in an R&amp;D combine cost effectively 
and 
entailing coordination advantages. The requirement for official 
support in each individual instance must be justified through 
externalities and coordination advantages with the intervention 
of the BMFT. 
  The initiative for basic type A projects should chiefly come 
from committed industrial firms for whom the project has great 
strategic importance but that see recognizable advantages to 
including other (private and government) partners. The amount of 
support should basically total 50 percent. Some single 
industrial partner, the one with the greatest strategic interest 
and the greatest competence, should assume project management. 
Basic type A projects should have as their objective a salable 
product in a period of at most a decade. Particular attention 
should be given to the complementarity and perceptibly limited 
activity and competence sectors of the participating partners. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-141A>        Chart 5.8: Proposed types of projects in a future support design </FIG>


  Groups of expert advisors for basic type A projects should 
include applied-orientation scientists having industrial 
background knowledge. The process for selecting, awarding and 
controlling projects should be strictly selective and based on 
established guidelines emphasizing primarily market strategy 
criteria. 
  Three types of projects should be distinguished among basic 
type A applied-orientation support projects. Different 
objectives are uppermost in each of them and these therefore 
require a different type of support. This entails the following 
types of projects: 
  A1: vertical projects 
  A2: horizontal broad-spectrum projects and 
  A3: SME projects. 
  Based on the results of the MATFO program assessment the 
future support design should manifest the following changes in 
emphasis: 
  1. a much greater emphasis on vertical applied projects 
leading to market-oriented products and simultaneously 
innovations in a number of net product stages 
  2. additional, albeit less heavily pushed, support for 
materials-related horizontal broad-spectrum projects and 
  3. explicit support for SME projects in such fields of 
activity and based on support principles that are appropriate to 
the innovation goals and requirements of medium-size firms (see 
chart 5.9). 
  - A1:vertical projects 
  Approximately 30 to 40 percent of support financing in the 
future materials and systems innovation program should be 
focused on vertical projects with an applied orientation. In now 
wise, however, should such focusing be confused with "near 
market" projects. Many developments in the materials engineering 
sector require simultaneous developments in a number of process 
and net product stages and thereby occasion high project costs, 
risks and lead times. Although such complex developments are 
application oriented and linked to quite specific final 
applications, they are still far from being "near market" or 
"marketable without problems."[.sup]23[/] [footnote - The 
BMFT's list of criteria for determining the need for support 
should be reworked in view of this too lopsided treatment of the 
"near market" terminology]. Support for such complex, vertical 
projects does indeed appear indispensable, but it should still 
be well grounded in each instance. 
  Participation in vertical projects should extend to 
materials 
suppliers, processors and final consumers. The decisive factor 
should be at what processing stage the critical development 
steps occur and how urgent the need for coordination is. 
Participation should not be extended too broadly (a maximum of 
five firms). One of the firms, preferably the consumer firm, 
should assume project management. 
  - A2: horizontal broad-spectrum projects 
  About 20 to 25 percent of the budget of the future materials 
and systems innovation program should be allocated to horizontal 
broad-spectrum projects in which quite specific materials and 
individual net product stages are foremost. Participants should 
comprise materials suppliers, application-oriented institutes, 
processors and materials specialists from consumer firms. At 
this point there should be an opening projected in the direction 
of possible international cooperation. Uppermost should be the 
joint quest for fresh know-how involving all participants 
equally but that each, separately, could not address because of 
financial, informational or specific standardization 
restrictions. Such horizontal projects also justify support for 
50 percent of the development cost. 
  Horizontal projects are not without problems in their 
coordination and call for a very skillful selection of 
participants. Project selection, oversight and control also 
merit comparatively higher outlay on the part of the program 
management. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-EST-10L-143A>        Chart 5.9: Proposed project types in the context of applied-oriented broad-spectrum </FIG>

  - SME projects 
  SME support was originally one of the objectives of the 
1985-1994 MATFO program. Project analyses, however, indicated 
that the participation of SMEs turned out to be only very 
limited, contrary to original expectations. This was certainly 
due to the design of the current program (basic orientation, 
combined projects, focusing on capital intensive materials 
developments). 
  Reorientation under the future 1995-2005 materials and 
systems innovation program, however, should provide for 
definitely greater participation by SMEs in an amount totaling 
15 percent of total support volume. This can only be 
accomplished by shifting the program's focus and furnishing 
support instruments that are also actually compatible with the 
innovations requirements and characteristics of medium-size 
enterprises. 
  SMEs are especially promising in the following sectors as 
target groups for any future materials and systems innovation 
program: 


    -  as suppliers of development and production activities 
at specified processing stages (e.g., processors of composite 
materials, surface and solidification processes) 
  -  as specialized suppliers for preliminary products, equipment 
and services 
  -  as innovative users of new materials in the kind of sectors 
that are typified by low numbers of pieces or by highly 
specialized niche markets. 
  Before adopting the new materials and systems innovation 
program therefore, a targeted screening should be undertaken as 
to which of those three types of SMEs in which special niches 
are to be considered as target groups in Germany for a 
SME-oriented partial program. Then the support apparatus should 
be appropriately adapted to their specific requirements. This 
also means, in particular, greater flexibility in the choice of 
appropriate support instruments. The apparatus of indirectly 
specific support as a complement to project support may also be 
considered in this context for a more intensive expansion of 
specific new categories of materials and processing technologies. 
  There should be a targeted screening of type A1 A2 projects 
as to which SME-appropriate activities (supplies, services, 
applications) could be supported through complementary SME 
support in the arena of larger combined projects. In this 
context, even innovative support concepts (support of 
technologically oriented corporate institutes, providing share 
capital, supporting corporate ventures, etc.) should be 
consciously kept in view. 
  - Type B projects: support for basic research 
  Approximately 20 percent of the program's budget should be 
allocated to basic research problems and exploratory research 
designed for the long term. In the materials research sector 
there are subjects and problems of a highly basic nature that 
are only inadequately covered by existing support institutions. 
The BMFT should also assume overall charge of those long term 
topics that are highly relevant for future development and 
industrial application of new materials. But it should 
deliberately use other support instruments and selection 
principles for this purpose. 
  Under long-term, basic type B projects, there should be 
support for the acquisition of basic know-how that may lead over 
a period of 10 to 20 years to effective applications in very 
many sectors of the German economy. The total amount of support 
for this should be as much as 100 percent. "Systems leadership" 
should, to the extent possible, reside with a top level 
scientist. Industry may take on a tutorial function and should 
be represented in the group of expert advisors. The award, 
oversight and control process should involve as little 
bureaucracy as possible. 
  Under basic type B basically-oriented projects, the 
appropriate institutional framework, from the outset, should not 
be defined too narrowly. Individual research centers and centers 
of competence should be support as well as combined projects. In 
the context of basically-oriented combined projects, a number of 
basic research institutions, with as many complementary fields 
of competence as possible, should be motivated to cooperate over 
longer time periods. Even corporate basic research sectors could 
be actively included in such projects. In organizing such basic 
projects unqualified attention should also be given to openness 
and innovative promise. This argues against too lopsided support 
for established groups and the perpetuation of programs in the 
same circles of research. Deliberate reconsideration should be 
given to new foundations by institutes and to ad hoc institutes. 
The selection and approval should be done by peer groups and top 
level scientists but not only by the same groups repeatedly in 
order to facilitate the inflow of new ideas from "hangers-on" 
and "cross-thinkers." Participating peer groups and scientists 
should also be sought outside purely national groups. 
  In addition to the direct support instrument, either for 
individual or combined projects, it appears to make sense to us, 
above all in the SME sector, to have selective application of 
indirectly specific activities for the establishment of 
corporate foundations or investments in relevant materials 
sectors (e.g., limited assumption of personnel costs and 
investment costs, providing share capital, etc.). But this 
should be more accurately examined in the context of a 
strategic, prior assessment as well as the impact of possibly 
necessary indirect measures such as tax relief, or the 
harmonization of laws and regulations hindering innovation. 
  - Type S projects: special projects having a high level of 
innovation 
  About 10 percent of the program's budget should be set aside 
for special projects having a high level of innovation. This 
should afford the possibility of supporting unconventional but 
long-term implementable developments. The spectrum of 
possibilities ranges from support for especially innovative 
individual projects to support for ad hoc institutes for top 
ranking scientists from research and industry to strategically 
important study groups. This expression of direct project 
support should be open to all groups of participants ad provide 
for both individual research and combined research. Amounts of 
support should total between 30 and 100 percent depending on the 
respective proximity to application. 
<H5>  5.5 Supplemental strategies and recommended action for other </H5>
institutions 
  Materials research and technology are still laboring under 
continued insufficient coordination of the decision-making and 
action-taking platforms due to its broad-spectrum character, the 
numerous functions and responsibilities that have to be tackled 
simultaneously and because of the many layers of unresolved 
effects. In the support policy sector there are a number of 
federal jurisdictions involved. The states of the FRG play a 
major role and increasingly even European programs are 
important. The effectiveness of any future materials support 
program quite decidedly depends on the coordination among such 
federal, state and EC levels. 
  To this effect, the success of more intense coordination 
definitely depends on whether any single institution (e.g., the 
BMFT) succeeds in acquiring control over finance and information 
flows and to what extent two or more institutions can be induced 
into sustained cooperation. In terms of these two questions, the 
following sectors of activities should be 
distinguished[.sup]24[/]. 


    -  Activities that the BMFT can engage in on its own in 
the context of its purview and government funding 
  -  activities that the BMFT has to conduct in association and in 
coordination with one or more other federal authorities 
  -  activities that call for cooperation between the federal 
government and the state governments and, lastly, 
  -  activities that require cooperation among the federal 
government, the EC and other supranational institutions on the 
European and international levels. 
  These four sorts of activities are arranged according to the 
degree of difficulty it takes for effective coordination to be 
able to be realized. The coordination of the kinds of activities 
that the BMFT is able to deal with on its own could be 
comparatively free of problems. In contrast, if not insoluble, 
the coordination between national and European activities can be 
particularly difficult especially if the strategies of different 
action groups cannot be mutually harmonized and if undefined 
limits to competencies persist. 
  In the implementation of a support strategy, the BMFT should 
first "set the tone" when it alone has "full control of the 
baton." But making a start in its own house is not always as 
easy as might be initially expected, considering intrinsic 
limits in the internal organization of fields and programs. The 
BMFT encompasses relevant materials research activities 
distributed among various departments and divisions. Any 
effective future materials and systems innovation program will 
require intensive networking among those responsible for a 
number of programs. These include, for instance, the current 
MATFO program, the surface and thin film engineering program, 
microsystems engineering and selective sectors of the 
information engineering program. Also to be included are 
officials from the departments that oversee, among other things, 
relevant materials research activities for basic research. A 
stab also has to be made at effective cooperation among the 
various participating project sponsors. Cooperation encompassing 
divisions and project sponsors should be supported through 
jointly supported projects and common study groups under the 
topic of "key industries for increasing international 
competitiveness." 
  Materials technology and its application are also heavily 
influenced by activities that call for a linkage or coordination 
of a number of federal authorities. 
  To better coordinate the various authorities we propose two 
measures: first, interministerial working groups should be 
created to jointly come up with a solution for specific, 
operationally defined issues (e.g., on the topic of recyclable 
materials) and support joint projects. The authorities should 
also be incorporated into the broad group of advisors for the 
future materials research program described in section 5.3. 
  Greater coordination between federal and state levels also 
appears to be of major importance for the future materials 
research program. Over the past decade there has occasionally 
been unparalleled technology-policy federalism in the FRG. The 
federal government should be striving for better coordination 
here by consciously being attentive to actions complementary to 
state strategies. In this regard attention should be given to 
the following division of labor and synergistic relationship: 


    -  under the states, development of universities, basic 
research and support for regional innovation strategies 
  -  on the federal level, nationally important technology support 
programs, support for strategically important basic research 
sectors and coordination between national and European research 
policy. 
  The BMFT and other federal authorities possess highly 
effective instruments for being able to better coordinate the 
various research sectors (for instance, via the DFG and BMFT 
financing of basic research). But there must first be a strategy 
for this on the national level. Whoever develops the strategy 
more rapidly and more compatibly with the requirements will 
assume a leadership role in shaping the program. At the moment, 
individual states are planning intensive activities in the 
materials research support sector. Under the umbrella of a 
future materials and systems innovation program, the competence 
and responsibility should reside much more with the federation. 
A higher level of materials research and technology is primarily 
a national responsibility that must be effectively supported by 
the states but that should not principally be determined by them. 
  In the future materials and systems innovation program too, 
special attention should focus on greater coordination between 
national and European support. In the upcoming decade European 
research and technology policy will increasingly assume greater 
significance and require increasingly greater competencies 
compared to national measures. Even the materials research 
sector, in fact, will be one of the important foci of European 
research and technology policy. Hence, any national support 
program will have to be increasingly more intensely coordinated 
with strategies and reserved activities on the European level. 
  Greater coordination with European programs, however, should 
in no wise entail subordination of national programs. On the 
contrary, European research and technology policy can only 
continue to be strengthened if it is supported by highly 
developed national R&amp;D policies and if each of the leading 
states acts as a source of impetus using national activities. 
Within Europe, the FRG is the leading nation in important 
materials engineering sectors. The sectors in which we currently 
occupy a leadership position should be emphasized in order to 
develop national strategies and emphases on the basis of them. 
  Over the long-term it will be useful for the competitiveness 
of European industry and the competency of European materials 
research for national sectors of expertise and a greater 
division of labor to emerge on the basis of categories of 
materials and applied foci. In any event, this will be more 
productive than a more "leveling" strategy that reduces the 
level of research to a European average and in each country the 
same internationally insignificant research groups and supplier 
structures are established. The latter reflects past European 
materials engineering wherein each country endeavored to support 
more or less the same categories of materials and applied foci. 
Europe's future, however, lies in a greater degree of 
specialization, wherein the individual countries focus on quite 
specific fields in which they can make an appropriate impact in 
a global context. 
  In the period between 1993-2000, an appropriate European 
division of labor in the materials engineering sector will 
emerge only through an evolutionary process that will be 
typified by numerous iterations. Still, a minimum amount of 
"rational design" and effective strategizing appears to be 
indispensable. Therefore materials engineering in Europe will 
also be decidedly determined by the extent to which the decision 
makers from any single country actively shape European policy 
and have a targeted impact on the resulting division of labor. 
  More and more resources in the future will be allocated via 
European programs and the European element will have an 
increasingly greater impact on the shaping of national policy. 
In the future, there will be ever more demand for a proactive 
behavior with high support for European programs but building on 
a well-defined national strategy. The BMFT and the national 
institutes (project sponsors, expert advisory groups, 
institutes) should deliberately claim overall management of 
important parts of the European materials research program. 
There is merit in recommending a decision-making sequence in 
which materials research strategy continues to be defined on the 
national level before the next strategy-making step is taken on 
the European level. 
  Greater coordination of national and European materials 
research programs also means, in particular, targeted management 
on the partial program and project levels. The most important 
European programs and initiatives in materials research are 
BRITE/EURAM II, COST and EUREKA. National strategies that will 
be elaborated in the course of coming months in accordance with 
the methodology recommended in the preceding chapters, will have 
to stipulate especially who will be active in which program with 
which objective and in which way each single program will be 
supported through supplementary national activities. In this 
context, attention should be given to a balanced relation 
between the complexity and subsidiary aspects whereby important 
national and European materials research programs are mutually 
reinforced. 
  In the future, in order to effectively realize the required 
coordination among European, national and regional policies too, 
it will be essential in the future to commission an agency with 
systems management. Such systems management may be awarded 
either for materials research as a whole or just for program 
foci. Whatsoever shape appropriate coordination will assume on 
the European level in the second half of the nineties, FRG 
institutions should prepare in a timely fashion to assume a 
major role therein. Possible future systems managers may be 
chosen both from groups of private firms as well as public 
institutions. However, only institutions in those countries in 
which firms provide sizable funding for R&amp;D and in which 
there 
exists a strategically focused national R&amp;D support policy, 
will 
play any decisive role. 
